WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.360
[Amit Varma]: The world has changed forever and we will spend the next few years haunted by regrets

00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:16.280
[Amit Varma]: and thoughts of what might have been. Maybe we will regret spending too little time with

00:00:16.280 --> 00:00:20.920
[Amit Varma]: loved ones. Maybe we will regret spending too much time with them. Maybe we will regret

00:00:20.920 --> 00:00:26.160
[Amit Varma]: taking good health and long life for granted and not doing all that we could have. We will

00:00:26.160 --> 00:00:31.520
[Amit Varma]: cross off items from our bucket list, sacrificing those dreams forever, such as those that involve

00:00:31.520 --> 00:00:38.200
[Amit Varma]: travel. And we will wonder why we didn't appreciate more the beauty of noses and lips as those

00:00:38.200 --> 00:00:43.160
[Amit Varma]: parts of the face hidden from view in public due to an evolving custom become erogenous

00:00:43.160 --> 00:00:48.600
[Amit Varma]: zones for the kids born today. And everyone who is making decisions of public policy will

00:00:48.600 --> 00:00:53.280
[Amit Varma]: have more than just personal regrets to contend with. They will also have to deal with the

00:00:53.280 --> 00:00:58.840
[Amit Varma]: decisions that they took today in this turbulent time of COVID-19 with all their costs, with

00:00:58.840 --> 00:01:03.840
[Amit Varma]: all their lives lost. This is true regardless of what that decision might be. Every single

00:01:03.840 --> 00:01:09.360
[Amit Varma]: decision, in fact, is a devil's alternative. Many of the costs will be seen. Many of the

00:01:09.360 --> 00:01:14.680
[Amit Varma]: benefits will be unseen. Please indulge me while I elaborate on this with the example

00:01:14.680 --> 00:01:19.720
[Amit Varma]: of whether to do a lockdown or not. In early March, a policymaker in India would have looked

00:01:19.720 --> 00:01:25.200
[Amit Varma]: at the trajectory of COVID-19 and other countries and been alarmed. It would seem that if the

00:01:25.200 --> 00:01:30.440
[Amit Varma]: pandemic took off in India, it would be worse than anywhere else. Our poor, many of them

00:01:30.440 --> 00:01:35.320
[Amit Varma]: trapped in congested cities would suffer the most. To add to which is the fact that Indians

00:01:35.320 --> 00:01:40.520
[Amit Varma]: have more comorbidities or other existing illnesses like diabetes, more than people

00:01:40.520 --> 00:01:45.200
[Amit Varma]: from other countries. Our healthcare services are far worse than countries in the developed

00:01:45.200 --> 00:01:50.520
[Amit Varma]: world like Italy, Spain, and the USA, which have since been overwhelmed. You cannot think

00:01:50.520 --> 00:01:56.080
[Amit Varma]: of herd immunity as a way out, as the UK briefly considered, because that would require around

00:01:56.080 --> 00:02:01.440
[Amit Varma]: 60% of the population to get the disease. And even at a conservative mortality estimate

00:02:01.440 --> 00:02:08.440
[Amit Varma]: of 0.5%, that would mean 40 lakh people dead. As a policymakers then, what are the options

00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:13.680
[Amit Varma]: you have? Sure, you can ramp up testing and tracing, but there isn't enough state capacity

00:02:13.680 --> 00:02:19.320
[Amit Varma]: for that at that moment. Your best tool seems to be the blunt tool of a lockdown. Social

00:02:19.320 --> 00:02:23.880
[Amit Varma]: distancing should at least flatten the curve, as the phrase goes, so things don't go out

00:02:23.880 --> 00:02:28.720
[Amit Varma]: of hand while you build the state capacity to deal with the outbreaks that will occur

00:02:28.720 --> 00:02:33.800
[Amit Varma]: later. The problem here is that this decision carries huge costs, and you cannot calculate

00:02:33.800 --> 00:02:38.400
[Amit Varma]: them. As we have seen, there will be enormous suffering among migrant labor who are stuck

00:02:38.400 --> 00:02:44.440
[Amit Varma]: in inhospitable cities, often without food and water. As the economy is suspended, businesses

00:02:44.440 --> 00:02:49.400
[Amit Varma]: across the country will shut down, jobs will be lost, livelihoods will be destroyed. We

00:02:49.400 --> 00:02:55.600
[Amit Varma]: know that for every 1% rise in GDP, 2 million people come out of poverty. So what is the

00:02:55.600 --> 00:03:01.280
[Amit Varma]: cost of dropping several points of GDP growth, even possibly going into recession? What is

00:03:01.280 --> 00:03:07.080
[Amit Varma]: the cost to the poor, especially? Not only can we not calculate the first order effects

00:03:07.080 --> 00:03:12.360
[Amit Varma]: of a lockdown now, but even second order effects down the line. And even if we estimate the

00:03:12.360 --> 00:03:17.000
[Amit Varma]: gains from a lockdown now, we cannot estimate second order gains down the line from the

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:22.080
[Amit Varma]: productivity that would come from the lives saved. So whether or not you choose to go

00:03:22.080 --> 00:03:27.240
[Amit Varma]: in for a lockdown, the costs of the action will be seen and the benefits will be unseen.

00:03:27.240 --> 00:03:33.040
[Amit Varma]: Whatever you do, future generations can easily blame you in hindsight for making a mistake.

00:03:33.040 --> 00:03:37.520
[Amit Varma]: Sitting at a distance, a commentator like me can appreciate the complexity of all this

00:03:37.520 --> 00:03:42.760
[Amit Varma]: and refrain from making a decision or recording an episode. But in the thick of things, there

00:03:42.760 --> 00:03:47.800
[Amit Varma]: are people who have to decide and who know that whatever they decide, many, many people

00:03:47.800 --> 00:04:07.640
[Amit Varma]: will die because of what they do. Welcome to the scene and the unseen. When COVID-19

00:04:07.640 --> 00:04:12.640
[Amit Varma]: broke, there was huge popular demand on Twitter for me to do an episode on it. I refrained

00:04:12.640 --> 00:04:18.440
[Amit Varma]: because I felt, as I feel, that we are in the fog of war, so to say, in terms of information.

00:04:18.440 --> 00:04:23.680
[Amit Varma]: We do not know enough about the virus. We don't understand so many policy implications.

00:04:23.680 --> 00:04:28.360
[Amit Varma]: And most experts I know are struggling to get a grip on things. I like to do timeless

00:04:28.360 --> 00:04:32.920
[Amit Varma]: episodes that can be heard 30 years from now, that are a definitive guide to the subject

00:04:32.920 --> 00:04:37.240
[Amit Varma]: at hand. When the two political crisis of last year broke, the abolition of Article

00:04:37.240 --> 00:04:42.840
[Amit Varma]: 370 in Kashmir and the introduction of CAA, I took my time and recorded what I think of

00:04:42.840 --> 00:04:47.360
[Amit Varma]: as fairly definitive episodes on them, which will stand the test of time. I cannot offer

00:04:47.360 --> 00:04:52.760
[Amit Varma]: you something like that for COVID-19 right now. But it is too important and too consequential

00:04:52.760 --> 00:04:57.640
[Amit Varma]: for me to ignore. And I do spend a lot of time thinking about it and worrying about

00:04:57.640 --> 00:05:02.880
[Amit Varma]: it. So I finally decided to put together this episode with my friend and frequent guest,

00:05:02.880 --> 00:05:07.680
[Amit Varma]: the economist Shruti Rajgopalan, who has thought deeply about this crisis and written many

00:05:07.680 --> 00:05:12.920
[Amit Varma]: thousands of words on it. We will not discuss the scientific and epidemiological aspects

00:05:12.920 --> 00:05:17.560
[Amit Varma]: of it in detail, because we are not experts of that and we are not fans of bringing it.

00:05:17.560 --> 00:05:22.320
[Amit Varma]: Instead, we will talk about the policy aspects, the economic aspects, and the philosophical

00:05:22.320 --> 00:05:27.720
[Amit Varma]: dilemma of figuring out what the right decision can possibly be. We are recording this in

00:05:27.720 --> 00:05:32.840
[Amit Varma]: the early hours of April 17th, India time. And I'd like to add three things here. One,

00:05:32.840 --> 00:05:37.640
[Amit Varma]: I had put in a spurt of recording for this podcast in February, and I've banked episodes

00:05:37.640 --> 00:05:43.200
[Amit Varma]: till the start of June. I'll continue releasing them after this one and we'll wait to do deeper

00:05:43.200 --> 00:05:48.400
[Amit Varma]: episodes on COVID-19 when the dust settles. Two, I'm recording this episode for the first

00:05:48.400 --> 00:05:54.360
[Amit Varma]: time from my home using the app Zencaster to connect remotely with Shruti. So apologies

00:05:54.360 --> 00:05:59.200
[Amit Varma]: in advance if there are issues with the sound. Three, there are many podcasters out there

00:05:59.200 --> 00:06:04.880
[Amit Varma]: who are doing a much better job of speaking about this pandemic than I can. This lockdown

00:06:04.880 --> 00:06:10.080
[Amit Varma]: is a great time to discover new podcasts. So please check those out. One that I liked

00:06:10.080 --> 00:06:16.560
[Amit Varma]: in particular is by the data journalist Rukmini S, who tweets at the handle of at Rukmini.

00:06:16.560 --> 00:06:21.520
[Amit Varma]: She's done a series of great episodes on COVID-19. They are linked from her Twitter page. The

00:06:21.520 --> 00:06:26.520
[Amit Varma]: Takshashila folks have done some very good episodes of All Things Policy, their daily

00:06:26.520 --> 00:06:31.760
[Amit Varma]: policy podcast. Do search for that and check that out. The formidable Neha Matthews is

00:06:31.760 --> 00:06:37.720
[Amit Varma]: also doing great work at Indian Express Podcast, specifically a podcast called Three Things.

00:06:37.720 --> 00:06:42.460
[Amit Varma]: Check them out as well. Among people whose Twitter streams I have been following and

00:06:42.460 --> 00:06:48.920
[Amit Varma]: have learned from a lot in the last few days are Balaji S Rinevasan, at Balaji S, Max Roser

00:06:48.920 --> 00:06:55.520
[Amit Varma]: at Max C Roser and Anoop Mallani at Anoop underscore Mallani. Before we begin our conversation

00:06:55.520 --> 00:07:00.000
[Amit Varma]: today though, let's take a quick commercial break.

