[Amit Varma]: support.

00:08:16.440 --> 00:08:21.200
[Amit Varma]: Shruti, welcome to The Scene and the Unseen.

00:08:21.200 --> 00:08:24.080
[Guest]: Hi, Amit. It is so nice to hear your voice.

00:08:24.080 --> 00:08:28.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And you know, while we had gone for the break, dear listener, Shruti told me why

00:08:28.560 --> 00:08:33.960
[Amit Varma]: was I so dead serious? And why could I not make Rajma jokes like I did during our episode

00:08:33.960 --> 00:08:39.080
[Amit Varma]: on the Bhopal gas tragedy? But these are not exactly very funny times. How has the lockdown

00:08:39.080 --> 00:08:40.080
[Guest]: been for you?

00:08:40.080 --> 00:08:45.600
[Guest]: I'm embarrassed to say it's been very comfortable. You know, I'm one of the privileged few who

00:08:45.600 --> 00:08:51.320
[Guest]: lives in a very low density and safe and clean environment. I live in Arlington, Virginia.

00:08:51.320 --> 00:08:57.200
[Guest]: And I live with my favorite human and my favorite dog. And it's been very calm. And you know,

00:08:57.200 --> 00:09:02.000
[Guest]: luckily, we are not struggling for essential supplies. Our fridge is stocked, you know,

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:08.240
[Guest]: the dog just keeps us in good cheer. We have excellent internet. So all work continues,

00:09:08.240 --> 00:09:13.680
[Guest]: you know, as usual. And I work with a really great group of people who've all adjusted

00:09:13.680 --> 00:09:19.440
[Guest]: to this new situation beautifully. So there's been no stress on that end. I guess the only

00:09:19.440 --> 00:09:26.400
[Guest]: stress is when one thinks about COVID and writes about COVID and what's going on globally.

00:09:26.400 --> 00:09:33.200
[Guest]: It's just, you know, the lack of good news. It's just relentless right now. Anytime you

00:09:33.200 --> 00:09:38.320
[Guest]: look up anything, it's more bad news. And you know, terrible things are happening across

00:09:38.320 --> 00:09:43.600
[Guest]: the world to people. So that has been the only hard part so far. What about you?

00:09:43.600 --> 00:09:49.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I have also been extremely lucky. Like, you know, you and I just live such privileged

00:09:49.600 --> 00:09:54.360
[Amit Varma]: lives that we have no business complaining about small things here and there. And you

00:09:54.360 --> 00:09:58.200
[Amit Varma]: know, that brings me to a thought that I shall probably come back to closer to the end of

00:09:58.200 --> 00:10:05.080
[Amit Varma]: the episode about how one of the trends that we are seeing is that a lot of the less fortunate

00:10:05.080 --> 00:10:10.760
[Amit Varma]: people, a lot of the poorer people are looking at this lockdown as a measure of the elites

00:10:10.760 --> 00:10:17.400
[Amit Varma]: to protect themselves, while the poor suffer the brunt of it. And it's very easily understandable,

00:10:17.400 --> 00:10:21.240
[Amit Varma]: of course, why they think like that. And, you know, and we'll probably come back to

00:10:21.240 --> 00:10:26.400
[Amit Varma]: that a little later in the episode. But what I sort of wanted to kind of start chatting

00:10:26.400 --> 00:10:32.760
[Amit Varma]: with you about was that one, you've been working incredibly hard through this crisis, you've

00:10:32.760 --> 00:10:37.080
[Amit Varma]: done a couple of papers, you've written at least three columns, your alignment column

00:10:37.080 --> 00:10:43.840
[Amit Varma]: about this whole crisis. And you were one of the very early clear voices calling for

00:10:43.840 --> 00:10:49.960
[Amit Varma]: a lockdown. Now, before we get to that specific decision, tell me a little bit about your

00:10:49.960 --> 00:10:54.960
[Amit Varma]: framework of thinking about public policy in times like this. Like, how do you think

00:10:54.960 --> 00:10:59.080
[Amit Varma]: about policy when you think about what we should do and what we should not do? It seems

00:10:59.080 --> 00:11:03.520
[Amit Varma]: to me that normally, you'd be looking at policy from a point of view of saying, these are

00:11:03.520 --> 00:11:07.200
[Amit Varma]: the costs, these are the benefits, these are the probable costs and the probable benefits

00:11:07.200 --> 00:11:11.760
[Amit Varma]: and you apply all the principles you know, from your knowledge in different fields. But

00:11:11.760 --> 00:11:17.760
[Amit Varma]: over here, there seems to be this great fog, where, you know, we can't imagine what the

00:11:17.760 --> 00:11:23.320
[Amit Varma]: cost could be of doing this or that. And, you know, we are sort of playing around with

00:11:23.320 --> 00:11:28.200
[Amit Varma]: so little information, and there is so much at stake. So how do you think about this at

00:11:28.200 --> 00:11:30.440
[Amit Varma]: a meta level?

00:11:30.440 --> 00:11:37.960
[Guest]: So honestly, I find it very difficult to put on a different hat from the one I feel like

00:11:37.960 --> 00:11:42.920
[Guest]: I always wear, which is the economist hat. So you know, many of your listeners know this

00:11:42.920 --> 00:11:50.160
[Guest]: from my previous visits on the show, but I'm an economist by training. I think about pretty

00:11:50.160 --> 00:11:57.520
[Guest]: much everything in life in my work as a set of trade-offs, because that's the core fundamental

00:11:57.520 --> 00:12:03.480
[Guest]: idea when we think like economists. So what are the trade-offs and opportunity costs which

00:12:03.480 --> 00:12:10.240
[Guest]: are hidden or visible in any particular situation? The other hat that I wear is someone who's

00:12:10.240 --> 00:12:15.080
[Guest]: familiar with Indian political economy. So most of my work has been in the area of public

00:12:15.080 --> 00:12:21.600
[Guest]: choice, law and economics, and constitutional economics. And that kind of training and looking

00:12:21.600 --> 00:12:26.640
[Guest]: at the Indian system over the last decade has given me insight into a whole range of

00:12:26.640 --> 00:12:31.760
[Guest]: issues. You know, you and I have done episodes on the Bhopal gas tragedy, we've talked about

00:12:31.760 --> 00:12:38.000
[Guest]: labor law, we've talked about, you know, urban and rural municipal governance. So we've talked

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:45.400
[Guest]: about property rights. So just given the kind of work that I do, I have had like, you know,

00:12:45.400 --> 00:12:49.760
[Guest]: just a good fortune of looking at different aspects of Indian political economy, all of

00:12:49.760 --> 00:12:54.760
[Guest]: it as an economist. And when COVID started coming about in different parts of the world,

00:12:54.760 --> 00:13:02.000
[Guest]: and one could see that this is a pandemic, which could be on a global scale, I used the

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:07.040
[Guest]: same set of tools that I have always used to study this problem. So you know, I'm not

00:13:07.040 --> 00:13:12.280
[Guest]: thinking about this from a medicine point of view, I have absolutely no training in

00:13:12.280 --> 00:13:20.160
[Guest]: medicine, epidemiology, you know, microbiology, virology, nothing. So please don't take anything

00:13:20.160 --> 00:13:27.120
[Guest]: Amit and I discuss on those margins, just even if we, we mentioned something, you know,

00:13:27.120 --> 00:13:32.640
[Guest]: it's not our core competence. So my framework was the same framework I have used on every

00:13:32.640 --> 00:13:38.360
[Guest]: single topic that you and I have discussed, simply because I have no other skill set other

00:13:38.360 --> 00:13:39.360
[Guest]: than being an economist.

00:13:39.360 --> 00:13:44.960
[Amit Varma]: And and that seems to me to be, you know, actually, a very important framework, because

00:13:44.960 --> 00:13:49.120
[Amit Varma]: that is, you know, especially the part of the framework where you talk about understanding

00:13:49.120 --> 00:13:55.960
[Amit Varma]: the political economy in India, which seems critical, because when we talk about India,

00:13:55.960 --> 00:14:02.560
[Amit Varma]: in particular, you're going to a have a decision taken, which will have elements of both public

00:14:02.560 --> 00:14:09.240
[Amit Varma]: policy and politics, where you will have people who have to make decisions and consider not

00:14:09.240 --> 00:14:15.320
[Amit Varma]: just you know, the conflicting views of different experts from different sides, but also what

00:14:15.320 --> 00:14:20.280
[Amit Varma]: is politically feasible, what they can get away with, at some points, you know, as in

00:14:20.280 --> 00:14:25.040
[Amit Varma]: the case of extending the lockdown, there can be an element of covering your ass, and

00:14:25.040 --> 00:14:28.760
[Amit Varma]: so on and so forth, we can discuss sort of the political considerations that go into

00:14:28.760 --> 00:14:34.120
[Amit Varma]: that later. But, you know, you'd written an early column by early, I mean, it's recent,

00:14:34.120 --> 00:14:41.560
[Amit Varma]: but it seems early on March 16, where in mint, where you recommended very strongly that India

00:14:41.560 --> 00:14:46.400
[Amit Varma]: go for a lockdown. And I'll quote from that piece, you wrote, quote, according to World

00:14:46.400 --> 00:14:52.640
[Amit Varma]: Bank data, 2017. India has eight doctors for every 10,000 Indians, compared to at least

00:14:52.640 --> 00:14:58.400
[Amit Varma]: 41 doctors for 10,000 Italians. If India is three weeks behind Italy on the trend, and

00:14:58.400 --> 00:15:02.520
[Amit Varma]: you meant the trend of the pandemic, if India is three weeks behind Italy on the trend,

00:15:02.520 --> 00:15:06.960
[Amit Varma]: and if the country does not take drastic containment measures, given a weak healthcare setup, we

00:15:06.960 --> 00:15:12.840
[Amit Varma]: will register much higher fatality rates, especially among the poor. So stop quote,

00:15:12.840 --> 00:15:18.920
[Amit Varma]: and I of course, agree with you on this. And can you elaborate a little bit on why you

00:15:18.920 --> 00:15:23.240
[Amit Varma]: were so you know, even long before Modi himself came to the conclusion you were recommending

00:15:23.240 --> 00:15:28.760
[Amit Varma]: long before this column, in fact, that we have to do a lockdown? Why? So one of the

00:15:28.760 --> 00:15:33.520
[Guest]: things that happens, I have the good fortune of working at the Mercatus Center, which thought

00:15:33.520 --> 00:15:39.840
[Guest]: about COVID very deeply and carefully. You know, on a daily basis, I have the good fortune

00:15:39.840 --> 00:15:45.320
[Guest]: of reading and thinking and talking through to with people like Tyler Cowen, and Alex

00:15:45.320 --> 00:15:50.400
[Guest]: Dabrock, who write Marginal Revolution, they were way ahead of anyone else on the curve

00:15:50.400 --> 00:15:55.200
[Guest]: of COVID because they saw what's happening in China. And that kind of got me started

00:15:55.200 --> 00:16:00.920
[Guest]: because India has numbers which are very similar to China, right? So that's what really got

00:16:00.920 --> 00:16:07.680
[Guest]: me started. So let me explain the the trade off and why I was so vehemently in favor of

00:16:07.680 --> 00:16:13.560
[Guest]: a shutdown. When I saw what was happening in Italy, and about 1213 years ago, I have

00:16:13.560 --> 00:16:18.560
[Guest]: the good fortune of living in Italy for a semester. So I reached out to my Italian friends,

00:16:18.560 --> 00:16:24.120
[Guest]: I saw that almost every single one of them has lost someone in the family. The weekend,

00:16:24.120 --> 00:16:27.800
[Guest]: you know, I think of 10th March, when I was working on this column, or I was thinking

00:16:27.800 --> 00:16:34.680
[Guest]: about the column in Bergamo, the paper had 10 pages of obituaries. And that just kind

00:16:34.680 --> 00:16:39.980
[Guest]: of shook me what was happening in Italy. So I started thinking through what would happen

00:16:39.980 --> 00:16:46.920
[Guest]: if this happened in India, and I started looking at trends. Now, one thing where economists

00:16:46.920 --> 00:16:53.040
[Guest]: are a little bit lucky is we really think about exponential functions well past ninth

00:16:53.040 --> 00:16:58.480
[Guest]: or 10th standard, right? Most people in other jobs, they haven't looked at an exponential

00:16:58.480 --> 00:17:03.680
[Guest]: function after, after their 10th standard board exams. And we are continuously looking

00:17:03.680 --> 00:17:09.140
[Guest]: at growth rates, we're looking at compounding, we're looking at federal rates. So we are

00:17:09.140 --> 00:17:15.000
[Guest]: in the habit of thinking about exponential rates and how compounding works, that if something

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:20.680
[Guest]: is doubling every seven days, you're not going to think of it as large numbers right now.

00:17:20.680 --> 00:17:25.680
[Guest]: But five weeks from now, you're going to be in 10s of 1000s. Right? So what was happening

00:17:25.680 --> 00:17:30.660
[Guest]: in Italy, when I started looking at the trend lines, India was just, you know, a few weeks

00:17:30.660 --> 00:17:36.480
[Guest]: behind Italy. And when I saw what was happening in Italy, I was just shaken to the core. At

00:17:36.480 --> 00:17:42.320
[Guest]: that time, Italy was also struggling with its hospital system. And I said, Okay, what

00:17:42.320 --> 00:17:46.760
[Guest]: does the Indian healthcare system look like? I haven't lived in India for the last 12-13

00:17:46.760 --> 00:17:52.640
[Guest]: years. So I don't know the changes. My experience from my childhood is that government hospitals

00:17:52.640 --> 00:18:00.440
[Guest]: are extremely overcrowded. And all the private small dispensaries and clinics, some of them

00:18:00.440 --> 00:18:05.760
[Guest]: serve the poor through charitable trusts, and you know, just people's goodwill. And

00:18:05.760 --> 00:18:10.300
[Guest]: you know, the nonprofit sector, the really functional part of the Indian healthcare sector

00:18:10.300 --> 00:18:14.680
[Guest]: is the private healthcare sector, which tends to be quite expensive. And I was like, let

00:18:14.680 --> 00:18:19.680
[Guest]: me just get some numbers and start thinking about what this situation looks like. And

00:18:19.680 --> 00:18:25.200
[Guest]: that is where my panic really began. And it became very clear to me where I am on the

00:18:25.200 --> 00:18:32.160
[Guest]: trade off. So let me explain the trade off. During a pandemic, and of the kind, you know,

00:18:32.160 --> 00:18:39.760
[Guest]: of the COVID kind, where it's highly infectious, and people can be asymptomatic, and they can

00:18:39.760 --> 00:18:44.840
[Guest]: be carriers without knowing that they're carriers. Sometimes it takes 10 to 14 days for the symptoms

00:18:44.840 --> 00:18:49.220
[Guest]: to manifest. So if they've attended an event, or they've shaken someone's hand, it's perfectly

00:18:49.220 --> 00:18:54.040
[Guest]: possible that that person was not sick, and no precautions were required. But you realize

00:18:54.040 --> 00:19:00.720
[Guest]: two weeks later that they were, in fact sick, or just hadn't, you know, developed the symptoms.

00:19:00.720 --> 00:19:04.840
[Guest]: And you have been infected, and therefore you have interacted with 20 or 30 other people,

00:19:04.840 --> 00:19:09.000
[Guest]: and you could have infected them. So, you know, COVID is a particular kind of virus,

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:13.760
[Guest]: which is a little bit hidden or unseen, as you would like to say. So the nature of this

00:19:13.760 --> 00:19:18.920
[Guest]: virus means that it can spread quite quickly without people knowing. And that's exactly

00:19:18.920 --> 00:19:24.480
[Guest]: what happened in other countries. Now, when something spreads very quickly, there is no

00:19:24.480 --> 00:19:29.160
[Guest]: healthcare system in the world, no matter how developed a country, that provides one

00:19:29.160 --> 00:19:35.080
[Guest]: hospital bed for every citizen. It doesn't exist. The reason it doesn't exist is it's

00:19:35.080 --> 00:19:43.400
[Guest]: simply too costly. And in extremely rare circumstances, once in a century, once in a couple of centuries,

00:19:43.400 --> 00:19:47.560
[Guest]: you hit a situation where everyone is sick at the same time, either because of a natural

00:19:47.560 --> 00:19:52.900
[Guest]: disaster or war or pandemic. So for the rest of the time, it would be a huge opportunity

00:19:52.900 --> 00:19:59.000
[Guest]: cost on the system to have one bed per individual. So no country, including the Scandinavian

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:06.440
[Guest]: countries or the United States, nobody has hit that measure. So every country estimates

00:20:06.440 --> 00:20:12.040
[Guest]: some kind of healthcare capacity and says, this is how many hospital beds we have, this

00:20:12.040 --> 00:20:17.840
[Guest]: is how many doctors we have, this is how many ventilators we have. In most developed countries,

00:20:17.840 --> 00:20:22.560
[Guest]: this is a function of demand and supply. Demand and supply in these instances depends on how

00:20:22.560 --> 00:20:28.440
[Guest]: rich the people in that particular country are, what kind of healthcare system they have,

00:20:28.440 --> 00:20:33.760
[Guest]: do they have willingness to pay for it? If the demographics are tilted towards slightly

00:20:33.760 --> 00:20:40.440
[Guest]: older people, then you tend to have more ventilators and intensive care units, which sort of support

00:20:40.440 --> 00:20:46.720
[Guest]: the demand or the healthcare requirements of those people. So this varies across countries.

00:20:46.720 --> 00:20:53.800
[Guest]: Now in India, we have realized now that our healthcare system is extremely weak. So we

00:20:53.800 --> 00:21:00.640
[Guest]: have one of the fewest hospital beds amongst BRICS countries and most emerging economies.

00:21:00.640 --> 00:21:09.000
[Guest]: You pointed out the figure on doctors, right? So India has only about 86 doctors per 100,000

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:16.480
[Guest]: people. The global average is 150 doctors per 100,000 people. South Africa has 91. Nigeria

00:21:16.480 --> 00:21:23.160
[Guest]: is way worse than India. It has only 39 or 40 doctors per 100,000 people. So different

00:21:23.160 --> 00:21:30.020
[Guest]: healthcare systems are in different points on capacity, right? Same thing with ventilators.

00:21:30.020 --> 00:21:37.600
[Guest]: The United States has 172,000 ventilators and the ability to scale it up very quickly

00:21:37.600 --> 00:21:45.800
[Guest]: because they specialize in building ventilators. India has only about 40 to 50,000 ventilators

00:21:45.800 --> 00:21:49.960
[Guest]: and we import a lot of the ventilators and ventilator parts. So it's not easy for us

00:21:49.960 --> 00:21:55.040
[Guest]: to scale that number quickly. So I started digging into all these different things and

00:21:55.040 --> 00:22:01.120
[Guest]: looking at what can our healthcare capacity sustain? Because if everyone gets sick at

00:22:01.120 --> 00:22:05.840
[Guest]: the same time, which is likely to happen, or a large population gets sick at the same

00:22:05.840 --> 00:22:12.560
[Guest]: time through COVID, which is likely to happen, what will happen to our hospital system?

00:22:12.560 --> 00:22:18.960
[Guest]: As I told you, what I found was extremely frightening. So we have very few hospital

00:22:18.960 --> 00:22:24.520
[Guest]: beds, but even the hospital beds that we have, the big problem with it is that most of them

00:22:24.520 --> 00:22:31.560
[Guest]: are taken, right? Our intensive care units are operating at almost 100% capacity at the

00:22:31.560 --> 00:22:37.080
[Guest]: moment because intensive care units are extremely expensive and most of them are in the private

00:22:37.080 --> 00:22:43.240
[Guest]: sector and no private hospital finds it in its interest to just have an empty bed in

00:22:43.240 --> 00:22:49.360
[Guest]: intensive care. It's very, very costly, right? And there is fairly high demand. So we are

00:22:49.360 --> 00:22:56.560
[Guest]: operating at very, very close to full capacity for intensive care units. We are operating,

00:22:56.560 --> 00:23:00.520
[Guest]: when I called a few government hospitals and I asked them, what is their capacity right

00:23:00.520 --> 00:23:06.000
[Guest]: now of available beds? They said, they're working at 120% capacity in government hospitals.

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:09.680
[Guest]: And I said, how is that possible? And they said, oh, we don't have beds. People bring

00:23:09.680 --> 00:23:14.240
[Guest]: their own gaddahs and sleeping bags. They just come in for treatment. They sleep in

00:23:14.240 --> 00:23:21.520
[Guest]: the corridor. AIMS in New Delhi is famous for having a whole number of cancer patients

00:23:21.520 --> 00:23:26.400
[Guest]: who sleep under the flyover outside and just come in for treatment during the day. So this

00:23:26.400 --> 00:23:30.840
[Guest]: is a system where the healthcare facility is operating at above 100% of the number of

00:23:30.840 --> 00:23:34.840
[Guest]: beds they have because they need to treat a lot of people. They just don't have enough

00:23:34.840 --> 00:23:41.200
[Guest]: beds, but they can't turn people away. So India's capacity was very low, which means

00:23:41.200 --> 00:23:47.120
[Guest]: India desperately needs to flatten the curve. And what we mean by flattening the curve is

00:23:47.120 --> 00:23:52.320
[Guest]: that we need to create a circumstance where everybody cannot get the infection at the

00:23:52.320 --> 00:23:58.560
[Guest]: same time, right? So right now we don't have a vaccine for this. Different people have

00:23:58.560 --> 00:24:03.640
[Guest]: started formulating a treatment protocol, but we don't have a vaccination. So in the

00:24:03.640 --> 00:24:10.960
[Guest]: world without a vaccine, you need to close things down or social distance in a way that

00:24:10.960 --> 00:24:17.000
[Guest]: a few people get sick at a time and we spread that out so that the hospital capacity is

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:22.120
[Guest]: not overwhelmed and doesn't collapse altogether. And this is not just true of India. It is

00:24:22.120 --> 00:24:27.520
[Guest]: true of Italy. It is true of Spain. It is true of the United States. It's true of the

00:24:27.520 --> 00:24:33.040
[Guest]: UK. So across the world, no matter how rich or poor you have, as I mentioned, there is

00:24:33.040 --> 00:24:39.200
[Guest]: no healthcare system that has one bed and one doctor per citizen, which means we need

00:24:39.200 --> 00:24:46.240
[Guest]: to find some way of flattening the curve. Now, here is the trade off, right? The better

00:24:46.240 --> 00:24:51.320
[Guest]: your healthcare system or the greater the capacity of your healthcare system, the less

00:24:51.320 --> 00:24:56.960
[Guest]: you need to flatten the curve, right? The more it can accommodate, such as Germany.

00:24:56.960 --> 00:25:01.760
[Guest]: The worse your healthcare system, the poorer the capacity of the healthcare system, the

00:25:01.760 --> 00:25:06.160
[Guest]: more you need to flatten the curve, which means you need to go towards more and more

00:25:06.160 --> 00:25:13.280
[Guest]: severe or stringent lockdown measures. It just so happens that poorer countries have

00:25:13.280 --> 00:25:20.360
[Guest]: worse healthcare systems, generally speaking, which means poorer countries, developing countries

00:25:20.360 --> 00:25:25.720
[Guest]: will see the worst, most stringent lockdowns in this particular scenario. Otherwise they

00:25:25.720 --> 00:25:31.220
[Guest]: will face huge outbreaks and local transmission and community transmission.

00:25:31.220 --> 00:25:37.080
[Guest]: So India was very wise to recognize that our healthcare system is extremely weak and cannot

00:25:37.080 --> 00:25:42.000
[Guest]: accommodate this. So we need the most stringent version of the lockdown, which is what I was

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:50.920
[Guest]: also advocating. Now, the trouble with that is poorer countries also cannot easily soften

00:25:50.920 --> 00:25:56.300
[Guest]: or mitigate the problems that come with the lockdown. The lockdown means pretty much closing

00:25:56.300 --> 00:26:02.840
[Guest]: down all economic activity. Economic activity is what keeps people's homes running, what

00:26:02.840 --> 00:26:07.400
[Guest]: keeps the lights on, what puts food on the plate. And the poorer the country is, the

00:26:07.400 --> 00:26:12.440
[Guest]: more stringent the lockdown measures, which means the more poor people suffer.

00:26:12.440 --> 00:26:18.120
[Guest]: So the column that you read out on March 16th, all the stuff I had been tweeting just before

00:26:18.120 --> 00:26:24.000
[Guest]: and after that, and also the columns and papers I have written successively after, in every

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:31.400
[Guest]: single one of them, I've categorically mentioned that the lockdown needs to be combined with

00:26:31.400 --> 00:26:38.600
[Guest]: some kind of basic income or like direct cash transfer, right? Without that, the number

00:26:38.600 --> 00:26:45.600
[Guest]: of poor people who will die in India of starvation is incredibly high. So we are in a very tough

00:26:45.600 --> 00:26:51.080
[Guest]: situation right now. If we don't lock down, sorry, I just want to go back to one small

00:26:51.080 --> 00:26:54.760
[Guest]: point you said, we'll get to this later in the episode, but I think it's pertinent to

00:26:54.760 --> 00:26:59.240
[Guest]: mention it here. You said that a lot of poor people think that the lockdown is to keep

00:26:59.240 --> 00:27:04.440
[Guest]: the rich people safe, right? The elites safe while they watch Netflix, the poor people

00:27:04.440 --> 00:27:11.600
[Guest]: suffer. That was not the way I thought about it. The rich people, I'm afraid, will capture

00:27:11.600 --> 00:27:18.240
[Guest]: all the private hospital capacity, which will respond very quickly to money flowing in.

00:27:18.240 --> 00:27:22.320
[Guest]: So if there are lots of people who are demanding hospital beds, private hospitals will try

00:27:22.320 --> 00:27:28.400
[Guest]: and quickly increase capacity to deal with the increased demand. Government hospitals

00:27:28.400 --> 00:27:34.220
[Guest]: treat the poorest people and are doing it almost for free or very, very close to free.

00:27:34.220 --> 00:27:38.480
[Guest]: These are the places which are already overcrowded. And according to me, the poor people are the

00:27:38.480 --> 00:27:45.240
[Guest]: ones who would have been left without healthcare. So the lockdown, I believe, contrary to popular

00:27:45.240 --> 00:27:52.320
[Guest]: opinion actually protects the poor from the worst circumstances. Second, the poor in India

00:27:52.320 --> 00:27:58.400
[Guest]: have worse comorbidities because there is a greater amount of malnourishment. They have

00:27:58.400 --> 00:28:04.080
[Guest]: lesser access to clean air and clean water than the elites. And these three things put

00:28:04.080 --> 00:28:10.600
[Guest]: together place them at higher risk if they get infected by COVID. And that's another

00:28:10.600 --> 00:28:17.080
[Guest]: reason why we really need to think about this for a majority of the country, which has not

00:28:17.080 --> 00:28:23.560
[Guest]: got great resources or great healthcare. And they are the ones who will be protected by

00:28:23.560 --> 00:28:29.600
[Guest]: a sensibly executed lockdown. Now, of course, we did not have a well-executed lockdown.

00:28:29.600 --> 00:28:36.600
[Guest]: That's a whole different problem. But the original logic for me, sort of really putting

00:28:36.600 --> 00:28:42.080
[Guest]: out a lot of statements in favour of shutting down the Mumbai locals or in favour of shutting

00:28:42.080 --> 00:28:48.160
[Guest]: down a lot of economic activity and trying to flatten the curve was because I saw the

00:28:48.160 --> 00:28:54.720
[Guest]: other half of the equation, which is our healthcare capacity. And it is abysmal to non-existent,

00:28:54.720 --> 00:28:56.560
[Guest]: especially in the government sector.

00:28:56.560 --> 00:29:01.760
[Amit Varma]: Right. So, you know, before I get to my next question, a couple of related thoughts. One,

00:29:01.760 --> 00:29:08.240
[Amit Varma]: I want to underline for my listeners how extraordinary this virus is, the specific coronavirus is,

00:29:08.240 --> 00:29:13.520
[Amit Varma]: SARS-CoV-2, which is in the sense, it's practically the optimal virus if you want to cause damage.

00:29:13.520 --> 00:29:18.480
[Amit Varma]: If you look at viruses of the past, like Ebola, for example, Ebola had a far higher mortality

00:29:18.480 --> 00:29:23.320
[Amit Varma]: rate, I think almost half the people who got it died. But the point is that you immediately

00:29:23.320 --> 00:29:27.880
[Amit Varma]: became symptomatic, that is, you developed symptoms immediately, which immobilized you,

00:29:27.880 --> 00:29:32.920
[Amit Varma]: and you weren't able to travel around much to pass the virus on, and people would know

00:29:32.920 --> 00:29:38.320
[Amit Varma]: to avoid you because the symptoms would be so obvious. What is remarkable about this

00:29:38.320 --> 00:29:44.240
[Amit Varma]: specific coronavirus is that one, it takes a long time before carriers show symptoms

00:29:44.240 --> 00:29:48.400
[Amit Varma]: and sometimes they do not show symptoms at all. So they feel they are perfectly normal,

00:29:48.400 --> 00:29:52.760
[Amit Varma]: they're going around interacting with people, and they are passing the virus on. And at

00:29:52.760 --> 00:29:57.880
[Amit Varma]: the same time, while we don't know the specific mortality rate yet, that's something we'll

00:29:57.880 --> 00:30:03.240
[Amit Varma]: know only over a much longer period of time. The fact is that it is still high enough to

00:30:03.240 --> 00:30:08.320
[Amit Varma]: cause a huge amount of damage. So you have a very high chance of infectiousness of this

00:30:08.320 --> 00:30:14.000
[Amit Varma]: being passed around, combined with a mortality that is high enough to paralyze healthcare

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:18.760
[Amit Varma]: systems once things get out of hand. So it is practically the optimal virus. And here

00:30:18.760 --> 00:30:24.200
[Amit Varma]: in India, we actually had a chance to see this play out first in China, and then in

00:30:24.200 --> 00:30:28.440
[Amit Varma]: Italy, which is a first world country with, you know, developed healthcare systems. And

00:30:28.440 --> 00:30:32.800
[Amit Varma]: we saw how things batter. My second observation would be that as far as affecting the poor

00:30:32.800 --> 00:30:37.560
[Amit Varma]: is concerned, I agree with that. And I think both of us would agree that I mean, my guiding

00:30:37.560 --> 00:30:41.880
[Amit Varma]: principle when I think of public policy is Mahatma Gandhi's guiding principle, which

00:30:41.880 --> 00:30:47.360
[Amit Varma]: is a question he always asked himself is how will this affect the poor? That's what I care

00:30:47.360 --> 00:30:51.560
[Amit Varma]: about. If the answer to that is negative, I don't care what else the policy does. In

00:30:51.560 --> 00:30:58.280
[Amit Varma]: India, our imperative is to remove poverty, which you know, we have, there's been a failure

00:30:58.280 --> 00:31:04.520
[Amit Varma]: over decades. And there's also been some limited success since liberalization. But by and large,

00:31:04.520 --> 00:31:08.320
[Amit Varma]: that's still a moral imperative. We haven't paid enough enough attention to so I agree

00:31:08.320 --> 00:31:15.000
[Amit Varma]: with that. Now, now the dilemma here is that, look, when we think about a policy, we don't,

00:31:15.000 --> 00:31:20.360
[Amit Varma]: we can't only think of how the policy would work in theory, we have to think about how

00:31:20.360 --> 00:31:26.520
[Amit Varma]: it would work in practice. So the paradox here is that on the one hand, you know, people

00:31:26.520 --> 00:31:31.920
[Amit Varma]: like you and me are proposing a lockdown because state capacity in India has failed to the

00:31:31.920 --> 00:31:37.000
[Amit Varma]: extent that our healthcare systems are so poor. And we know that there will be carnage,

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:41.960
[Amit Varma]: especially among the poor people of India, if the pandemic really takes off here. So

00:31:41.960 --> 00:31:46.360
[Amit Varma]: there appears to be no option but a lockdown. That's the theory of it. Now the practice

00:31:46.360 --> 00:31:50.760
[Amit Varma]: of it, which also you've recognized, and you've commented on that right from the start, but

00:31:50.760 --> 00:31:55.080
[Amit Varma]: it's part of the paradox. The practice is that because of that state capacity, it is

00:31:55.080 --> 00:32:02.740
[Amit Varma]: also going to have enormous costs upon the poor. And by that, I don't just mean state

00:32:02.740 --> 00:32:07.860
[Amit Varma]: capacity in terms of the manpower of the state or what the state can do, and so on. But also

00:32:07.860 --> 00:32:14.280
[Amit Varma]: in terms of the approach and expertise, for example, your first piece asking for a lockdown

00:32:14.280 --> 00:32:19.120
[Amit Varma]: on March 16, you know, illustrated exponential growth with a chessboard where you place a

00:32:19.120 --> 00:32:22.400
[Amit Varma]: grain of rice on the first square and two on the second and you keep doubling and so

00:32:22.400 --> 00:32:27.200
[Amit Varma]: on. And then on March 30, you wrote another piece that I'm going to quote from which also

00:32:27.200 --> 00:32:32.280
[Amit Varma]: circles back to a chessboard. And in this you wrote, quote, in an earlier column, I

00:32:32.280 --> 00:32:36.960
[Amit Varma]: had compared various attempts at social and economic engineering with the exertions of

00:32:36.960 --> 00:32:42.520
[Amit Varma]: Adam Smith's man of system, who, quote, seems to imagine that he can arrange the different

00:32:42.520 --> 00:32:47.600
[Amit Varma]: members of a great society with as much ease as a hand arranges the different pieces upon

00:32:47.600 --> 00:32:53.880
[Amit Varma]: a chessboard. Stop quote twice. And, you know, and this sort of engineering mindset of designing

00:32:53.880 --> 00:33:00.480
[Amit Varma]: society is, you know, something that is endemic in India that has caused much distress in

00:33:00.480 --> 00:33:07.520
[Amit Varma]: say, earlier cases like demonetization, to just take a recent example. And so how do

00:33:07.520 --> 00:33:12.480
[Amit Varma]: you account for that, where it seems evident to you that only social distancing can save

00:33:12.480 --> 00:33:16.000
[Amit Varma]: us, we have to have a lockdown. But at the same time, you just know that the cost will

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:22.680
[Amit Varma]: be so incredibly high. And if you are to attempt, say, a sort of a utilitarian kind of calculation

00:33:22.680 --> 00:33:28.120
[Amit Varma]: here, you can only attempt utilitarian calculations where you have enough knowledge and here everything

00:33:28.120 --> 00:33:34.440
[Amit Varma]: is in this fog where the cost can be absolutely humongous. Did any of it take you by surprise

00:33:34.440 --> 00:33:38.640
[Amit Varma]: what happened all the things that went wrong after a lockdown? And how does one think of

00:33:38.640 --> 00:33:39.640
[Guest]: this?

00:33:39.640 --> 00:33:44.680
[Guest]: Okay, so I'm going to answer you, you've, you've posed like a really big problem. So

00:33:44.680 --> 00:33:50.360
[Guest]: I'm going to take a stab at it in two, three different parts. So the big conundrum we have

00:33:50.360 --> 00:33:57.480
[Guest]: right now is, as you know, I'm a public choice trained economist. And one of the key learnings

00:33:57.480 --> 00:34:02.120
[Guest]: of public choice is we don't just think of market failure, we also think of government

00:34:02.120 --> 00:34:10.200
[Guest]: failure, right? And this COVID-19 pandemic has brought us to our knees on both market

00:34:10.200 --> 00:34:15.480
[Guest]: failure and government failure, right? There is no question there's a market failure problem

00:34:15.480 --> 00:34:20.240
[Guest]: in the sense that there is a huge externality that private individuals can pose on other

00:34:20.240 --> 00:34:26.160
[Guest]: private individuals deliberately or inadvertently because of the characteristics of the virus,

00:34:26.160 --> 00:34:33.440
[Guest]: as you mentioned. And there is no easy market-based decentralized solution to the problem, right?

00:34:33.440 --> 00:34:37.660
[Guest]: It's in everyone's interest to be out and about, especially if they're asymptomatic.

00:34:37.660 --> 00:34:42.360
[Guest]: But that also means that they can spread the virus much more quickly and affect the people

00:34:42.360 --> 00:34:47.200
[Guest]: who are in high risk groups, who are really going to lose their lives because of it. So

00:34:47.200 --> 00:34:53.000
[Guest]: we need some kind of government intervention to, you know, regulate or impose social distancing,

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:58.000
[Guest]: the most stringent version of it being a lockdown. But the flip side to that is while there is

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:05.480
[Guest]: market failure, there is also government failure, right? And weaker states, developing countries,

00:35:05.480 --> 00:35:12.100
[Guest]: poorer states tend to be rife with government failure problems. America has had such a high

00:35:12.100 --> 00:35:16.480
[Guest]: degree of government failure while dealing with this pandemic. And everyone has been

00:35:16.480 --> 00:35:20.640
[Guest]: talking about Trump's response and how, you know, the administration was asleep at the

00:35:20.640 --> 00:35:27.080
[Guest]: wheel and they delayed any kind of, you know, putting in place any machinery for social

00:35:27.080 --> 00:35:31.480
[Guest]: distancing as well as treatment, as well as economic stimulus and so on and so forth.

00:35:31.480 --> 00:35:36.400
[Guest]: So in that sense, it doesn't surprise me that different governments across the world are

00:35:36.400 --> 00:35:42.360
[Guest]: struggling with the appropriate response, right? What did surprise me about the Indian

00:35:42.360 --> 00:35:50.240
[Guest]: government's response is that it was so blind and deaf to the poor. That genuinely shocked

00:35:50.240 --> 00:35:55.480
[Guest]: me, because normally the way I think about this is politicians are self-interested and

00:35:55.480 --> 00:36:01.640
[Guest]: they think of their core, you know, sort of voting constituency. India is a poor country.

00:36:01.640 --> 00:36:08.960
[Guest]: A lot of the people were talking about the median voter is also typically below the,

00:36:08.960 --> 00:36:14.080
[Guest]: you know, not, they don't make elite salaries. They don't live elite lifestyles. And I thought

00:36:14.080 --> 00:36:21.480
[Guest]: that all policies, when it came to the lockdown, out of sheer self-interest would be made keeping

00:36:21.480 --> 00:36:28.320
[Guest]: that person in mind, you know, your core constituency of voters. The way those people were just

00:36:28.320 --> 00:36:34.480
[Guest]: rendered invisible in our system, that truly took me by surprise. And I realized when I

00:36:34.480 --> 00:36:40.960
[Guest]: wrote the Man of System column in regard to Modi's lockdown, it was very specifically

00:36:40.960 --> 00:36:47.000
[Guest]: talking about the lockdown announcement. If we go back to that announcement, which was,

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:54.440
[Guest]: you know, end of March, he does not mention what is an essential service, right? There

00:36:54.440 --> 00:37:00.680
[Guest]: is no clarity on what will be open and what is to remain closed. There is no clarity or

00:37:00.680 --> 00:37:06.080
[Guest]: direction given to the police on how they are to enforce the lockdown. The moment he

00:37:06.080 --> 00:37:12.160
[Guest]: finished his announcement at about 8.30 PM, there was a run on all the stores and pharmacies

00:37:12.160 --> 00:37:17.000
[Guest]: because people wanted to stock up because they didn't know if they can get milk tomorrow.

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:20.280
[Guest]: And the reason they didn't know if they can get milk tomorrow is because there was no

00:37:20.280 --> 00:37:27.420
[Guest]: direction on a 40 minute, you know, prime ministerial broadcast on whether he thought

00:37:27.420 --> 00:37:34.320
[Guest]: essential services would stay open and how he was planning to deal with it. Now, my understanding

00:37:34.320 --> 00:37:38.920
[Guest]: of why that announcement was made in a particular way was he thought people will just trust

00:37:38.920 --> 00:37:43.920
[Guest]: him. So if he says, we will keep essential services open, people just trust him, you

00:37:43.920 --> 00:37:50.000
[Guest]: know, like nice pieces on the chessboard, they stay put. And they say, I think that's

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:58.000
[Guest]: what happened. I'm not sure. It's far worse with migrants, right? Economic migrants, especially

00:37:58.000 --> 00:38:02.600
[Guest]: in the informal sector, almost all are in the informal sector. They've been rendered

00:38:02.600 --> 00:38:07.840
[Guest]: utterly invisible in our current political economy. And this is not a COVID problem.

00:38:07.840 --> 00:38:13.880
[Guest]: This is a larger political economy problem in India. 92% of the Indian labor force works

00:38:13.880 --> 00:38:20.400
[Guest]: in the informal sector. 60 to 70% are daily wage laborers in that particular system. Only

00:38:20.400 --> 00:38:27.600
[Guest]: 8% of India's labor force is formal, you know, all above board with formal contracts. In

00:38:27.600 --> 00:38:34.280
[Guest]: these circumstances, when like we're talking not about a few thousand people or a hundred

00:38:34.280 --> 00:38:40.600
[Guest]: thousand people, we're talking about 400, 500 million people in the country at a particular

00:38:40.600 --> 00:38:46.680
[Guest]: point in time, just to not think of them or not to think about how they're going to survive

00:38:46.680 --> 00:38:51.780
[Guest]: the next three weeks when they don't have a daily wage coming in. He did not make an

00:38:51.780 --> 00:38:56.320
[Guest]: announcement to give them any income support. There was no announcement made for in-kind

00:38:56.320 --> 00:39:03.080
[Guest]: transfer in that particular, you know, press announcement. There was literally nothing

00:39:03.080 --> 00:39:08.360
[Guest]: for them. So are we really surprised that they wanted to go home? Right? If there's

00:39:08.360 --> 00:39:12.640
[Guest]: any kind of economic uncertainty, the first thing I would want to do is go to a safe place

00:39:12.640 --> 00:39:16.400
[Guest]: where I will be looked after as opposed to being a strange city where I'm staying in

00:39:16.400 --> 00:39:20.600
[Guest]: a slum, where I don't know if I'll have a job tomorrow, where I don't know if I can

00:39:20.600 --> 00:39:26.040
[Guest]: get out of the home tomorrow and I can even buy bread or biscuits to eat. So we saw this

00:39:26.040 --> 00:39:31.280
[Guest]: huge exodus of migrant labor trying to go back home to places where they have a safety

00:39:31.280 --> 00:39:38.480
[Guest]: net. And then we saw the state just come down on them with the full brute force, literally

00:39:38.480 --> 00:39:44.320
[Guest]: beating people up. You know, who was standing at bus stops. What happened in Anand Vihar

00:39:44.320 --> 00:39:51.800
[Guest]: in Delhi is just an embarrassment. So it's a combination of a complete failure to understand

00:39:51.800 --> 00:39:59.120
[Guest]: how a normal, rational person would think in these circumstances and a particular sort

00:39:59.120 --> 00:40:05.040
[Guest]: of blindness to who are the people in need in India? Who are the people who are vulnerable

00:40:05.040 --> 00:40:10.080
[Guest]: to economic stress, who are vulnerable to health stress or vulnerable to social stress?

00:40:10.080 --> 00:40:15.200
[Guest]: And how do we keep that person in mind, like the Gandhi talisman that you spoke about and

00:40:15.200 --> 00:40:21.000
[Guest]: figure out policies around it? His press announcement just completely sort of, it was a failure

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:26.480
[Guest]: on all of those counts. There was some relief package which was announced 48 hours later.

00:40:26.480 --> 00:40:33.640
[Guest]: It was too little, too late. By then the economic stress and the panic related economic stress

00:40:33.640 --> 00:40:39.380
[Guest]: and uncertainty had already spread, right? In every single one of my recommendations

00:40:39.380 --> 00:40:45.560
[Guest]: to have a lockdown, at each point I've said, we need to give direct cash transfer, maybe

00:40:45.560 --> 00:40:51.000
[Guest]: some food subsidies for three to four months. Because let's say the lockdown lifts in five

00:40:51.000 --> 00:40:55.320
[Guest]: weeks, doesn't mean all industries are going to function, right? Are we going to allow

00:40:55.320 --> 00:40:59.200
[Guest]: construction? Is that essential? If you don't allow construction, then all the people who

00:40:59.200 --> 00:41:04.480
[Guest]: work on daily labor as daily labor and construction sites are no longer going to have a job. So

00:41:04.480 --> 00:41:09.240
[Guest]: we need to really carefully think about what does the Indian political economy look like?

00:41:09.240 --> 00:41:15.240
[Guest]: Who are the people working in it? There's only seven to 8% elites who have formal contracts,

00:41:15.240 --> 00:41:20.480
[Guest]: internet, who can stay at home and think about, you know, I'm getting bored watching Netflix

00:41:20.480 --> 00:41:24.800
[Guest]: kind of problem. Everyone else is going to think about livelihood. They're going to think

00:41:24.800 --> 00:41:29.200
[Guest]: about their children. They're going to think about the ability to feed themselves and literally

00:41:29.200 --> 00:41:38.200
[Guest]: no sort of, you know, policy or emergency relief was created for them. Now things have

00:41:38.200 --> 00:41:43.480
[Guest]: started coming in. The government has started thinking more keenly about emergency relief.

00:41:43.480 --> 00:41:48.960
[Guest]: You know, they're thinking of opening up food go downs, you know, giving away in-kind transfers

00:41:48.960 --> 00:41:54.680
[Guest]: in terms of food grain, things like that, LPG gas. So the government has now started

00:41:54.680 --> 00:41:58.440
[Guest]: thinking about it, but the initial wave of panic could have just been stopped if the

00:41:58.440 --> 00:42:04.840
[Guest]: Modi administration had thought about the citizens as individual people who react to

00:42:04.840 --> 00:42:09.580
[Guest]: circumstances as opposed to pieces on a chess board, which can simply be pushed around.

00:42:09.580 --> 00:42:14.440
[Amit Varma]: So I have like three observations to make here. The third one in part a disagreement,

00:42:14.440 --> 00:42:18.400
[Amit Varma]: which leads to a further question. But the first two observations are that number one,

00:42:18.400 --> 00:42:24.600
[Amit Varma]: when we speak of state capacity, I'd also like to speak of within that subset, which

00:42:24.600 --> 00:42:28.480
[Amit Varma]: is intellectual capacity in the sense that one thing I think that does not exist in the

00:42:28.480 --> 00:42:34.520
[Amit Varma]: state is the capacity to appreciate the complexities of the economy, which run through spontaneous

00:42:34.520 --> 00:42:41.400
[Amit Varma]: disorder. For example, nobody within the state seemed to figure out that, you know, that

00:42:41.400 --> 00:42:47.000
[Amit Varma]: almost every service in a sense was an essential service because they were all interconnected.

00:42:47.000 --> 00:42:51.400
[Amit Varma]: It was one thing to say that, okay, a grocery store is an essential service and it will

00:42:51.400 --> 00:42:56.880
[Amit Varma]: remain open, but there is an entire supply chain of, for example, truckers are bringing

00:42:56.880 --> 00:43:02.000
[Amit Varma]: maida to the grocery store and those truckers have to eat somewhere. And if the dhabas are

00:43:02.000 --> 00:43:07.320
[Amit Varma]: closed on the highway, they cannot drive the truck. And there are all kinds of ancillaries

00:43:07.320 --> 00:43:12.640
[Amit Varma]: up and down the chain, which involves practically the whole economy. And honestly, those are

00:43:12.640 --> 00:43:18.480
[Amit Varma]: all too complex for a central planner or a group of babus or an expert committee sitting

00:43:18.480 --> 00:43:24.360
[Amit Varma]: down somewhere to basically figure out that these are all the things that will happen.

00:43:24.360 --> 00:43:29.360
[Amit Varma]: This is not meant in any way as a criticism of the lockdown or to say that the lockdown

00:43:29.360 --> 00:43:33.520
[Amit Varma]: should not have happened. You know, like you, I recommended from the start, we should have

00:43:33.520 --> 00:43:37.320
[Amit Varma]: a lockdown and I stand by that. But these are some of the things which you couldn't

00:43:37.320 --> 00:43:42.600
[Amit Varma]: have looked at. Secondly, one of the things which came, I won't say it appalled me because

00:43:42.600 --> 00:43:48.200
[Amit Varma]: it was not new to me. One of the things that came into stark relief during this entire

00:43:48.200 --> 00:43:55.480
[Amit Varma]: period is you use the term citizens earlier. I object to that because constantly the political

00:43:55.480 --> 00:44:01.200
[Amit Varma]: dispensation has treated us not as citizens, but as subjects. You know, even in the Prime

00:44:01.200 --> 00:44:06.800
[Amit Varma]: Minister's last address, which he made where he's saying that keep a distance and we must

00:44:06.800 --> 00:44:11.600
[Amit Varma]: make sure it doesn't spread and blah, blah, blah. It was all about this is what you must

00:44:11.600 --> 00:44:16.480
[Amit Varma]: do. It's not about here is what I am doing for you. I am the Pradhan Sevak. These are

00:44:16.480 --> 00:44:20.880
[Amit Varma]: the incentives I've put in place to get more mass manufactured. These are, you know, how

00:44:20.880 --> 00:44:25.480
[Amit Varma]: we are going to get more ventilators down and all of that. Nothing about what he was

00:44:25.480 --> 00:44:31.800
[Amit Varma]: doing for us, but more about here is what you subjects must do. And you know, that sort

00:44:31.800 --> 00:44:37.320
[Amit Varma]: of approach is a little appalling. The third area where I want to sort of cast a sceptical

00:44:37.320 --> 00:44:43.000
[Amit Varma]: eye on what you said about cash transfers and food subsidies and all that. Forget the

00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:48.200
[Amit Varma]: theory of that. I'm not going to argue now about whether those are desirable or not.

00:44:48.200 --> 00:44:51.560
[Amit Varma]: But I'm just going to say that listen, the state could not have implemented them. So

00:44:51.560 --> 00:44:55.920
[Amit Varma]: even if they were to see that there'll be a huge problem with migrant labor, and we

00:44:55.920 --> 00:45:00.200
[Amit Varma]: need to feed everyone, the state did not have the capacity and does not have the capacity

00:45:00.200 --> 00:45:04.840
[Amit Varma]: as of now to implement it. In fact, you know what you see in the big cities where I'm familiar

00:45:04.840 --> 00:45:11.520
[Amit Varma]: with relief efforts such as Mumbai and Delhi, 90% if not more of the relief efforts at feeding

00:45:11.520 --> 00:45:16.760
[Amit Varma]: these migrants or sheltering these migrants are coming from civil society. And because

00:45:16.760 --> 00:45:22.080
[Amit Varma]: I define markets as basically all voluntary exchanges, it is actually markets which are

00:45:22.080 --> 00:45:28.760
[Amit Varma]: coming into play. So you know, society helping itself and the state remaining a sort of a

00:45:28.760 --> 00:45:34.640
[Amit Varma]: failed state. And this actually sheds light. And of course, you know, COVID-19 sheds light

00:45:34.640 --> 00:45:38.440
[Amit Varma]: on many things. And we'll speak about that as this episode goes on. But one of the things

00:45:38.440 --> 00:45:43.440
[Amit Varma]: that it shed lights on is why government needs to be as local as possible. Because the more

00:45:43.440 --> 00:45:50.480
[Amit Varma]: local government is, the more problems like this are solvable. You know, for example,

00:45:50.480 --> 00:45:55.760
[Amit Varma]: you see the response in Kerala where you really see the benefits of local government and local

00:45:55.760 --> 00:46:02.080
[Amit Varma]: knowledge coming into play. Even in Maharashtra sitting in Mumbai, I'm pleasantly surprised

00:46:02.080 --> 00:46:06.120
[Amit Varma]: at the leadership and communication of someone like Uddhav Thackeray. I mean, I've opposed

00:46:06.120 --> 00:46:10.760
[Amit Varma]: the Shiv Sena all my life, but he's been coming on TV every evening or giving these broadcasts

00:46:10.760 --> 00:46:14.960
[Amit Varma]: every evening in Marathi, where he's just talking in this conversational way about the

00:46:14.960 --> 00:46:20.040
[Amit Varma]: nuts and bolts of what is happening and what he's doing. And my sense is that the more

00:46:20.040 --> 00:46:26.200
[Amit Varma]: local you make governance, the better the governance will be, which is a larger point

00:46:26.200 --> 00:46:31.200
[Amit Varma]: to people like you and I have made forever, but has come into sharp focus because of this

00:46:31.200 --> 00:46:37.000
[Guest]: crisis. Yeah, so I'll tell you where I mean, I completely agree with you, even your disagreement

00:46:37.000 --> 00:46:42.880
[Guest]: with me. My point was not that the state can actually execute a direct cash transfer perfectly.

00:46:42.880 --> 00:46:49.120
[Guest]: My point was more that they didn't even think about it, right? Just the complete like blindness

00:46:49.120 --> 00:46:54.960
[Guest]: to who are the people in this country and what will be the immediate, you know, cause

00:46:54.960 --> 00:46:59.880
[Guest]: for panic or what are the immediate circumstances? Now, if they had announced something like

00:46:59.880 --> 00:47:06.740
[Guest]: that, it might have sort of not caused the large scale exodus. Now, I completely agree

00:47:06.740 --> 00:47:10.880
[Guest]: with you that India doesn't have the state capacity to execute these things perfectly,

00:47:10.880 --> 00:47:16.080
[Guest]: but it would have at least prevented the original chaos that started, which potentially could

00:47:16.080 --> 00:47:20.440
[Guest]: have spread the virus, which was already in big cities to now, you know, districts in

00:47:20.440 --> 00:47:25.760
[Guest]: Western Bihar and UP. So that could have been prevented, but it wasn't prevented because

00:47:25.760 --> 00:47:29.920
[Guest]: they just weren't thinking about people, as you said, like citizens, they were thinking

00:47:29.920 --> 00:47:34.960
[Guest]: about them like subjects or just someone to be directed. Now, coming to the state capacity

00:47:34.960 --> 00:47:42.840
[Guest]: issue, this is the great conundrum of this COVID crisis. Now, we need the lockdown because

00:47:42.840 --> 00:47:47.000
[Guest]: we have poor healthcare capacity. We have poor healthcare capacity because we have overall

00:47:47.000 --> 00:47:53.760
[Guest]: weak state capacity, but overall weak state capacity also means two more things. One,

00:47:53.760 --> 00:47:59.680
[Guest]: we cannot enforce social distancing very well, right? And this is on two margins. One is

00:47:59.680 --> 00:48:06.320
[Guest]: we just don't have the manpower and personnel to actually make sure that everyone is sheltered

00:48:06.320 --> 00:48:11.480
[Guest]: in place. Everyone has essentials, everyone has food, and, you know, people who need help

00:48:11.480 --> 00:48:15.400
[Guest]: or medical assistance have it so that they can shelter in place properly. We don't have

00:48:15.400 --> 00:48:21.920
[Guest]: that manpower at the state level, which means a lot of the, you know, gaps are picked up

00:48:21.920 --> 00:48:29.880
[Guest]: by civil society. The second part is weak state capacity also means that we don't have,

00:48:29.880 --> 00:48:35.840
[Guest]: not everyone in India has clean water or access to clean water, which means this whole, please

00:48:35.840 --> 00:48:43.360
[Guest]: keep washing your hands. I mean, it's laughable. 10% of India has absolutely no access to clean

00:48:43.360 --> 00:48:50.120
[Guest]: piped water, right? In the other 90%, we have pretty good data on who has piped water to

00:48:50.120 --> 00:48:56.920
[Guest]: their dwelling, but most people have extreme water shortages. Close to 60% of Indians who

00:48:56.920 --> 00:49:01.960
[Guest]: do get piped water have extreme water shortages, especially in the summer months, right? For

00:49:01.960 --> 00:49:09.160
[Guest]: anything except drinking water. Most of rural India, you know, 50%, 60% of rural India relies

00:49:09.160 --> 00:49:15.160
[Guest]: on community hand pumps to get most of its water. So in these circumstances, even the

00:49:15.160 --> 00:49:20.480
[Guest]: simplest solution, which is keep washing your hands, it is a huge protection against the

00:49:20.480 --> 00:49:26.520
[Guest]: spread of the virus, is not easily implementable in India. Now you live in Mumbai, one of the

00:49:26.520 --> 00:49:32.120
[Guest]: ticking time bombs in Mumbai, which literally keeps me up at night is Dharavi. Dharavi,

00:49:32.120 --> 00:49:38.240
[Guest]: in the slum part of Dharavi, they don't have access to clean water. Four to 500 people

00:49:38.240 --> 00:49:45.240
[Guest]: on average use a single bathroom facility, right? And all this is a function of weak

00:49:45.240 --> 00:49:49.960
[Guest]: state capacity to begin with. The inability to make sure that we have access to clean

00:49:49.960 --> 00:49:55.480
[Guest]: water, that we have access to clean sanitation facilities, that people are not washing their

00:49:55.480 --> 00:50:00.720
[Guest]: hands right next to where people are openly defecating or urinating. We have not solved

00:50:00.720 --> 00:50:05.800
[Guest]: that problem in 70 years. So now suddenly putting on a mask on TV and saying, please

00:50:05.800 --> 00:50:10.680
[Guest]: keep washing your hands, it doesn't get you very far because the state capacity has not

00:50:10.680 --> 00:50:18.360
[Guest]: made that solution possible. So we have a problem in both facilitating shelter in place

00:50:18.360 --> 00:50:23.920
[Guest]: and social distancing, and also in the most basic forms, which is, you know, can people

00:50:23.920 --> 00:50:31.040
[Guest]: wash their hands? Can people keep themselves clean? So this is just the kind of, or sort

00:50:31.040 --> 00:50:37.480
[Guest]: of the depth of the problem we have with COVID. Now, these problems make the lockdown even

00:50:37.480 --> 00:50:43.160
[Guest]: more essential, right? Because if people can't shelter in place appropriately and they can't

00:50:43.160 --> 00:50:49.200
[Guest]: wash their hands and they could possibly become vectors or worse still asymptomatic vectors

00:50:49.200 --> 00:50:54.060
[Guest]: spreading the virus, then even more reason we need a more stringent version of the lockdown.

00:50:54.060 --> 00:50:59.640
[Guest]: So then the police and the danda comes down even more harshly. So the whole problem as

00:50:59.640 --> 00:51:06.000
[Guest]: you rightly identified is one of very weak state capacity, both intellectual, also in

00:51:06.000 --> 00:51:11.040
[Guest]: terms of manpower, and also in terms of just the way we think about these problems at the

00:51:11.040 --> 00:51:17.600
[Guest]: union, state and local government level. Now coming to the local government issue, a lot

00:51:17.600 --> 00:51:24.840
[Guest]: of these problems of, you know, clean water, public sanitation, the ability to have access

00:51:24.840 --> 00:51:32.280
[Guest]: to facilities, right? Just can I go to a food shelter? Can I get access to water easily?

00:51:32.280 --> 00:51:36.720
[Guest]: Can I get access to medical supplies easily? These things are best done at the municipal

00:51:36.720 --> 00:51:42.760
[Guest]: level and over 70 years, we never built up any kind of local government and we didn't

00:51:42.760 --> 00:51:48.720
[Guest]: empower it. You and I have talked about this in at least two of your previous episodes,

00:51:48.720 --> 00:51:53.720
[Guest]: one which was on urban local government and the other one which was on a cast and open

00:51:53.720 --> 00:52:01.360
[Guest]: defecation. In both cases, we discussed in detail how the 73rd and the 74th amendment

00:52:01.360 --> 00:52:07.000
[Guest]: of the constitution created an entire layer of government. They empowered it to be democratically

00:52:07.000 --> 00:52:12.160
[Guest]: elected, but they never devolved funds to that layer of government. So, you know, we

00:52:12.160 --> 00:52:18.520
[Guest]: have no fiscal federalism in India. Municipalities today, if the union government writes a check

00:52:18.520 --> 00:52:22.560
[Guest]: and just sends it to municipal governments, they don't have the capacity to even spend

00:52:22.560 --> 00:52:28.080
[Guest]: it because they have not developed capacity over the years, hired enough manpower, actually

00:52:28.080 --> 00:52:34.000
[Guest]: spent these resources. Kerala and Tamil Nadu are two states which historically devolved

00:52:34.000 --> 00:52:39.520
[Guest]: much more of the governance to the local level from the state government and that's why they

00:52:39.520 --> 00:52:45.360
[Guest]: have been so good at combating this current problem, right, of COVID-19. Kerala has been

00:52:45.360 --> 00:52:50.640
[Guest]: particularly good for other reasons too, which we can get into if you want, but the element

00:52:50.640 --> 00:52:56.360
[Guest]: of how strong is your local governance is incredibly important. Now, in the absence

00:52:56.360 --> 00:53:01.720
[Guest]: of union government being able to do anything, state government not being able to reach the

00:53:01.720 --> 00:53:07.740
[Guest]: last mile, our fail-safe in India is civil society and it has always been civil society.

00:53:07.740 --> 00:53:12.120
[Guest]: It was the case during demonetization, it was really civil society which came to the

00:53:12.120 --> 00:53:17.640
[Guest]: rescue. You know, people started using each other, family networks, giving each other

00:53:17.640 --> 00:53:25.360
[Guest]: IOUs to actually get through life and even then we had an inordinate human cost, a lot

00:53:25.360 --> 00:53:31.120
[Guest]: of deaths, a lot of deprivation, a lot of loss of livelihood, but people got through

00:53:31.120 --> 00:53:35.880
[Guest]: because of civil society and COVID-19 is no different. They will, whatever we manage to

00:53:35.880 --> 00:53:40.400
[Amit Varma]: get through will be because of civil society. On that hopeful note, let's take a quick commercial

