00:55:09.960 --> 00:55:13.960
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to The Scene and The Unseen. I'm chatting with Shruti Rajgopalan about

00:55:13.960 --> 00:55:19.840
[Amit Varma]: COVID-19, a subject she spent a lot of time thinking and writing about. And one of the

00:55:19.840 --> 00:55:25.400
[Amit Varma]: places where her writing has appeared on this is on the great blog Marginal Revolution,

00:55:25.400 --> 00:55:30.040
[Amit Varma]: which is even though the age of blogs is dead, that is a one blog I still go to almost every

00:55:30.040 --> 00:55:35.640
[Amit Varma]: day to remarkable thinkers who run it, Tyler Cowen and Alex Tabarrok, both of whom have

00:55:35.640 --> 00:55:40.360
[Amit Varma]: been on The Scene and The Unseen. In fact, I have one episode I recorded with Shruti

00:55:40.360 --> 00:55:45.960
[Amit Varma]: and Alex when I met them in Delhi at the start of Feb, which will now be released in June.

00:55:45.960 --> 00:55:49.800
[Amit Varma]: And you know, it has nothing to do with COVID, obviously, because it was the start of Feb.

00:55:49.800 --> 00:55:54.560
[Amit Varma]: You'll have to wait for that. But I have rambled again. The reason I brought up Marginal Revolution

00:55:54.560 --> 00:55:59.240
[Amit Varma]: was that Shruti wrote a piece on Marginal Revolution and all her stuff will be linked

00:55:59.240 --> 00:56:05.740
[Amit Varma]: from the show notes, where Shruti, you spoke about the few things that the government needs

00:56:05.740 --> 00:56:09.800
[Amit Varma]: to do to make the lockdown a success. Like this piece was written right after the lockdown

00:56:09.800 --> 00:56:15.200
[Amit Varma]: was announced. And you said, okay, it's not enough to announce it. You need to make sure

00:56:15.200 --> 00:56:20.040
[Amit Varma]: that we use this opportunity. Here are the things we need to do. So can you recapitulate

00:56:20.040 --> 00:56:25.280
[Guest]: some of that for me? Yeah, so the way this came about is I work

00:56:25.280 --> 00:56:30.920
[Guest]: at George Mason University. So you know, the Marginal Revolution appearance should be considered

00:56:30.920 --> 00:56:36.880
[Guest]: in that context. Tyler Cowen runs is also the academic director of the Mercator Center,

00:56:36.880 --> 00:56:42.040
[Guest]: which is where I work. Alex Tabarrok and Tyler were both my teachers when I did my PhD. Alex

00:56:42.040 --> 00:56:46.920
[Guest]: is also a co-author. And we've appeared on your podcast and done a few things together.

00:56:46.920 --> 00:56:52.560
[Guest]: So when the lockdown happened in India, as soon as Prime Minister Modi announced the

00:56:52.560 --> 00:56:58.160
[Guest]: lockdown, I started thinking through, you know, the kinds of things that are important.

00:56:58.160 --> 00:57:04.720
[Guest]: And my way, just like you, of thinking through a lot of these ideas is just to write and

00:57:04.720 --> 00:57:09.520
[Guest]: I'd written an email to Tyler Cowen. And that, you know, a version of that email is what

00:57:09.520 --> 00:57:15.440
[Guest]: appeared on the blog. So that's what you see. Now, when the lockdown was going on, I was

00:57:15.440 --> 00:57:22.560
[Guest]: working on another paper with my co-author, Abhishek Chautagunta. He is a doctoral student

00:57:22.560 --> 00:57:29.200
[Guest]: at the University of Hamburg, really smart, young economist. And we were working on assessing

00:57:29.200 --> 00:57:33.640
[Guest]: India's healthcare capacity. So this is the first paper, which we've alluded to a few

00:57:33.640 --> 00:57:38.040
[Guest]: times where we were looking at how many hospital beds does India have? How many doctors does

00:57:38.040 --> 00:57:43.340
[Guest]: it have? And so on. This is now a Mercatus working paper and it's available publicly.

00:57:43.340 --> 00:57:49.560
[Guest]: So while writing this paper, a few things became very clear. One, as I said, overall,

00:57:49.560 --> 00:57:55.560
[Guest]: India's healthcare capacity is extremely weak, right? Another thing that became very clear,

00:57:55.560 --> 00:57:59.520
[Guest]: and I wasn't aware of this because I've not worked on the health sector before the COVID

00:57:59.520 --> 00:58:06.840
[Guest]: crisis, is that India's private sector for healthcare is about three to four times larger

00:58:06.840 --> 00:58:12.120
[Guest]: in terms of overall healthcare capacity than the government healthcare system, right? And

00:58:12.120 --> 00:58:18.280
[Guest]: that has been consequence of a lot of historical policies and the focus of the government.

00:58:18.280 --> 00:58:24.560
[Guest]: But consequently, about 55 to 60% of the hospital bed capacity is in the private sector in India.

00:58:24.560 --> 00:58:30.680
[Guest]: 90% of the doctors work in the private or charitable sector in India, right? 80% of

00:58:30.680 --> 00:58:36.400
[Guest]: the ventilators are in the private sector because close to 80% or more of the intensive

00:58:36.400 --> 00:58:42.840
[Guest]: care beds are in the private sector. So it became very clear to me that during the lockdown,

00:58:42.840 --> 00:58:47.160
[Guest]: the whole point of the lockdown, as we mentioned at the head of the podcast, is that there's

00:58:47.160 --> 00:58:52.880
[Guest]: this trade-off, right? We need to flatten the curve. So a lockdown is only helpful if

00:58:52.880 --> 00:58:58.080
[Guest]: you build up healthcare capacity during the lockdown so that when things start slowly

00:58:58.080 --> 00:59:03.720
[Guest]: opening up, you have more healthcare capacity to deal with the transmission of the virus.

00:59:03.720 --> 00:59:09.240
[Guest]: Now, if you don't do that, no matter when you lift the lockdown, there is going to be

00:59:09.240 --> 00:59:13.800
[Guest]: a spread of infection and we can't have an endless lockdown. So this was from that point

00:59:13.800 --> 00:59:18.880
[Guest]: of view. Now, if the Indian healthcare system was entirely run by the government as it is

00:59:18.880 --> 00:59:25.480
[Guest]: in many other countries, I would have had a different recommendation. But most of India's

00:59:25.480 --> 00:59:32.520
[Guest]: healthcare resources, especially at the top end for critical care, ventilators, pharmaceuticals,

00:59:32.520 --> 00:59:37.040
[Guest]: all of this is in the private sector, which means that to battle the COVID crisis, we

00:59:37.040 --> 00:59:42.280
[Guest]: need to really rely on the private sector response. And as you and I have talked about

00:59:42.280 --> 00:59:52.080
[Guest]: many, many times before, we need to sort of initiate and stimulate private response by

00:59:52.080 --> 00:59:57.840
[Guest]: incentivizing them. And the best way to incentivize them is to pump in a lot of funds into the

00:59:57.840 --> 01:00:03.720
[Guest]: private sector and not take it over. So as you know, in India, we have a huge tendency

01:00:03.720 --> 01:00:09.160
[Guest]: to nationalize things. It seems that hasn't happened in a while, since Indira Gandhi,

01:00:09.160 --> 01:00:17.040
[Guest]: what we nationalized and demonetized our currency. So the tendency to sort of appropriate private

01:00:17.040 --> 01:00:22.680
[Guest]: property and nationalize is been there in every single government in India, not just

01:00:22.680 --> 01:00:28.120
[Guest]: the Modi government. So my first recommendation was that we need to resist that temptation

01:00:28.120 --> 01:00:34.320
[Guest]: because the moment you nationalize private healthcare capacity, it cannot grow. So if

01:00:34.320 --> 01:00:40.360
[Guest]: today we have 131 beds per 100,000 by including public and private capacity, tomorrow, if

01:00:40.360 --> 01:00:46.120
[Guest]: you nationalize it, that's where it ends. On the other hand, if you say that we're going

01:00:46.120 --> 01:00:51.760
[Guest]: to pay for all tests and the treatment, even of the poorest people, please keep your doors

01:00:51.760 --> 01:00:57.820
[Guest]: open to them. The government will reimburse or subsidize. Then private sector has a huge

01:00:57.820 --> 01:01:05.480
[Guest]: incentive to respond and increase capacity. So this has been said many, many times over.

01:01:05.480 --> 01:01:10.440
[Guest]: You mentioned marginal revolution, the book that is written by Tyler Cowen and Alex Tabarrok

01:01:10.440 --> 01:01:18.000
[Guest]: on principles of microeconomics has this lovely sentence on the price system. It says the

01:01:18.000 --> 01:01:26.160
[Guest]: price is a signal wrapped in an incentive. So it both signals whether there is a shortage

01:01:26.160 --> 01:01:30.800
[Guest]: or whether there is a surplus because the price will adjust, but it is also an incentive.

01:01:30.800 --> 01:01:37.640
[Guest]: When prices are high, suppliers have an incentive to increase supply. So that was the thought

01:01:37.640 --> 01:01:43.200
[Guest]: process behind it. It's really econ 101. We're in an emergency. When you take stock, most

01:01:43.200 --> 01:01:49.120
[Guest]: of the resources are in the private sector. So let's respond with that. Aside from most

01:01:49.120 --> 01:01:52.600
[Guest]: of our resources being in the private sector, the other thing I realized, and this will

01:01:52.600 --> 01:01:56.520
[Guest]: be of no surprise to you because we've talked about this for education. It's no different

01:01:56.520 --> 01:02:04.080
[Guest]: in healthcare. Even the poorest Indians prefer going to a private healthcare facility and

01:02:04.080 --> 01:02:09.000
[Guest]: paying a lot of money for it rather than going to the free or highly subsidized government

01:02:09.000 --> 01:02:15.000
[Guest]: facility. And you can imagine why government hospitals are not that great. They are extremely

01:02:15.000 --> 01:02:20.800
[Guest]: overcrowded. They have very few doctor to patient ratio. They don't have the most advanced

01:02:20.800 --> 01:02:25.840
[Guest]: equipment and especially at the smaller primary healthcare centers, depending on which state

01:02:25.840 --> 01:02:30.740
[Guest]: you're in, things tend to be falling apart, right? So if you look at the national sample

01:02:30.740 --> 01:02:39.320
[Guest]: survey data across every expenditure quintile, that is from the lowest household expenditure

01:02:39.320 --> 01:02:45.960
[Guest]: group, the lowest fifth to the highest, every single quintile, people prefer going to private

01:02:45.960 --> 01:02:50.320
[Guest]: hospitals and they spend an enormous amount of money in private hospitals. And the way

01:02:50.320 --> 01:02:56.000
[Guest]: they fund that is borrowing from family, selling jewelry, selling land and things like that.

01:02:56.000 --> 01:03:01.880
[Guest]: So there is a huge demand even amongst the poorest citizens to go to private facilities

01:03:01.880 --> 01:03:06.920
[Guest]: so we can just leverage that if the state said we will subsidize it, right? And this

01:03:06.920 --> 01:03:11.640
[Guest]: is the time for the state to intervene and really look after people. I would have said

01:03:11.640 --> 01:03:17.920
[Guest]: that the same is true for testing. And as you know, the Supreme Court has displayed

01:03:17.920 --> 01:03:23.560
[Guest]: and continue to display its complete economic illiteracy and lack of common sense time and

01:03:23.560 --> 01:03:29.920
[Guest]: time again. They said that all private labs need to conduct tests for free, right? Now

01:03:29.920 --> 01:03:34.880
[Guest]: the problem with this is private labs can't just work on science and good intentions.

01:03:34.880 --> 01:03:39.000
[Guest]: They need to cover their costs. And if you tell someone that they can't make money even

01:03:39.000 --> 01:03:43.280
[Guest]: to pay their employees and keep the lights on, then they will just shut shop, which means

01:03:43.280 --> 01:03:47.160
[Guest]: we already have too few labs in India. We're going to have even fewer because of this awful

01:03:47.160 --> 01:03:51.520
[Guest]: policy. What they should have said instead, I mean, first they shouldn't have said anything

01:03:51.520 --> 01:03:55.880
[Guest]: at all on this matter because they're really giving executive orders from the bench. This

01:03:55.880 --> 01:04:01.240
[Guest]: is not a judicial issue, right? So they should have stayed away from it. What the executive

01:04:01.240 --> 01:04:06.560
[Guest]: state government and union government should have said instead was we will reimburse private

01:04:06.560 --> 01:04:13.880
[Guest]: labs for tests where people cannot pay for tests, right? And usually in these circumstances,

01:04:13.880 --> 01:04:18.480
[Guest]: it's not like there's going to be a huge moral hazard problem. Rich people can easily pay

01:04:18.480 --> 01:04:23.520
[Guest]: 4,000 rupees or whatever the cost of a private test is, whereas poor people can't. And that

01:04:23.520 --> 01:04:28.200
[Guest]: difference is quite clear. And I think we can trust hospitals to know who can pay and

01:04:28.200 --> 01:04:34.280
[Guest]: who cannot pay depending on the circumstances and the government should have just reimbursed.

01:04:34.280 --> 01:04:39.320
[Guest]: So there will be much more large scale, wide scale testing, right? The poorest people will

01:04:39.320 --> 01:04:44.520
[Guest]: not be denied tests, but at the same time, we don't compromise testing capacity because

01:04:44.520 --> 01:04:49.080
[Guest]: private labs need to provide a bulk of testing capacity. The other reason we want a lot of

01:04:49.080 --> 01:04:53.360
[Guest]: new private labs to come up is we don't want everyone to go to one place for a test in

01:04:53.360 --> 01:04:57.840
[Guest]: a pandemic. We want people to go to a lot of different private labs. In fact, what we

01:04:57.840 --> 01:05:03.040
[Guest]: want is mobile labs that go to people. So these are the sorts of things that the government

01:05:03.040 --> 01:05:08.760
[Guest]: should have thought about that I hinted in that marginal revolution blog post. And this

01:05:08.760 --> 01:05:14.040
[Guest]: really had to do with me evaluating along with Abhishek Chattergunta, the kind of healthcare

01:05:14.040 --> 01:05:19.160
[Guest]: capacity we have. And we found that, you know, a bulk of it is in the private sector and

01:05:19.160 --> 01:05:23.840
[Guest]: two other findings from that paper were that there is huge variation in capacity across

01:05:23.840 --> 01:05:29.440
[Guest]: different states. Healthcare is a state level subject in India. And the difference between

01:05:29.440 --> 01:05:35.360
[Guest]: Andhra Pradesh and Bihar is just staggering, right? So there are even within India, as

01:05:35.360 --> 01:05:40.120
[Guest]: you know, Kerala has dealt with the problem particularly well. But Andhra Pradesh has

01:05:40.120 --> 01:05:48.120
[Guest]: very high ratio of doctors per capita or hospital beds per capita. Bihar, UP, Chhattisgarh,

01:05:48.120 --> 01:05:53.640
[Guest]: Jharkhand, traditionally extremely low. And you can imagine this, right? Poorer states

01:05:53.640 --> 01:05:59.360
[Guest]: also have, you know, lower GDP per capita, which means lower demand for private healthcare

01:05:59.360 --> 01:06:04.520
[Guest]: facilities, which means fewer clusters of healthcare in urban and peri-urban areas.

01:06:04.520 --> 01:06:08.760
[Guest]: So they just stuck with whatever the government healthcare system is. So that is kind of,

01:06:08.760 --> 01:06:15.200
[Guest]: you know, the situation there. The third, and this is extremely related to COVID, is

01:06:15.200 --> 01:06:20.120
[Guest]: most of the government efforts in healthcare facilities are in rural areas. And this is

01:06:20.120 --> 01:06:25.240
[Guest]: historically because, you know, rural health has been a huge problem. Infant mortality

01:06:25.240 --> 01:06:31.360
[Guest]: rates in rural areas has been very high historically. So over the last 30 years, successive governments

01:06:31.360 --> 01:06:38.720
[Guest]: have made a huge push to improve rural healthcare. In the process, most of the government facilities

01:06:38.720 --> 01:06:45.120
[Guest]: are in rural areas and fewer in urban areas. And most of the urban healthcare is handled

01:06:45.120 --> 01:06:50.880
[Guest]: by the private sector. But this also means that the urban poor are at risk, if you're

01:06:50.880 --> 01:06:55.680
[Guest]: not willing to subsidize the private sector, because they will overcrowd existing government

01:06:55.680 --> 01:07:01.360
[Guest]: hospitals and that number is extremely low in urban areas. And urban areas are at a high

01:07:01.360 --> 01:07:06.040
[Guest]: risk of the pandemic. So these were some of the trends that we found, which I tried to

01:07:06.040 --> 01:07:12.040
[Guest]: highlight. And because of this understanding of the difference between the healthcare capacity

01:07:12.040 --> 01:07:16.520
[Guest]: of the private sector and government sector, I made certain recommendations, which is,

01:07:16.520 --> 01:07:20.920
[Guest]: you know, we need to incentivize the private sector, and we need to think about how we

01:07:20.920 --> 01:07:27.360
[Guest]: spread the problem across the country. And some of it is to, you know, make sure we don't

01:07:27.360 --> 01:07:32.760
[Guest]: have price and quantity controls. We don't have import tariffs right now when we desperately

01:07:32.760 --> 01:07:42.000
[Guest]: need to import testing kits. We try and have some kind of bilateral negotiations with various

01:07:42.000 --> 01:07:47.000
[Guest]: countries. As you know, we are a huge producer of generic pharmaceuticals, and the whole

01:07:47.000 --> 01:07:52.640
[Guest]: world is relying on us to supply some of this, including the anti-malarial, which, you know,

01:07:52.640 --> 01:07:59.440
[Guest]: some people have found may or may not help treat COVID. But we should also think about

01:07:59.440 --> 01:08:05.480
[Guest]: things that India doesn't have, such as ventilators, right? India is extremely short of ventilators.

01:08:05.480 --> 01:08:10.720
[Guest]: We have only about 48,000 ventilators across the country. And most of them, as I mentioned

01:08:10.720 --> 01:08:16.200
[Guest]: before, are already taken. So we need to think about importing ventilators from other countries,

01:08:16.200 --> 01:08:22.720
[Guest]: right? So we need to keep the market system open and functioning, even though the tendency

01:08:22.720 --> 01:08:26.160
[Guest]: during the pandemic is let's suppress the market system.

01:08:26.160 --> 01:08:32.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and I want to elaborate a little bit on that. But first, I want to express my outrage,

01:08:32.200 --> 01:08:37.080
[Amit Varma]: which all my listeners will share, that one of my guests before I could said the word

01:08:37.080 --> 01:08:41.800
[Amit Varma]: incentive, there is this common trope on Twitter that Amit can't go five minutes without talking

01:08:41.800 --> 01:08:46.240
[Amit Varma]: about incentives on his show. And I did not do it through the entire first half. But now

01:08:46.240 --> 01:08:52.440
[Amit Varma]: that you've brought it up, I'm an economist, so kill me. Yeah. So now that you have brought

01:08:52.440 --> 01:08:57.480
[Amit Varma]: it up, I will have to sort of elaborate on an aspect of what you mentioned, which is

01:08:57.480 --> 01:09:02.720
[Amit Varma]: a beautiful phrase of prices being signals wrapped up in incentives. An illustration

01:09:02.720 --> 01:09:09.960
[Amit Varma]: of that, for example, is a price control that was initiated a few days ago on hand sanitizers.

01:09:09.960 --> 01:09:13.400
[Amit Varma]: And the result of that is that you don't have hand sanitizers in the market right now, at

01:09:13.400 --> 01:09:17.720
[Amit Varma]: least last I checked. And look, here's how it works. What happens is, let's say there's

01:09:17.720 --> 01:09:22.640
[Amit Varma]: a hand sanitizer, which is going for 50 rupees, a bottle of hand sanitizer for 50 rupees,

01:09:22.640 --> 01:09:27.880
[Amit Varma]: suddenly it becomes 200 rupees. And the state steps in and says, Oh, you know, hand sanitizer

01:09:27.880 --> 01:09:32.120
[Amit Varma]: seller, you are profiteering. This is bad. What will the poor do? No, the price must

01:09:32.120 --> 01:09:37.520
[Amit Varma]: be fixed at 50 rupees. This does two things. One is the immediate effect, which is not

01:09:37.520 --> 01:09:43.080
[Amit Varma]: even so bad. Honestly, the immediate effect is that it is first come first serve and sanitizers

01:09:43.080 --> 01:09:47.560
[Amit Varma]: sell out at 50 rupees. And then that's it. If there's a shortage, you can't get them

01:09:47.560 --> 01:09:53.480
[Amit Varma]: anymore, which is the situation now. But the worst effect is that had the price being allowed

01:09:53.480 --> 01:10:00.560
[Amit Varma]: to go up to 200 or whatever, that would have incentivized manufacturers to ramp up manufacturing.

01:10:00.560 --> 01:10:06.320
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, manufacturers of other chemical products, for example, to say that let us,

01:10:06.320 --> 01:10:12.200
[Amit Varma]: you know, find a way to make sanitizers for now, because that is where the profit margins

01:10:12.200 --> 01:10:16.640
[Amit Varma]: are. And therefore, what would have happened is that the prices would eventually have gotten

01:10:16.640 --> 01:10:22.240
[Amit Varma]: back to normal, because the supply shortfall would have been met by people incentivized

01:10:22.240 --> 01:10:28.640
[Amit Varma]: by the prices. That's the beauty of prices. They carry information and incentives and

01:10:28.640 --> 01:10:35.360
[Amit Varma]: people simply do not get this. Similarly, why I was kind of appalled by that Supreme

01:10:35.360 --> 01:10:41.520
[Amit Varma]: Court ruling that there should be free, which in my view is basically mass murder. Because

01:10:41.520 --> 01:10:46.120
[Amit Varma]: if you just look at the incentives, you cannot give an order to private people like they

01:10:46.120 --> 01:10:51.000
[Amit Varma]: are your freaking slaves, or that they are your subjects to go back to that, to the term

01:10:51.000 --> 01:10:55.720
[Amit Varma]: we used earlier, they are rational people responding to incentives who need to feed

01:10:55.720 --> 01:11:00.800
[Amit Varma]: their families who need to pay their employees who need to pay the rent of their workplace.

01:11:00.800 --> 01:11:04.720
[Amit Varma]: And there is no way to do that. If they start giving products for free, it doesn't make

01:11:04.720 --> 01:11:10.760
[Amit Varma]: sense. What I vastly prefer is the solution that you have come up with. And that brings

01:11:10.760 --> 01:11:15.760
[Amit Varma]: up issues we will also discuss. What I vastly prefer is that the state figure out a way

01:11:15.760 --> 01:11:21.240
[Amit Varma]: to pay for them. So the incentives of the private players keep working in the right

01:11:21.240 --> 01:11:26.800
[Amit Varma]: direction, that there is something in it for us if we keep manufacturing these. Of course,

01:11:26.800 --> 01:11:33.120
[Amit Varma]: civil society is full of good people who are doing good things for their fellow citizens

01:11:33.120 --> 01:11:38.600
[Amit Varma]: out of the goodness of their heart. That is great. But most of the ways in which we serve

01:11:38.600 --> 01:11:43.240
[Amit Varma]: each other arise out of this sort of self interest. You know, people are not going to

01:11:43.240 --> 01:11:48.400
[Amit Varma]: put sanitizers out in the market out of altruism, they're going to do it because they want to

01:11:48.400 --> 01:11:53.480
[Amit Varma]: make a profit off it. And that's how people will get the sanitizers they need or the masks

01:11:53.480 --> 01:12:00.320
[Amit Varma]: they need, or whatever. And and, you know, and having finished this rant before I move

01:12:00.320 --> 01:12:04.960
[Guest]: on from the rant, by the way, good rant. I mean, if you were in my principles of economic

01:12:04.960 --> 01:12:10.640
[Amit Varma]: class, you would have gotten full points. This is glorious. And I have, of course, learned

01:12:10.640 --> 01:12:17.440
[Amit Varma]: a lot from you over the years in our conversations. So a formal education is not necessary. And

01:12:17.440 --> 01:12:24.720
[Amit Varma]: this brings, I wasn't inviting you to my class summit. Don't worry, just saying well done.

01:12:24.720 --> 01:12:30.300
[Amit Varma]: I would be the classic disruptive backbencher if I did come to your class. But having sort

01:12:30.300 --> 01:12:34.880
[Amit Varma]: of gotten the rant out of the way, I also want to raise another question which has been

01:12:34.880 --> 01:12:39.640
[Amit Varma]: coming up, which is, you and I, of course, are what, you know, people would apply the

01:12:39.640 --> 01:12:45.200
[Amit Varma]: term libertarians to us, I have more and more come to object to that term or any other term,

01:12:45.200 --> 01:12:50.640
[Amit Varma]: because I think that we think too much along tribal lines. So I don't want to be thought

01:12:50.640 --> 01:12:55.120
[Amit Varma]: of as someone who belongs to a particular tribe or otherwise. But one thing that people

01:12:55.120 --> 01:13:01.320
[Amit Varma]: often say and have said during the pandemic is that here is this pandemic, and you are

01:13:01.320 --> 01:13:08.400
[Amit Varma]: supposed to hate the state and like private action, but you are actually a wonder of wonders,

01:13:08.400 --> 01:13:13.000
[Amit Varma]: you are actually promoting coercive action by the state and recommending things like

01:13:13.000 --> 01:13:18.760
[Amit Varma]: a coercive lockdown and so on. And why is that and I briefly want to state my position

01:13:18.760 --> 01:13:24.040
[Amit Varma]: on that and then you know, I'm sure you'll have a deeper more nuanced take on it. But

01:13:24.040 --> 01:13:29.800
[Amit Varma]: my take is simply this, my take is that look, you know, most libertarians would agree that

01:13:29.800 --> 01:13:35.480
[Amit Varma]: the state is necessary for certain reasons. There is the classic liberal paradox that,

01:13:35.480 --> 01:13:39.680
[Amit Varma]: you know, for our rights to have any meaning, we need someone to protect our rights and

01:13:39.680 --> 01:13:43.740
[Amit Varma]: that someone can only be the state to whom we grant the monopoly on violence. And the

01:13:43.740 --> 01:13:49.440
[Amit Varma]: existence of the states means that automatically, some of our rights are being infringed by

01:13:49.440 --> 01:13:55.700
[Amit Varma]: the state itself, that becomes a necessary evil. Now, arguments can be made about how

01:13:55.700 --> 01:13:59.680
[Amit Varma]: big the state should be and what the scope of the state should be. But people like you

01:13:59.680 --> 01:14:05.280
[Amit Varma]: and me would agree that like the state in India is a weak state that does a lot of things

01:14:05.280 --> 01:14:10.320
[Amit Varma]: badly. You and I I think would agree that any ideal state anywhere should be a strong

01:14:10.320 --> 01:14:15.040
[Amit Varma]: state that does a few things very well, but otherwise doesn't interfere much. It's the

01:14:15.040 --> 01:14:21.440
[Amit Varma]: opposite in India. And one of the fundamental core roles of a state is to protect the citizens,

01:14:21.440 --> 01:14:25.760
[Amit Varma]: that is a whole raison d'etre, that is why it exists in the first place, protect the

01:14:25.760 --> 01:14:30.580
[Amit Varma]: citizens, not just from other citizens, which is why you need the rule of law, not just

01:14:30.580 --> 01:14:36.720
[Amit Varma]: from enemy states outside of your geographical borders, which is why you need a defense ministry,

01:14:36.720 --> 01:14:43.320
[Amit Varma]: but also from things like a virus. And this is a classic situation where like you said,

01:14:43.320 --> 01:14:48.040
[Amit Varma]: there is a market failure of sorts, which is natural. And therefore, the state needs

01:14:48.040 --> 01:14:54.080
[Amit Varma]: to step in at this point and sort it out. What would your take be? Is it similar to

01:14:54.080 --> 01:14:57.120
[Guest]: mine or? Quite similar, I would just state it a little

01:14:57.120 --> 01:15:03.400
[Guest]: bit differently. So as a libertarian, or as a classical liberal, to me, that just simply

01:15:03.400 --> 01:15:10.400
[Guest]: means that on the margin, I would favor liberty enhancing measures, and I would walk away

01:15:10.400 --> 01:15:18.200
[Guest]: from coercive measures. So I have a preference for voluntary action over coercive action.

01:15:18.200 --> 01:15:24.120
[Guest]: So that's an ideological framework, that is what I believe in. Many people don't believe

01:15:24.120 --> 01:15:28.960
[Guest]: in that for various reasons, we can debate that later. Now, it just so happens that a

01:15:28.960 --> 01:15:35.440
[Guest]: lot of voluntary action is negotiated very, very well through the market. Not all of it,

01:15:35.440 --> 01:15:40.880
[Guest]: but a lot of it. And by this, this is the classic Adam Smith version of the market,

01:15:40.880 --> 01:15:48.040
[Guest]: which is, it is an institution which aligns self-interest with social interest beautifully.

01:15:48.040 --> 01:15:52.740
[Guest]: So going back to your hand sanitizer example, people may be selling hand sanitizer to make

01:15:52.740 --> 01:15:56.920
[Guest]: a quick buck because the price increased, but in the process, they are supplying an

01:15:56.920 --> 01:16:01.520
[Guest]: extremely valuable commodity in the midst of a global pandemic to the people who need

01:16:01.520 --> 01:16:06.160
[Guest]: it the most, right? And they are doing it not out of their benevolence, they're doing

01:16:06.160 --> 01:16:11.900
[Guest]: it probably out of their self-interest to make money. But in the process, they are serving

01:16:11.900 --> 01:16:18.040
[Guest]: people who actually come and become their customers. So the market, nine out of 10 times

01:16:18.040 --> 01:16:24.040
[Guest]: does a great job aligning self-interest with social interest. And in the marketplace, more

01:16:24.040 --> 01:16:30.760
[Guest]: often than not, private costs and social costs tend to be similar. Now, as you and I have

01:16:30.760 --> 01:16:36.160
[Guest]: talked about this before, there are cases where that doesn't happen. And these are classic

01:16:36.160 --> 01:16:41.480
[Guest]: externality cases where we say there is a market failure, right? Air pollution is something

01:16:41.480 --> 01:16:45.760
[Guest]: you and I have talked about before, which is a classic market failure, where it is in

01:16:45.760 --> 01:16:53.040
[Guest]: each person's interest or incentive to pollute. But the overall outcome is so far beyond what

01:16:53.040 --> 01:16:58.280
[Guest]: the social cost of it is so far beyond what the private cost of each person breathing

01:16:58.280 --> 01:17:04.120
[Guest]: in that same air that there is a huge, huge externality problem. Now, let's come to the

01:17:04.120 --> 01:17:09.480
[Guest]: pandemic. We have a very, very similar market failure in the pandemic. And frankly, because

01:17:09.480 --> 01:17:13.800
[Guest]: we are still in an epistemic fog, and we don't know how bad it is or how bad it could be

01:17:13.800 --> 01:17:20.920
[Guest]: or which groups it affects the most. We just don't even fully realize what that social

01:17:20.920 --> 01:17:26.040
[Guest]: cost could be. But we at least understand conceptually that the social cost deviates

01:17:26.040 --> 01:17:29.800
[Guest]: from the private cost that is much bigger than the private cost, that there could be

01:17:29.800 --> 01:17:33.920
[Guest]: people who are asymptomatic who go around spreading this, right? That there could be

01:17:33.920 --> 01:17:38.480
[Guest]: people who are symptomatic, but because of economic desperation, or some other problem,

01:17:38.480 --> 01:17:44.560
[Guest]: are out and about working and they inadvertently spread it. So there is a question of a classic

01:17:44.560 --> 01:17:49.480
[Guest]: market failure problem. You know, we've met the market failure. So when it comes to a

01:17:49.480 --> 01:17:53.760
[Guest]: market failure, yes, you need some kind of government action. But we have to realize

01:17:53.760 --> 01:17:59.600
[Guest]: that the government is not perfect. And even when we invite government action to correct

01:17:59.600 --> 01:18:03.880
[Guest]: market failure, we need to think about the incentive problems of the government and we

01:18:03.880 --> 01:18:08.120
[Guest]: need to think about the knowledge problems of the government, right? And those are two

01:18:08.120 --> 01:18:14.560
[Guest]: margins where if we can streamline incentives, well, things would be better. So for instance,

01:18:14.560 --> 01:18:18.000
[Guest]: when it comes to the knowledge problem of governments, we you and I already talked about

01:18:18.000 --> 01:18:22.960
[Guest]: how this is best done at the most local level, which is the municipal or the panchayati raj

01:18:22.960 --> 01:18:28.160
[Guest]: level because they have the most knowledge because what is happening in Dharavi is completely

01:18:28.160 --> 01:18:32.900
[Guest]: different from what is happening in Sikkim, right? And so that is one way of thinking

01:18:32.900 --> 01:18:40.600
[Guest]: about how do we further fine tune align the government structure such that it can respond

01:18:40.600 --> 01:18:44.560
[Guest]: with the least amount of failure with the most amount of success while correcting a

01:18:44.560 --> 01:18:51.720
[Guest]: market failure, right? The second is the incentives, which is things like you sort of talked about

01:18:51.720 --> 01:18:56.960
[Guest]: this in your introduction, which is people are going to be blamed in government no matter

01:18:56.960 --> 01:19:03.040
[Guest]: what, right? So there are incentives to think about what kind of risk averse measures would

01:19:03.040 --> 01:19:09.800
[Guest]: one be more likely to take. So one is most people who are working, who are IAS officers

01:19:09.800 --> 01:19:14.000
[Guest]: and who are formulating policy on this, they're fairly well off, they're part of the elite.

01:19:14.000 --> 01:19:18.880
[Guest]: They have CGHS, you know, which is a central government health scheme. They're never going

01:19:18.880 --> 01:19:23.120
[Guest]: to go to a terrible hospital for treatment. They're fairly well protected. They have piped

01:19:23.120 --> 01:19:28.280
[Guest]: water and all of those things. Maybe they will err on the side of social distancing

01:19:28.280 --> 01:19:34.040
[Guest]: policy, which they can follow, but no one else can follow, right? Or if someone like

01:19:34.040 --> 01:19:39.520
[Guest]: me is formulating policy, for instance, I have a grandfather who's 102 years old. He's

01:19:39.520 --> 01:19:45.360
[Guest]: in good health, knock on wood, but he's 102 years old. He is one of the highest risk category

01:19:45.360 --> 01:19:51.120
[Guest]: of people in this kind of a situation. Now, someone like me, if I were the chair of a

01:19:51.120 --> 01:19:57.040
[Guest]: bureaucrat might impose too harsh a lockdown because the person who is, who I'm trying

01:19:57.040 --> 01:20:03.480
[Guest]: to protect is someone like my grandfather and I'm elite and I'm comfortable and I really

01:20:03.480 --> 01:20:09.480
[Guest]: don't care about, you know, what is going to happen to migrant labor or daily wage labor.

01:20:09.480 --> 01:20:15.400
[Guest]: So there are incentives to think about. Are the incentives aligned such that you impose

01:20:15.400 --> 01:20:21.040
[Guest]: the least amount of total costs on your citizens or are they aligned such that you sort of,

01:20:21.040 --> 01:20:25.120
[Guest]: you know, protect your own back, serve your own interests, even if they're personal interests

01:20:25.120 --> 01:20:30.200
[Guest]: and impose a lot of social costs, either because you had too stringent a lockdown or no lockdown

01:20:30.200 --> 01:20:36.240
[Guest]: at all, right? So these are some of the things to think about even while we wear our libertarian

01:20:36.240 --> 01:20:43.720
[Guest]: hat. So overall, we want the system to be as, you know, voluntary based and low in coercion

01:20:43.720 --> 01:20:48.320
[Guest]: as possible. But I'm afraid, I'm sorry to all the libertarians out there, we've met

01:20:48.320 --> 01:20:54.600
[Guest]: our market failure. So we need to do something and we have the government that we have. So

01:20:54.600 --> 01:21:00.440
[Guest]: we need to put on our public choice, political economy hats and try and think about minimizing

01:21:00.440 --> 01:21:06.000
[Guest]: government failure and minimizing government overreach every time on the margin. We can't

01:21:06.000 --> 01:21:07.000
[Guest]: do anything systemically.

01:21:07.000 --> 01:21:12.440
[Amit Varma]: I agree with everything, first of all. And, and the interesting, the dilemma that I can't

01:21:12.440 --> 01:21:18.160
[Amit Varma]: find a resolution for in my head is what you just said, that if you look at it, the extension

01:21:18.160 --> 01:21:22.640
[Amit Varma]: of the lockdown, you know, which by the way, I think is a perfectly fine decision. I don't

01:21:22.640 --> 01:21:26.640
[Amit Varma]: have an argument with it. But quite apart from the goodness or the badness of that,

01:21:26.640 --> 01:21:30.720
[Amit Varma]: which we will never know, because, you know, there'll be so much that remains unseen for

01:21:30.720 --> 01:21:35.240
[Amit Varma]: decades about the costs and the benefits. But the extension of the lockdown was almost

01:21:35.240 --> 01:21:40.920
[Amit Varma]: a political inevitability, because, you know, the politicians would be able to cover their

01:21:40.920 --> 01:21:45.200
[Amit Varma]: ass and say that, look, we are doing better than the rest of the world, because we put

01:21:45.200 --> 01:21:49.560
[Amit Varma]: this lockdown in place, which is surely partly true. And therefore, we got to do more of

01:21:49.560 --> 01:21:54.400
[Amit Varma]: it. And also because of people who will be worst hurt, the people who are really affected

01:21:54.400 --> 01:21:58.800
[Amit Varma]: by this, like the migrant laborers and all of that, are not such an influential voice

01:21:58.800 --> 01:22:04.440
[Amit Varma]: in politics. I don't imagine migrant laborers anywhere really count as a vote bank and certainly

01:22:04.440 --> 01:22:11.040
[Amit Varma]: not as influential interest groups. So they will always be the ones who get shafted.

01:22:11.040 --> 01:22:18.720
[Guest]: Yeah, so I will say one thing, I think the lockdown is a failure. Okay. The lockdown

01:22:18.720 --> 01:22:25.320
[Guest]: would be successful only if you use the period of the lockdown to build up healthcare capacity,

01:22:25.320 --> 01:22:31.480
[Guest]: so that when you reopen the economy slowly and steadily, you need to flatten the curve

01:22:31.480 --> 01:22:36.160
[Guest]: a little bit less than five weeks ago. That was the whole point of the lockdown. Because

01:22:36.160 --> 01:22:41.040
[Guest]: if you don't build up healthcare capacity during the lockdown, then whenever you reopen

01:22:41.040 --> 01:22:45.440
[Guest]: the economy, you're in the exact same conundrum, which means technically you can never reopen

01:22:45.440 --> 01:22:50.900
[Guest]: the economy. So we closed things down March 24. We have no greater healthcare capacity

01:22:50.900 --> 01:22:58.040
[Guest]: today on April 17 than we had on March 24, which means we wasted a month with huge economic

01:22:58.040 --> 01:23:05.560
[Guest]: costs and no immediate sight into when we can open things. So in that sense, I think

01:23:05.560 --> 01:23:12.120
[Guest]: the lockdown is a complete and total failure, because I don't think the government understood

01:23:12.120 --> 01:23:16.320
[Guest]: that at the end of the lockdown, whenever the time comes to open the economy, there

01:23:16.320 --> 01:23:22.440
[Guest]: will be transmission, right? So there seems to be no policy around that. I have not seen

01:23:22.440 --> 01:23:28.640
[Guest]: any state other than Kerala, at this point, trying to seriously build up healthcare capacity.

01:23:28.640 --> 01:23:33.200
[Guest]: What states are doing is just suppressing, right? And they're like in panic situations

01:23:33.200 --> 01:23:38.400
[Guest]: with firefighting. So Maharashtra is firefighting. We're trying to contain the problem in slums.

01:23:38.400 --> 01:23:43.040
[Guest]: We're trying to do contact tracing. We're trying to do testing. So all of those things

01:23:43.040 --> 01:23:48.180
[Guest]: are very important, and they're great that we're doing that. But at the end of the day,

01:23:48.180 --> 01:23:51.360
[Guest]: if you don't increase the number of hospital beds, and you don't increase the number of

01:23:51.360 --> 01:23:56.920
[Guest]: tests and private labs, and pharmaceutical firms which are producing medicines, then

01:23:56.920 --> 01:24:00.880
[Guest]: you can never get out of the lockdown, right? It's never going to be a good time to get

01:24:00.880 --> 01:24:05.200
[Guest]: out. So I will disagree with you a little bit in that I think the lockdown is a good

01:24:05.200 --> 01:24:09.640
[Guest]: idea because we have no other choice. But I also recognize that the lockdown is a failure

01:24:09.640 --> 01:24:13.720
[Guest]: because the most important thing, you know, union and state government should have done

01:24:13.720 --> 01:24:17.840
[Guest]: during the lockdown. I don't see that happening other than two or three different states.

01:24:17.840 --> 01:24:21.520
[Amit Varma]: No, I agree with you on the fact that these are all the things we needed to do during

01:24:21.520 --> 01:24:26.160
[Amit Varma]: the lockdown. And I had actually suspended judgment on that because I don't think there's

01:24:26.160 --> 01:24:31.520
[Amit Varma]: enough information available to me to know whether that capacity is being built. I would

01:24:31.520 --> 01:24:36.960
[Amit Varma]: have thought it a no brainer. I know that there are lots of very smart people on advisory

01:24:36.960 --> 01:24:42.200
[Amit Varma]: panels advising the government. But yes, there is that epistemic fog. And if they haven't

01:24:42.200 --> 01:24:47.960
[Amit Varma]: actually put those extra beds in place or ramped up the production of masks, because

01:24:47.960 --> 01:24:52.360
[Amit Varma]: honestly, when the lockdown ends, every freaking Indian has to be wearing a mask outdoors.

01:24:52.360 --> 01:24:56.080
[Amit Varma]: You know, if you haven't ramped up ventilators, then I agree with you, it's pointless.

01:24:56.080 --> 01:25:00.400
[Guest]: I'll tell you what happened in India, there will be a government mandate that says everyone

01:25:00.400 --> 01:25:04.960
[Guest]: has to wear a mask in public. We don't have enough masks, which means some poor person

01:25:04.960 --> 01:25:08.800
[Guest]: is going to be out and about without a mask looking for food or medicines. And then the

01:25:08.800 --> 01:25:14.480
[Guest]: police will beat that person up. Right? So this is the way we execute things in India

01:25:14.480 --> 01:25:19.200
[Guest]: without realizing that you can't just dictate from the top. It's not, there's no Akshaya

01:25:19.200 --> 01:25:24.400
[Guest]: Patra. Okay. You can't say we want masks and masks will just magically appear. You need

01:25:24.400 --> 01:25:28.800
[Guest]: to incentivize the private sector. You need to say there's an essential good, let's produce

01:25:28.800 --> 01:25:33.320
[Guest]: masks, right? You need to say we will pay for every single person's mask who cannot

01:25:33.320 --> 01:25:39.160
[Guest]: afford it. Masks are very cheap compared to private tests and hospital beds and things

01:25:39.160 --> 01:25:45.020
[Guest]: like that. So civil society can help in a huge way, but we still need to have some kind

01:25:45.020 --> 01:25:49.760
[Guest]: of a signal that here we need more masks. So we don't have that yet. I mentioned this

01:25:49.760 --> 01:25:54.480
[Guest]: before the, you know, we have testing kits, which we've imported, which are just sitting

01:25:54.480 --> 01:26:00.900
[Guest]: waiting for customs clearance, waiting for approvals from the drug controller, right?

01:26:00.900 --> 01:26:06.400
[Guest]: We still have import duties on a whole number of things. Very recently, the finance minister,

01:26:06.400 --> 01:26:12.400
[Guest]: thankfully in a wonderful move, suspended import duties on medical equipment. But we

01:26:12.400 --> 01:26:18.840
[Guest]: just have a supply side problem on each of these things. And until we remove the roadblocks

01:26:18.840 --> 01:26:23.920
[Guest]: for the supply side problem, we won't get an increase in supply on any of the essential

01:26:23.920 --> 01:26:29.680
[Guest]: goods, which either help mitigate the problem, like, you know, hand sanitizers and masks,

01:26:29.680 --> 01:26:33.420
[Guest]: or help treat the problem like hospital beds and ventilators.

01:26:33.420 --> 01:26:38.160
[Amit Varma]: And you, in fact, recently wrote a column, which could easily have been titled the seen

01:26:38.160 --> 01:26:43.160
[Amit Varma]: and the unseen. It referred to Bastia and his famous essay from which I got the title

01:26:43.160 --> 01:26:49.680
[Amit Varma]: of the show and it repeated to you. Thank you. Great honor. I dedicate this show and

01:26:49.680 --> 01:26:55.400
[Amit Varma]: your dedication to me, to Frederick Bastia himself, one of my 19th century heroes whose

01:26:55.400 --> 01:26:59.840
[Amit Varma]: masterpiece The Law I think everyone should read and all his essays. In fact, they will

01:26:59.840 --> 01:27:05.080
[Amit Varma]: be linked from the show notes. But meanwhile, can you sort of quickly shed light on some

01:27:05.080 --> 01:27:10.040
[Amit Varma]: of the seen and the unseen effects of the pandemic because I just found it so delightful.

01:27:10.040 --> 01:27:16.880
[Guest]: Oh, yeah. So you know, the classic example that Bastia gives when he talks about the

01:27:16.880 --> 01:27:22.640
[Guest]: seen and the unseen effects is the broken window example, right? So the folklore goes

01:27:22.640 --> 01:27:27.720
[Guest]: such that, you know, you break a window of a tailoring shop and people say that, oh,

01:27:27.720 --> 01:27:32.720
[Guest]: this is wonderful because it's going to stimulate the economy because now someone has to spend

01:27:32.720 --> 01:27:38.360
[Guest]: money to repair the broken window, which means the glass manufacturers and the window installer

01:27:38.360 --> 01:27:43.880
[Guest]: and all these people will, will make money and it will stimulate the economy. So that's

01:27:43.880 --> 01:27:49.280
[Guest]: the seen effect. The unseen effect is that had the window not been broken, there would

01:27:49.280 --> 01:27:54.280
[Guest]: have been more money in the pocket of the tailoring facility. And maybe they could have

01:27:54.280 --> 01:27:58.880
[Guest]: employed another employee. And maybe they could have bought another sewing machine.

01:27:58.880 --> 01:28:04.240
[Guest]: And that would have stimulated a whole number of other important areas in the economy. And

01:28:04.240 --> 01:28:10.360
[Guest]: it would have been a valuable, you know, spending of resources towards things that people actually

01:28:10.360 --> 01:28:15.000
[Guest]: want rather than just breaking a window and repairing it. So breaking a window and repairing

01:28:15.000 --> 01:28:19.040
[Guest]: it was a useful thing. We can keep stimulating the economy that way, right? But we know that

01:28:19.040 --> 01:28:24.200
[Guest]: it's not, it's a wasteful thing. So the scene effect and the unseen effect are quite different.

01:28:24.200 --> 01:28:29.760
[Guest]: Now, this is just one of the many, many examples that Bastia talks about. In my column, I was

01:28:29.760 --> 01:28:36.040
[Guest]: talking about import tariffs specifically. So as I mentioned, we have very high import

01:28:36.040 --> 01:28:41.280
[Guest]: tariffs more generally. And in the case of medical equipment, they are somewhere between

01:28:41.280 --> 01:28:46.160
[Guest]: say 12% and 26%, depending on, you know, the CES is applied and what you're talking about

01:28:46.160 --> 01:28:53.400
[Guest]: exactly. The testing kits, many of them are 26% tariff is applied to them. Now, as we

01:28:53.400 --> 01:28:59.400
[Guest]: know, the reason, the ostensible reason given for import tariffs is that they protect domestic

01:28:59.400 --> 01:29:06.280
[Guest]: industry, right? And the way they protect domestic industry is because the domestic

01:29:06.280 --> 01:29:12.160
[Guest]: industry is not as competitive. And what we mean by competitive is it doesn't produce,

01:29:12.160 --> 01:29:17.760
[Guest]: say testing kits with the lowest number of resources available, right? It doesn't, it's

01:29:17.760 --> 01:29:23.920
[Guest]: more costly than people who do it abroad. But we still want to encourage domestic industry

01:29:23.920 --> 01:29:30.360
[Guest]: even though they don't produce as effectively or as cheaply. In the process, we put in a

01:29:30.360 --> 01:29:38.120
[Guest]: tariff and any foreign supplier who is selling to India is going to have a higher price presented

01:29:38.120 --> 01:29:43.280
[Guest]: to the consumer. So the consumer, if they can buy from the domestic person at a hundred

01:29:43.280 --> 01:29:48.920
[Guest]: rupees for the same thing, we'll have to pay 126 rupees to the foreign supplier. So the

01:29:48.920 --> 01:29:54.400
[Guest]: domestic supplier seems cheap in comparison. These things are typically put in when the

01:29:54.400 --> 01:30:01.360
[Guest]: domestic producer makes testing kits available at say 120 rupees, right? The foreign supplier

01:30:01.360 --> 01:30:07.240
[Guest]: makes it available at a hundred rupees. So the 26 rupee tariff is going to make the domestic

01:30:07.240 --> 01:30:11.960
[Guest]: producer seem slightly cheaper on the margin or make them more competitive on the margin.

01:30:11.960 --> 01:30:16.200
[Guest]: Now this is encouraged saying that the domestic producer will use local resources. They will

01:30:16.200 --> 01:30:21.040
[Guest]: employ local people and all of those good things. So that's the scene effect. The unseen

01:30:21.040 --> 01:30:26.080
[Guest]: effect is that every single individual and lab in the country, which is buying a testing

01:30:26.080 --> 01:30:32.040
[Guest]: kit is spending an extra 26 rupees that they could have spent on other things. They could

01:30:32.040 --> 01:30:36.280
[Guest]: have spent that extra 26 rupees on a mask. They could have spent that extra 26 rupees

01:30:36.280 --> 01:30:40.200
[Guest]: on food. If they had a lot of money sloshing around in their pockets, they could have given

01:30:40.200 --> 01:30:47.720
[Guest]: that 26 rupees to someone who needed it desperately. And now all that money is spent, you know,

01:30:47.720 --> 01:30:53.640
[Guest]: sort of propping up a domestic producer because they weren't as competitive as a foreign producer.

01:30:53.640 --> 01:30:58.840
[Guest]: Now normally we tolerate all of this under the guise of patriotism. And the whole problem

01:30:58.840 --> 01:31:05.520
[Guest]: is presented as a tax on the foreign supplier, you know, vis-a-vis the domestic supplier.

01:31:05.520 --> 01:31:10.800
[Guest]: So we're, we're taxing foreigners. We're hurting foreigners. We're protecting Indians. But

01:31:10.800 --> 01:31:17.280
[Guest]: the unseen effect is we are hurting the Indian consumer to protect the Indian producer. And

01:31:17.280 --> 01:31:22.040
[Guest]: in this particular instance, normally this unseen effect, you know, is not visible. In

01:31:22.040 --> 01:31:26.880
[Guest]: this particular instance of the COVID crisis, it has become extremely visible because in

01:31:26.880 --> 01:31:34.560
[Guest]: this case, the domestic consumer are people who desperately need a test or are sick, who

01:31:34.560 --> 01:31:39.760
[Guest]: will die waiting for a test or will transmit the virus to other people. And the producer

01:31:39.760 --> 01:31:44.880
[Guest]: is, you know, some manufacturer. Now suddenly the tables are a little bit turned. We're

01:31:44.880 --> 01:31:50.520
[Guest]: like, Oh, we're literally going to kill people while waiting for a test because we're not

01:31:50.520 --> 01:31:56.820
[Guest]: allowing them to import foreign tests, which are more cheap and competitive and available

01:31:56.820 --> 01:32:02.160
[Guest]: in larger quantities than the domestic manufacturers. So this is one instance where the pandemic

01:32:02.160 --> 01:32:07.960
[Guest]: has made a traditionally unseen effect seen. And in fact, the result became so visible

01:32:07.960 --> 01:32:12.400
[Guest]: that even the government has taken notice. So the finance ministry, I believe on April

01:32:12.400 --> 01:32:18.440
[Guest]: 9th, issued a notification saying that until September 30th, they're going to suspend all

01:32:18.440 --> 01:32:24.120
[Guest]: import tariffs on medical equipment and masks and ventilators and testing kits. And also

01:32:24.120 --> 01:32:28.520
[Guest]: on the inputs that go into these, you know, the various equipments, because for ventilators,

01:32:28.520 --> 01:32:32.200
[Guest]: we actually import a lot of different parts, but we might assemble it in India. So it's

01:32:32.200 --> 01:32:37.160
[Guest]: important to also think about inputs. So the government actually made this change. So it

01:32:37.160 --> 01:32:44.100
[Guest]: was a remarkable thing where a traditionally unseen effect has become visible. And thankfully,

01:32:44.100 --> 01:32:51.080
[Guest]: we have made one step towards greater trade, lesser coercion, and fewer transfer of resources

01:32:51.080 --> 01:32:54.720
[Amit Varma]: from consumers to producers. You know, I want to rant a little bit about this because this

01:32:54.720 --> 01:33:02.080
[Amit Varma]: really makes me angry. I think import duties, all import duties without exception, are immoral.

01:33:02.080 --> 01:33:05.760
[Amit Varma]: They are an attack on the people of your own country. And I want to talk a little bit about

01:33:05.760 --> 01:33:10.960
[Amit Varma]: this. I'll go back to your example. Let's say that there is a sanitizer that a domestic

01:33:10.960 --> 01:33:15.760
[Amit Varma]: producer can make for a hundred and twenty rupees. And you know, a company outside, maybe

01:33:15.760 --> 01:33:20.780
[Amit Varma]: in China or wherever, can make for a hundred bucks. I, the consumer, can now get it for

01:33:20.780 --> 01:33:26.080
[Amit Varma]: a hundred bucks if there are no import duties. You put an import duty of 26%, 26 rupees,

01:33:26.080 --> 01:33:31.160
[Amit Varma]: that is 126. I have to buy from the local guy for 120. What is happening here? One,

01:33:31.160 --> 01:33:36.480
[Amit Varma]: as you pointed out, the unseen effect is that that 20 rupees that I would have saved would

01:33:36.480 --> 01:33:40.560
[Amit Varma]: have gone back into the economy. I would have spent it on something else. It would have

01:33:40.560 --> 01:33:44.960
[Amit Varma]: been put to productive use in the economy. It would have generated jobs, which would

01:33:44.960 --> 01:33:51.400
[Amit Varma]: have been productive jobs and, you know, more than made up for the loss of whatever the

01:33:51.400 --> 01:33:55.880
[Amit Varma]: domestic industry would be. But secondly, and I want to phrase it like this, what the

01:33:55.880 --> 01:34:01.960
[Amit Varma]: government did with an import duty was it redistributed money from the poor to the rich.

01:34:01.960 --> 01:34:07.760
[Amit Varma]: What happened was that the poor consumer at large lost 20 rupees. It was coerced away

01:34:07.760 --> 01:34:12.660
[Amit Varma]: from him by this government regulation and given to a rich interest group of domestic

01:34:12.660 --> 01:34:17.800
[Amit Varma]: manufacturers. And the rich interest groups of domestic manufacturer then spends a chunk

01:34:17.800 --> 01:34:22.600
[Amit Varma]: of that lobbying the government or bribing the government to pass the import duty in

01:34:22.600 --> 01:34:28.240
[Amit Varma]: the first place. This is the circle that we need to watch out for. You know, the crony

01:34:28.240 --> 01:34:35.040
[Amit Varma]: capitalist using the power of the state to redistribute money from the poor to the rich.

01:34:35.040 --> 01:34:40.200
[Amit Varma]: And this happens in so many different ways. All protectionism, all protectionism is like

01:34:40.200 --> 01:34:45.600
[Amit Varma]: this, you know, restricting, for example, FDI on retail, which so many of the parties

01:34:45.600 --> 01:34:50.320
[Amit Varma]: have been for is another example of that. And they are always couched in rhetoric of

01:34:50.320 --> 01:34:55.240
[Amit Varma]: who we are helping the domestic manufacturer. But listen, markets exist for the benefit

01:34:55.240 --> 01:35:01.040
[Amit Varma]: of consumers, for the benefits of citizens. And all of this amounts to redistribution

01:35:01.040 --> 01:35:06.080
[Amit Varma]: from the poor to the rich. And therefore, I hope that in time now that we have come

01:35:06.080 --> 01:35:12.400
[Amit Varma]: to see the evil effects of these import duties, that in time, you know, we begin to cut down

01:35:12.400 --> 01:35:13.880
[Amit Varma]: on import duties altogether.

01:35:13.880 --> 01:35:19.640
[Guest]: I like one more thing. You said we are transferring from the poor to the rich, which is incredibly

01:35:19.640 --> 01:35:24.080
[Guest]: true in a country like India, where you know, large number of consumers have pretty much

01:35:24.080 --> 01:35:29.200
[Guest]: anything tend to be poorer than the manufacturers. The other thing is we're distributing from

01:35:29.200 --> 01:35:34.800
[Guest]: a very large number of people to a very small concentration. Right. And that is also the

01:35:34.800 --> 01:35:39.120
[Guest]: reason why some of these things persist. So it's very difficult for a large number of

01:35:39.120 --> 01:35:46.240
[Guest]: citizens, you know, maybe a hundred thousand people in India need one of the medical equipment

01:35:46.240 --> 01:35:50.560
[Guest]: or, you know, a mask or something that we're talking about. And it's very difficult for

01:35:50.560 --> 01:35:56.200
[Guest]: them to coordinate and say, hey, you're robbing us of 20 rupees each. And it's much easier

01:35:56.200 --> 01:36:02.440
[Guest]: for the six or seven manufacturers to coordinate and say, oh, we're going to get 20 rupees

01:36:02.440 --> 01:36:07.800
[Guest]: additional from, you know, a hundred thousand consumers out there, and we can split it amongst

01:36:07.800 --> 01:36:12.640
[Guest]: the five of us. So now how do we lobby the government? So this is a classic case of concentrated

01:36:12.640 --> 01:36:17.240
[Guest]: benefits and diffused costs, which is why many of these things exist. So it's not just

01:36:17.240 --> 01:36:22.520
[Guest]: a transfer from the poor to the rich, which is a morally bankrupt situation. But the reason

01:36:22.520 --> 01:36:27.480
[Guest]: why they persist is also it's a transfer from a very large number of people who pay a small

01:36:27.480 --> 01:36:31.480
[Guest]: fraction to a very small number of people who gain a large fraction.

01:36:31.480 --> 01:36:37.640
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And in fact, to add to that, I'd also point out that the cost is unseen in the sense

01:36:37.640 --> 01:36:42.240
[Amit Varma]: that I, as a consumer, don't know the cost that I would have saved had the import duty

01:36:42.240 --> 01:36:46.920
[Amit Varma]: not in place. I, for example, as a consumer certainly pay something every year for to

01:36:46.920 --> 01:36:50.920
[Amit Varma]: keep Air India afloat. You know, I have paid something in the past to have these giant

01:36:50.920 --> 01:36:55.680
[Amit Varma]: statues built, but I don't know what it is. It is unseen to me. And even if I knew what

01:36:55.680 --> 01:36:59.920
[Amit Varma]: it was that, hey, Amit, you're spending a hundred rupees every year on Air India, and

01:36:59.920 --> 01:37:04.200
[Amit Varma]: you know, a hundred rupees each on a million things like that. For the sake of that one

01:37:04.200 --> 01:37:08.880
[Amit Varma]: hundred rupees, I would not be able to get together with all other citizens. It would

01:37:08.880 --> 01:37:12.840
[Amit Varma]: not be incentive enough to actually spend so much time and effort. But for the person

01:37:12.840 --> 01:37:16.920
[Amit Varma]: who is gaining from it, for Air India, it's very easy to then lobby the government.

01:37:16.920 --> 01:37:18.400
[Guest]: They're unionized employees.

01:37:18.400 --> 01:37:25.360
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, exactly. Who are, you know, subsisting on this coercion. But, you know, sort of,

01:37:25.360 --> 01:37:28.640
[Amit Varma]: let's go back. And your column, of course, has more examples of this. And it's a beautiful

01:37:28.640 --> 01:37:32.400
[Amit Varma]: column. I'll link it from the show notes. I wish I had written it.

01:37:32.400 --> 01:37:37.760
[Guest]: All columns dedicated to Amit Verma are beautiful columns.

01:37:37.760 --> 01:37:42.680
[Amit Varma]: This is the first column ever that has been dedicated to me, but thank you so much. It

01:37:42.680 --> 01:37:45.080
[Amit Varma]: should be dedicated to Bastia, not to me.

01:37:45.080 --> 01:37:51.800
[Guest]: No, no. Yes, I do mention Bastia in the column. But a conversation with you got me thinking

01:37:51.800 --> 01:37:58.040
[Guest]: about this. So Amit and I had chatted sometime in the morning, just before I started working

01:37:58.040 --> 01:38:02.360
[Guest]: on the column. And something Amit said to me, you know, got me thinking in that direction.

01:38:02.360 --> 01:38:07.520
[Guest]: And I was already thinking about import duties. And I was like, very frustrated with the fact

01:38:07.520 --> 01:38:11.840
[Guest]: that there are testing kits stuck at ports because the drug controller has not approved

01:38:11.840 --> 01:38:16.040
[Guest]: it and, you know, things like that. So that's what instigated me to write this, which is

01:38:16.040 --> 01:38:20.840
[Guest]: why it is dedicated to Amit. Yes, all great ideas. We are all riding on the coattails

01:38:20.840 --> 01:38:21.840
[Guest]: of Bastia.

01:38:21.840 --> 01:38:26.080
[Amit Varma]: We are riding on the coattails of Bastia. And at this point, I must point out, I must

01:38:26.080 --> 01:38:31.080
[Amit Varma]: retrospectively dedicate my last column to you, because it was about the flailing state.

01:38:31.080 --> 01:38:36.160
[Amit Varma]: And of course, I first learned about that great 2009 paper by Land Pritchett because

01:38:36.160 --> 01:38:41.880
[Amit Varma]: of you, you introduced me to that paper. And I want to now sort of turn to that the argument

01:38:41.880 --> 01:38:47.000
[Amit Varma]: I made in that column, which will be linked in the show notes, is basically that this

01:38:47.000 --> 01:38:53.320
[Amit Varma]: temporal passing, hopefully passing disaster of COVID-19 has also shed light on a deeper

01:38:53.320 --> 01:38:57.800
[Amit Varma]: underlying disaster, which we have completely normalized, which is a failure of the Indian

01:38:57.800 --> 01:39:02.640
[Amit Varma]: state. The term Land Pritchett used for it was flailing state, which is when, you know,

01:39:02.640 --> 01:39:07.640
[Amit Varma]: the head of the state, the brain of the state has no connection with any of the bodily organs,

01:39:07.640 --> 01:39:12.080
[Amit Varma]: which we have actually seen in practice, where after the lockdown was actually called, there

01:39:12.080 --> 01:39:16.380
[Amit Varma]: was so much police brutality across the country, because they simply hadn't got the instructions

01:39:16.380 --> 01:39:23.280
[Amit Varma]: that essential services to be kept open, people can go out to buy food, etc, etc. And the

01:39:23.280 --> 01:39:29.160
[Amit Varma]: larger point I was making, and again, something that I get emotive about and feel strongly

01:39:29.160 --> 01:39:33.960
[Amit Varma]: about is that, you know, there has been a huge, not just state failure, but moral failure

01:39:33.960 --> 01:39:38.600
[Amit Varma]: over the last 70 years. And what we have done to a poor in the fact that we are still a

01:39:38.600 --> 01:39:44.440
[Amit Varma]: poor country 72 years after independence, I think the a couple of the stats I cited

01:39:44.440 --> 01:39:52.880
[Amit Varma]: in my column is that every day, every day in India, 3000 children die of starvation

01:39:52.880 --> 01:39:57.200
[Amit Varma]: of not getting enough food, one fourth of all Indian children are malnourished. And

01:39:57.200 --> 01:40:01.280
[Amit Varma]: honestly, you know, I can cite figures from various fields, you can look around you look

01:40:01.280 --> 01:40:06.240
[Amit Varma]: what is being done to our farmers, you look what is being done to our women, you know,

01:40:06.240 --> 01:40:12.520
[Amit Varma]: perennial second class citizens, and a layer of pain that lies beneath every other crisis

01:40:12.520 --> 01:40:17.440
[Amit Varma]: that you can name, whether it's a jobs crisis or the farming crisis. And all of this points

01:40:17.440 --> 01:40:24.360
[Amit Varma]: to sort of the failure of the state and the way in which society runs itself despite the

01:40:24.360 --> 01:40:29.440
[Amit Varma]: state, as we have seen in all the volunteer efforts coming out, coming up across the country

01:40:29.440 --> 01:40:36.040
[Amit Varma]: to help the migrant laborers just to take a small example. Now, my sort of related question

01:40:36.040 --> 01:40:43.040
[Amit Varma]: and is that, look, you know, you and I would both agree that part of this failure lies

01:40:43.040 --> 01:40:48.000
[Amit Varma]: in the way that we think about it, that we think as men of system to use Adam Smith's

01:40:48.000 --> 01:40:53.640
[Amit Varma]: term. And we think in paternalistic terms, that if we give handouts and all of that,

01:40:53.640 --> 01:40:58.240
[Amit Varma]: then we can solve the problem of poverty, which is how we know that it cannot be solved

01:40:58.240 --> 01:41:03.640
[Amit Varma]: that we know that there is, you know, a disconnect between there is a trade off between growth

01:41:03.640 --> 01:41:09.440
[Amit Varma]: and redistribution. And that 1% of GDP growth lifts 2 million people out of poverty, that

01:41:09.440 --> 01:41:14.920
[Amit Varma]: economic freedom and allowing society to function well is the biggest driver of growth and therefore

01:41:14.920 --> 01:41:22.000
[Amit Varma]: of people coming out of poverty and paternalistic policies have a very limited impact. Now,

01:41:22.000 --> 01:41:30.040
[Amit Varma]: in terms of dealing with the current COVID-19 crisis, you have proposed as a short term

01:41:30.040 --> 01:41:36.600
[Amit Varma]: measure, a number of policies which otherwise we would frown upon as paternalistic and,

01:41:36.600 --> 01:41:42.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, giving a man a fish instead of teaching him how to fish, for example, a time bound

01:41:42.040 --> 01:41:48.440
[Amit Varma]: UBI. So explain to me your thinking on this, that, you know, policies which we would never

01:41:48.440 --> 01:41:55.440
[Amit Varma]: consider to and which we know would not work for this larger ongoing normalized disaster,

01:41:55.440 --> 01:42:00.920
[Amit Varma]: that is poverty in the Indian state, we are seeing them as a short term fix now, is it

01:42:00.920 --> 01:42:05.560
[Amit Varma]: an extension of the fact that in this crisis, the primary duty of the Indian state is to

01:42:05.560 --> 01:42:11.240
[Amit Varma]: protect the citizen. And if those measures like a lockdown have economic costs, those

01:42:11.240 --> 01:42:15.520
[Amit Varma]: have to be ameliorated by the state. Is that where the thinking is coming from?

01:42:15.520 --> 01:42:20.840
[Guest]: Yeah, so three things, you know, you've you've talked about, I think, three distinct issues

01:42:20.840 --> 01:42:25.800
[Guest]: with the state. So the first one, the flailing state, I completely agree with you. I mean,

01:42:25.800 --> 01:42:31.120
[Guest]: that's a fantastic paper by Lant. He's written a lot on this. Alex and I wrote about this

01:42:31.120 --> 01:42:36.140
[Guest]: too. Our basic point, which, you know, you agree with, is that the Indian state tries

01:42:36.140 --> 01:42:42.920
[Guest]: to do too much, too soon. It tries to regulate areas that it has no capacity to regulate.

01:42:42.920 --> 01:42:47.720
[Guest]: It tries to monitor things that it simply cannot do. And it does too little of what

01:42:47.720 --> 01:42:52.120
[Guest]: it is supposed to do, which is provide law and order and provide public goods and security

01:42:52.120 --> 01:42:59.560
[Guest]: and things like that. In fact, one great line from Ed Glazer, the economist, when he wrote

01:42:59.560 --> 01:43:07.000
[Guest]: about state capacity in an essay, he said, a country that cannot provide clean water

01:43:07.000 --> 01:43:13.600
[Guest]: should not be in the business of regulating film dialogue. And you and I, as, you know,

01:43:13.600 --> 01:43:17.440
[Guest]: classical liberals will agree that no one should be in the business of regulating film

01:43:17.440 --> 01:43:23.160
[Guest]: dialogue anyway. But on the margin, what he was talking about was state capacity is limited

01:43:23.160 --> 01:43:29.080
[Guest]: resource like anything else. And the Indian government spends all its capacity on all

01:43:29.080 --> 01:43:35.320
[Guest]: these useless things, which it cannot possibly accomplish, right? Instead of actually providing

01:43:35.320 --> 01:43:42.680
[Guest]: clean water, basic public goods, sewage systems, you know, maybe like a primary education system,

01:43:42.680 --> 01:43:48.360
[Guest]: things that we associate with the government doing even in your and my version of a limited

01:43:48.360 --> 01:43:54.360
[Guest]: government. So our government is completely like, so in the process, it has spread itself

01:43:54.360 --> 01:44:00.320
[Guest]: too thin and it's flailing. So the Indian government has labor regulation, which the

01:44:00.320 --> 01:44:05.440
[Guest]: most advanced countries in the world don't have and cannot hope to enforce. And so what

01:44:05.440 --> 01:44:10.400
[Guest]: happens as a consequence is that the Indian government also doesn't enforce all its regulation.

01:44:10.400 --> 01:44:15.400
[Guest]: It just does it in a discretionary and pernicious fashion. So when it wants to come down hard

01:44:15.400 --> 01:44:20.560
[Guest]: on some manufacturer, they will send the labor inspector and, you know, sort of list the

01:44:20.560 --> 01:44:25.400
[Guest]: 30 violations and try to put that person in jail or extract a huge fine. So that's how

01:44:25.400 --> 01:44:29.840
[Guest]: the Indian government operates. So I'm completely with you. I think I wrote a similar column

01:44:29.840 --> 01:44:34.520
[Guest]: on this. I think it's called the Upside Down Indian State. I'll share it with you so that

01:44:34.520 --> 01:44:35.520
[Amit Varma]: you can put it in the show notes.

01:44:35.520 --> 01:44:36.880
[Guest]: We can link it in the show notes.

01:44:36.880 --> 01:44:42.120
[Guest]: Yeah. So that's one part of it. And there I'm in complete agreement with you. The second

01:44:42.120 --> 01:44:48.240
[Guest]: part of it is what is the appropriate role of the state in peace times and what is the

01:44:48.240 --> 01:44:53.320
[Guest]: appropriate role of the state in pandemic times? Now, I completely agree with you that

01:44:53.320 --> 01:44:59.240
[Guest]: over 70 years because of terrible socialist laws and paternalistic laws and, you know,

01:44:59.240 --> 01:45:06.120
[Guest]: us just trying to stifle the market system and voluntary action at each and every stage,

01:45:06.120 --> 01:45:10.880
[Guest]: we have completely suppressed private enterprise. And in the process, we've impoverished hundreds

01:45:10.880 --> 01:45:15.600
[Guest]: of millions of people. So on that, I think there is no debate between you and me. And

01:45:15.600 --> 01:45:21.520
[Guest]: I think 90 percent of the economists agree with us. But the fact of the matter is we

01:45:21.520 --> 01:45:29.480
[Guest]: are currently living in a country of 1.3 billion people where 275 million are below the poverty

01:45:29.480 --> 01:45:35.520
[Guest]: line and the poverty line is 1.25 dollars a day. So these people subsist on less than

01:45:35.520 --> 01:45:42.440
[Guest]: 3000 rupees a month. OK, and that's something we need to seriously think about. The second

01:45:42.440 --> 01:45:49.480
[Guest]: is even people above the poverty line because of really stupid policies like our labor regulation,

01:45:49.480 --> 01:45:54.360
[Guest]: like our industrial licensing, most of them work in the informal sector, which means they

01:45:54.360 --> 01:46:00.880
[Guest]: don't have the safety of contracts like, you know, people like me, for instance. So I have

01:46:00.880 --> 01:46:06.440
[Guest]: a contract with my employer. You know, they can't fire me if I'm working remotely. And

01:46:06.440 --> 01:46:10.000
[Guest]: right now I'm not able to produce anything because of the covid crisis. You know, I still

01:46:10.000 --> 01:46:16.680
[Guest]: get a paycheck. Most people living and working in India do not have that security. When you

01:46:16.680 --> 01:46:21.560
[Guest]: work in the informal sector, you also don't get employee insurance. You don't get pension

01:46:21.560 --> 01:46:26.200
[Guest]: provident fund, you know, a whole host of things. And a very large proportion of the

01:46:26.200 --> 01:46:31.640
[Guest]: people in the informal sector are actually daily wage laborers, which means if I can't

01:46:31.640 --> 01:46:36.880
[Guest]: go to work today because I have a fever or my family member is sick, then I don't get

01:46:36.880 --> 01:46:42.280
[Guest]: paid anything and I need to go to bed, you know, starving. So that's the circumstance

01:46:42.280 --> 01:46:48.000
[Guest]: we have created for about three to four hundred million people. So these people in India are

01:46:48.000 --> 01:46:54.240
[Guest]: above the poverty line because they work very hard. They work long hours. They work as daily

01:46:54.240 --> 01:46:59.200
[Guest]: wage laborers, usually in the informal sector. But the flip side to that is the moment you

01:46:59.200 --> 01:47:05.400
[Guest]: have something like demonetization or a lockdown to mitigate the covid pandemic, these people

01:47:05.400 --> 01:47:12.680
[Guest]: are not going to get paid. So they are not a group that has savings. Right. So, for instance,

01:47:12.680 --> 01:47:18.640
[Guest]: if I didn't get paid right now, I'm an economist. I've come from a lot of privilege. I have

01:47:18.640 --> 01:47:24.680
[Guest]: some savings in the bank that tied me over for X number of months. There's a large group

01:47:24.680 --> 01:47:30.680
[Guest]: in India, three to four hundred million people who cannot go through three weeks of a lockdown

01:47:30.680 --> 01:47:35.200
[Guest]: because they don't have savings to sustain them for three weeks. And this is no fault

01:47:35.200 --> 01:47:39.280
[Guest]: of theirs. It's not like they did poor financial planning and ate too much popcorn when they

01:47:39.280 --> 01:47:44.880
[Guest]: went to watch a movie. Right. They just don't make enough money. They live on subsistence

01:47:44.880 --> 01:47:49.280
[Guest]: day to day. If they earn today, they can feed their family. If they don't earn tomorrow,

01:47:49.280 --> 01:47:54.680
[Guest]: they can't feed their family. Now, this group has suddenly it's very vulnerable to economic

01:47:54.680 --> 01:48:00.920
[Guest]: stress even in normal times. And they get pushed to the poverty line or below poverty

01:48:00.920 --> 01:48:06.400
[Guest]: line when there is a huge shock. So, you know, when everything gets locked down because of

01:48:06.400 --> 01:48:11.480
[Guest]: pollution in Delhi, that is a big shock. Not only do these people get sick, they also don't

01:48:11.480 --> 01:48:16.600
[Guest]: have the ability to go to work when things get locked down because of demonetization

01:48:16.600 --> 01:48:22.640
[Guest]: or a covid lockdown. Same problem. So they're very vulnerable to economic stress and they

01:48:22.640 --> 01:48:28.760
[Guest]: slide back into poverty. So poverty is not a fixed concept of I'm poor or I'm not poor.

01:48:28.760 --> 01:48:33.760
[Guest]: It's all circumstances. Right. So currently, in addition to the 275 million who are below

01:48:33.760 --> 01:48:39.160
[Guest]: poverty line and they are very well targeted, we have a pretty good idea of who these people

01:48:39.160 --> 01:48:43.940
[Guest]: are and a lot of policies targeted towards them. You and I can debate the effectiveness

01:48:43.940 --> 01:48:48.080
[Guest]: of those policies, but the government has at least made an attempt to identify these

01:48:48.080 --> 01:48:54.400
[Guest]: people. The 400 million people who are on the cusp of economic stress being pushed one

01:48:54.400 --> 01:48:58.880
[Guest]: way or another. So when markets flourish, you know, they get lifted out of poverty and

01:48:58.880 --> 01:49:03.920
[Guest]: when markets can't flourish, they get pushed back into poverty. This group is invisible,

01:49:03.920 --> 01:49:12.560
[Guest]: right? Or unseen to go back to our theme. And we do need to think about them. We definitely

01:49:12.560 --> 01:49:16.280
[Guest]: need to think about them in pandemic times, even if we don't think about them in peace

01:49:16.280 --> 01:49:22.040
[Guest]: times. But I think overall, we need some kind of a sensible solution for that. So in the

01:49:22.040 --> 01:49:27.920
[Guest]: post, I had suggested a UBI. I did not think of it as a paternalistic act. I thought of

01:49:27.920 --> 01:49:34.520
[Guest]: it as a fundamental moral duty of the state to make sure that its citizens do not starve.

01:49:34.520 --> 01:49:40.000
[Guest]: And the reason the citizens are in that position in the first place is because both as a government

01:49:40.000 --> 01:49:45.240
[Guest]: and as a society, we have consistently looked the other way when it comes to the informal

01:49:45.240 --> 01:49:52.120
[Guest]: labour sector, right? We are not very good about, you know, even the most elite among

01:49:52.120 --> 01:49:57.720
[Guest]: us. How many people are offering health benefits to their household help? I don't know, right?

01:49:57.720 --> 01:50:02.880
[Guest]: I would assume a very small percentage. So it's not just the government, it's also the

01:50:02.880 --> 01:50:10.840
[Guest]: rest of us. As a country, as a society, we have made these people invisible in the system

01:50:10.840 --> 01:50:15.160
[Guest]: and we just operate business as usual and we look the other way. When we pass a slum,

01:50:15.160 --> 01:50:20.440
[Guest]: we just hold our nose up and, you know, sort of, we carry on with things. And right now,

01:50:20.440 --> 01:50:28.040
[Guest]: the pandemic has cracked open this sort of, you know, underbelly of the Indian political

01:50:28.040 --> 01:50:33.800
[Guest]: economy, which we always pretend doesn't exist. So slums is another problem. As you and I

01:50:33.800 --> 01:50:39.240
[Guest]: have talked about this before, slums are a consequence of terrible urban land regulation

01:50:39.240 --> 01:50:44.520
[Guest]: and housing policy. That's why slums exist. Bombay would not function without slums. No

01:50:44.520 --> 01:50:49.400
[Guest]: big city in India can function without slums because 42% of the households in Bombay live

01:50:49.400 --> 01:50:55.160
[Guest]: in slum or slum-like arrangements, informal arrangements, but they are the bulk of the

01:50:55.160 --> 01:51:00.600
[Guest]: labor that runs the Mumbai economy, right? So we need to think about these people, but

01:51:00.600 --> 01:51:05.520
[Guest]: we don't address these issues normally. Now that there is an outbreak in Dharavi, suddenly

01:51:05.520 --> 01:51:10.600
[Guest]: we're like, oh my God, we need a slum policy. But historically, we've not addressed it.

01:51:10.600 --> 01:51:15.480
[Guest]: And now helping these people, we can't say that's paternalism or that's a handout. At

01:51:15.480 --> 01:51:22.520
[Guest]: this moment in a pandemic, it is absolutely our fundamental moral responsibility to ensure

01:51:22.520 --> 01:51:29.080
[Guest]: the people we have personally, and as a society kept impoverished, do not die of starvation

01:51:29.080 --> 01:51:35.680
[Guest]: or do not die of disease. So that's my response to that. When it comes to your third question

01:51:35.680 --> 01:51:42.720
[Guest]: of do I think a UBI should carry on beyond this? Now, in normal times, both you and I

01:51:42.720 --> 01:51:48.680
[Guest]: are not in favor of transfers from the government to citizens. We are not in favor of subsidies

01:51:48.680 --> 01:51:53.600
[Guest]: and things like that. Now, as an economist, I will say that an income support, which is

01:51:53.600 --> 01:51:58.680
[Guest]: not means tested, that is we're not saying you get it if you qualify, if you're below

01:51:58.680 --> 01:52:03.000
[Guest]: a certain income or if you have a certain profession. So basically we just give it to

01:52:03.000 --> 01:52:08.040
[Guest]: everyone of a particular category. Those tend to be the cleanest transfers. They have the

01:52:08.040 --> 01:52:15.920
[Guest]: least distortions, right? So as an economist, I'm a huge fan of universal or quasi-universal

01:52:15.920 --> 01:52:23.360
[Guest]: income and that being given in the form of a direct cash transfer, simply because it's

01:52:23.360 --> 01:52:28.640
[Guest]: the cleanest instrument that we can think of. It has the fewest price distortions. So

01:52:28.640 --> 01:52:33.000
[Guest]: it's much better than giving agricultural subsidy, water subsidy, food subsidy, fertilizer

01:52:33.000 --> 01:52:38.360
[Guest]: subsidy and all the million other distortive subsidies that we have. So that's the economist

01:52:38.360 --> 01:52:44.600
[Guest]: part of it. The other aspect I want to shine light on when it comes to income support as

01:52:44.600 --> 01:52:50.400
[Guest]: an economist, and we are seeing this happening the world over, the market process, while

01:52:50.400 --> 01:52:58.840
[Guest]: it's incredibly valuable in pushing people towards prosperity, it is not seamless and

01:52:58.840 --> 01:53:05.440
[Guest]: it is not even in its effects, right? There are business cycles and we've seen this happening

01:53:05.440 --> 01:53:11.760
[Guest]: in developed countries because of globalizations. There are certain areas such as manufacturing,

01:53:11.760 --> 01:53:16.120
[Guest]: which have taken a huge hit and the people who are working in those sectors suddenly

01:53:16.120 --> 01:53:20.880
[Guest]: find themselves unemployed, right? And they are not at any personal fault. They're not

01:53:20.880 --> 01:53:26.720
[Guest]: lazy. It's not that they don't work hard. It's just the global forces of the market

01:53:26.720 --> 01:53:32.500
[Guest]: are so big that their firm had to move its manufacturing operations to China or something

01:53:32.500 --> 01:53:39.520
[Guest]: like that. And as a society, we need to think about how do we support people for a short

01:53:39.520 --> 01:53:45.240
[Guest]: period of time or in times when there are business cycles such that they can retool

01:53:45.240 --> 01:53:50.680
[Guest]: and get back into the economy as opposed to them losing their job and then suddenly being

01:53:50.680 --> 01:53:55.360
[Guest]: out of work. Now, even someone like me, as we talked about this, I come from a lot of

01:53:55.360 --> 01:54:03.360
[Guest]: privilege, but I have hyper-specialized. I have just been in academia my whole life.

01:54:03.360 --> 01:54:09.320
[Guest]: I don't know very much beyond economics and public policy. If you asked me to go and work

01:54:09.320 --> 01:54:14.380
[Guest]: tomorrow and say, hey, your university is closed, but we need a lot of masks. Why don't

01:54:14.380 --> 01:54:19.000
[Guest]: you go and work in a factory that produces masks? I mean, they'll throw me out. I don't

01:54:19.000 --> 01:54:23.680
[Guest]: know how to sew or I know how to sew very badly. So it's going to take me some time

01:54:23.680 --> 01:54:28.000
[Guest]: to retool, even if I'm willing to take on a different job, which is in manufacturing

01:54:28.000 --> 01:54:33.960
[Guest]: or a different kind of job writing outside of academy or something like that. So we need

01:54:33.960 --> 01:54:38.400
[Guest]: to think about that. So the market is not seamless. It comes with business cycles. And

01:54:38.400 --> 01:54:44.240
[Guest]: this is true both in India, where we're looking at unproductive sectors of the economy, like

01:54:44.240 --> 01:54:48.920
[Guest]: agriculture and people moving to manufacturing or services, people moving from unproductive

01:54:48.920 --> 01:54:55.380
[Guest]: rural areas to urban areas. Income support hugely helps people when they're making these

01:54:55.380 --> 01:55:00.200
[Guest]: transitions and these transitions are extremely necessary when we think about a functional

01:55:00.200 --> 01:55:06.120
[Guest]: market system. Can some of these transitions be provided by civil society? Absolutely.

01:55:06.120 --> 01:55:12.280
[Guest]: I don't think income support should mean that civil society cannot participate. Second,

01:55:12.280 --> 01:55:16.940
[Guest]: I don't think income support should be very high. The kind of income support I'm talking

01:55:16.940 --> 01:55:23.840
[Guest]: about is 3000 rupees a month. That's the poverty line, right? So it is not enough to incentivize

01:55:23.840 --> 01:55:30.240
[Guest]: anyone to just stop working and hang out at home. It's just about going to buy you food

01:55:30.240 --> 01:55:35.920
[Guest]: and shelter, if at all. So I don't think there is too much moral hazard and I don't think

01:55:35.920 --> 01:55:41.520
[Guest]: there's too much paternalism. And the really rich people who spend 3000 rupees on a meal

01:55:41.520 --> 01:55:46.720
[Guest]: or a drink, who don't need it, will not get it anyway. So I think it's a very clean instrument

01:55:46.720 --> 01:55:52.160
[Guest]: and I think it's necessary. I don't think this is a paternalistic act. I think if you

01:55:52.160 --> 01:55:56.960
[Guest]: and I are to take the functioning of the market seriously, we also need to think about business

01:55:56.960 --> 01:56:03.040
[Guest]: cycles. We need to talk about sectoral shifts. We need to think about how people in a society

01:56:03.040 --> 01:56:07.720
[Guest]: which is civilized, which has deep division of labor and specialization, are not going

01:56:07.720 --> 01:56:13.040
[Guest]: to be able to transition from one area to another area overnight and seamlessly. And

01:56:13.040 --> 01:56:18.760
[Guest]: according to me, the cleanest instrument I can think of in these circumstances is some

01:56:18.760 --> 01:56:21.960
[Guest]: kind of direct cash transfer, basic income support.

01:56:21.960 --> 01:56:28.200
[Amit Varma]: Okay. So I have a bunch of thoughts on all of that. To begin with, I'd like to share

01:56:28.200 --> 01:56:29.640
[Guest]: an image with you, which are...

01:56:29.640 --> 01:56:34.680
[Guest]: I feel like we can finally disagree on something. So I'm looking forward to this. We agree far

01:56:34.680 --> 01:56:35.680
[Amit Varma]: too much.

01:56:35.680 --> 01:56:38.880
[Amit Varma]: The disagreement comes at the end. In fact, you know, when people ask me that, you know,

01:56:38.880 --> 01:56:42.160
[Amit Varma]: why don't you get people on your show you disagree with? I say, look, I disagree with

01:56:42.160 --> 01:56:46.560
[Amit Varma]: almost everyone who comes on my show, with the exception being Shruti Rajgopalan. So

01:56:46.560 --> 01:56:54.320
[Amit Varma]: boom, that achievement unlocked. But anyway, my first observation is not a disagreement.

01:56:54.320 --> 01:56:59.080
[Amit Varma]: It's in fact, it strengthens your case, which is an image that our mutual friend Kumar Anand

01:56:59.080 --> 01:57:03.600
[Amit Varma]: once told me about, where Kumar used to live in Mumbai in those days. Now, of course, he's

01:57:03.600 --> 01:57:09.120
[Amit Varma]: in Delhi. And Kumar was once chatting with a taxi driver, and the taxi driver told him

01:57:09.120 --> 01:57:13.480
[Amit Varma]: about the circumstances of his life in Mumbai. Obviously, he was a migrant from somewhere

01:57:13.480 --> 01:57:18.520
[Amit Varma]: else, I forget where, UP, Bihar, wherever, to Mumbai. Now, the taxi driver lived with

01:57:18.520 --> 01:57:24.120
[Amit Varma]: seven other people, eight people to a room. So they shared this narrow cloistered space.

01:57:24.120 --> 01:57:28.400
[Amit Varma]: And when the time came for him to work, he got up from sleep, and he went to work. Now

01:57:28.400 --> 01:57:32.560
[Amit Varma]: here's the kicker. There were actually 16 people who lived in that room, but they slept

01:57:32.560 --> 01:57:37.200
[Amit Varma]: in shifts. So you'd have eight people who would have it for half the day. And then those

01:57:37.200 --> 01:57:41.240
[Amit Varma]: eight people would go out to work to drive the taxis or whatever other work they do.

01:57:41.240 --> 01:57:45.240
[Amit Varma]: And the other eight would come back from their shift, whatever it was they were doing, and

01:57:45.240 --> 01:57:50.320
[Amit Varma]: they would sleep. So in a room, you managed to pack in eight people. And then you're there

01:57:50.320 --> 01:57:54.160
[Amit Varma]: actually 16 people. Now what happens when you have a lockdown? What happens when you

01:57:54.160 --> 01:57:59.120
[Amit Varma]: have a lockdown is, first of all, none of these guys has work, right? None of these

01:57:59.120 --> 01:58:04.240
[Amit Varma]: guys has work, they're all out of work. They're probably people who subsist on maybe they

01:58:04.240 --> 01:58:09.080
[Amit Varma]: have a week's money in advance at most, they don't have savings. And now instead of eight

01:58:09.080 --> 01:58:13.400
[Amit Varma]: to a room, there are 16 to a room. They can't even lie down in their own space because their

01:58:13.400 --> 01:58:18.080
[Amit Varma]: own space was, you know, had that temporal limitation. And the thought that strikes me

01:58:18.080 --> 01:58:24.320
[Amit Varma]: here is who let them down? In my mind, if I go to root causes, I would say again, it's

01:58:24.320 --> 01:58:29.720
[Amit Varma]: that same thing. It's a failing state that let them down that over 72 years we have with

01:58:29.720 --> 01:58:36.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, our crony socialism and our distrust of private enterprise, we have not allowed

01:58:36.640 --> 01:58:41.440
[Amit Varma]: our society to progress to the level where everyone can meet what the philosopher Harry

01:58:41.440 --> 01:58:46.520
[Amit Varma]: Frankfurt calls a doctrine of sufficiency. None of these people meet that and all of

01:58:46.520 --> 01:58:51.280
[Amit Varma]: these 16 people may be above the poverty line. So when a pandemic happens, and there's a

01:58:51.280 --> 01:58:55.920
[Amit Varma]: lockdown, do we owe them something? And I agree with you, it's a moral imperative, we

01:58:55.920 --> 01:59:01.800
[Amit Varma]: owe them something. But I will also, you know, frame it by alluding to something the great

01:59:01.800 --> 01:59:06.880
[Amit Varma]: farmer Sharad Joshi once said. Sharad Joshi, of course, is one of my favorite 20th century

01:59:06.880 --> 01:59:11.280
[Amit Varma]: leaders. You can hear a bit more about in the only Hindi episode I've done on my podcast,

01:59:11.280 --> 01:59:15.840
[Guest]: which is episode 86 of the scene and the unseen. It is my most favorite scene in the unseen

01:59:15.840 --> 01:59:20.520
[Amit Varma]: episode of all time. Which is the first, you know, I should do more Hindi episodes, but

01:59:20.520 --> 01:59:24.080
[Guest]: that is with the farmer leader. It wasn't because it was in Hindi. It was because of

01:59:24.080 --> 01:59:30.200
[Amit Varma]: Gunwant Patil, who is just such a clear thinker. So that episode was with the farmer leader

01:59:30.200 --> 01:59:36.920
[Amit Varma]: Gunwant Patil, who was an old associate of Sharad Joshi. And he spoke about Sharad Joshi's

01:59:36.920 --> 01:59:43.600
[Amit Varma]: fantastic phrase, negative subsidy. Now, what is a negative subsidy? We all talk and this

01:59:43.600 --> 01:59:49.520
[Amit Varma]: is extremely unfair. We talk unfairly of farmers, of people who are subsidized by the state.

01:59:49.520 --> 01:59:55.320
[Amit Varma]: This is rubbish. In Sharad Joshi's words, farmers are actually hurt so much by the bad

01:59:55.320 --> 01:59:59.280
[Amit Varma]: policies of the state and do go back and listen to that episode. And one more I'll link from

01:59:59.280 --> 02:00:05.000
[Amit Varma]: the show notes are hurt so much by the acts of the state that they actually lose money.

02:00:05.000 --> 02:00:13.160
[Amit Varma]: And Sharad Joshi calls this the negative subsidy. And Joshiji was against all forms of paternalism.

02:00:13.160 --> 02:00:18.280
[Amit Varma]: But nevertheless, you know, if you look at the manifestos that he drew up for the Shetkari

02:00:18.280 --> 02:00:24.160
[Amit Varma]: Sanghatana, the party which he founded and ran so well, everything there was promoting

02:00:24.160 --> 02:00:28.080
[Amit Varma]: freedom and anti-paternalistic and talking about removal of controls and blah, blah,

02:00:28.080 --> 02:00:31.400
[Amit Varma]: blah. But there was one thing which on the surface sounds paternalistic, which was farm

02:00:31.400 --> 02:00:37.600
[Amit Varma]: loan waivers. But it sounds paternalistic on the surface. Joshiji's point was that look,

02:00:37.600 --> 02:00:43.620
[Amit Varma]: this is a compensation for the negative subsidy that we have been subjected to all our lives.

02:00:43.620 --> 02:00:49.520
[Amit Varma]: And in his mind, it was, you know, a temporary measure that you have to do only side by side

02:00:49.520 --> 02:00:55.240
[Amit Varma]: with all the other reforms. And how farm loan waivers, of course, used in modern India,

02:00:55.240 --> 02:01:00.840
[Amit Varma]: are in a paternalistic way without making any of those structural reforms, and therefore

02:01:00.840 --> 02:01:06.080
[Amit Varma]: they do not work. Now, I want to sort of when we are talking about markets, and since agriculture

02:01:06.080 --> 02:01:12.200
[Amit Varma]: is what we brought the subject to, I also want to point out that when we liberalized

02:01:12.200 --> 02:01:17.640
[Amit Varma]: and it was a very limited liberalization, sadly, in 91, the one sector that we did not

02:01:17.640 --> 02:01:22.040
[Amit Varma]: touch was agriculture, it wasn't liberalized at all. I've had episodes speaking in depth

02:01:22.040 --> 02:01:28.160
[Amit Varma]: about this. And that is a one sector where there is the largest amount of distress. So

02:01:28.160 --> 02:01:35.960
[Amit Varma]: I would still hold that in the long run, you have to let voluntary action play a role that,

02:01:35.960 --> 02:01:42.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, people are not costs, they are resources. And that if you look at what has happened

02:01:42.000 --> 02:01:48.360
[Amit Varma]: in other free economies, and in the sectors that we did free up, they have done far better.

02:01:48.360 --> 02:01:53.760
[Amit Varma]: And you know, in agriculture, they continue to sort of do not so well. And here, I would

02:01:53.760 --> 02:01:57.400
[Amit Varma]: again, you know, go back to you know, when we talk about UBI, and when we talk about

02:01:57.400 --> 02:02:03.320
[Amit Varma]: helping poor people with redistribution, I would point out here, there is a cost to this.

02:02:03.320 --> 02:02:07.940
[Amit Varma]: And it is both a moral and a financial cost. The moral cost, of course, is coercion. Every

02:02:07.940 --> 02:02:12.120
[Amit Varma]: compassionate act of government is founded on coercion, because the government takes

02:02:12.120 --> 02:02:18.120
[Amit Varma]: its taxes by coercive means. So that is a moral cost. And it's a moral cost, we should

02:02:18.120 --> 02:02:23.800
[Amit Varma]: acknowledge while talking about what government action is justified and is not justified.

02:02:23.800 --> 02:02:28.160
[Amit Varma]: I would, for example, say that the rule of law is justified, that coercion is justified

02:02:28.160 --> 02:02:33.040
[Amit Varma]: for that it is not justified for building 100 meter statue, or for spending 1000s of

02:02:33.040 --> 02:02:40.040
[Amit Varma]: crores in advertising, government services, not the case, irrelevant. Leave that aside

02:02:40.040 --> 02:02:44.400
[Amit Varma]: for a moment. But the financial cost, you know, I had Ajay Shah and Vijay Kelkar on

02:02:44.400 --> 02:02:47.920
[Amit Varma]: my show a few months back. And in fact,

02:02:47.920 --> 02:02:52.880
[Guest]: that book is really fantastic. I think everybody must read In Service of the Republic.

02:02:52.880 --> 02:02:57.160
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, they wrote a brilliant book called In Service of the Republic, which I totally second

02:02:57.160 --> 02:03:02.680
[Amit Varma]: what you just said, everyone should read that. And a concept that they very clearly elaborated

02:03:02.680 --> 02:03:07.600
[Amit Varma]: upon at length is a marginal cost of public funds, which is for every one rupee spent

02:03:07.600 --> 02:03:12.480
[Amit Varma]: by the government, the cost of the economy is that of three rupees, I mean, between two

02:03:12.480 --> 02:03:17.280
[Amit Varma]: and a half to three and a half in India, but you can approximate that to three rupees.

02:03:17.280 --> 02:03:21.480
[Amit Varma]: So it's not just if you give a handout of one rupee to someone, the cost to the rest

02:03:21.480 --> 02:03:26.360
[Amit Varma]: of the rest of society at large for off that one rupee is three rupees for a variety of

02:03:26.360 --> 02:03:28.680
[Amit Varma]: reasons, which the book elaborates upon.

02:03:28.680 --> 02:03:35.800
[Guest]: Yes. And in the scheme of things, UBI is on the lower end of that cost, because it's much

02:03:35.800 --> 02:03:42.040
[Amit Varma]: cleaner than most other subsidies. But there is a certain cost of public funds, no question.

02:03:42.040 --> 02:03:47.400
[Amit Varma]: Sure. So now the point that I'm getting to with regard to UBI is that I would actually

02:03:47.400 --> 02:03:52.600
[Amit Varma]: be okay with UBI, if we make the assumption that look, in a poor country, there is immediate

02:03:52.600 --> 02:03:57.600
[Amit Varma]: distress that you have to relieve. And therefore, the UBI works for that. But the caveats I

02:03:57.600 --> 02:04:03.760
[Amit Varma]: would put is that it has to come in place of all the other failed paternalism that effectively

02:04:03.760 --> 02:04:09.200
[Amit Varma]: makes us that effectively makes us a predatory state. I do not see that happening in the

02:04:09.200 --> 02:04:14.720
[Amit Varma]: political economy. And be in a case like this, while I agree that it is a moral imperative

02:04:14.720 --> 02:04:19.080
[Amit Varma]: that we have to make sure nobody starves. I mean, that is regardless of context, that

02:04:19.080 --> 02:04:25.080
[Amit Varma]: is regardless of COVID, no one should starve. But then the point is that, and this sort

02:04:25.080 --> 02:04:28.480
[Amit Varma]: of leads me to the next question, but we'll come to that next.

02:04:28.480 --> 02:04:34.360
[Guest]: Hang on one second. You know, I don't want to keep peddling all my columns. But my argument,

02:04:34.360 --> 02:04:40.240
[Guest]: I have written against UBI in India, though I'm a big fan of UBI overall. And my argument

02:04:40.240 --> 02:04:46.600
[Guest]: was very similar to yours, which is in India, normally, UBI should be a substitute for all

02:04:46.600 --> 02:04:51.700
[Guest]: our other bad, you know, subsidies. So what we should do is we should add up the cost

02:04:51.700 --> 02:04:55.360
[Guest]: of all those subsidies, we should scrap all of them, and whatever money is remaining in

02:04:55.360 --> 02:04:59.960
[Guest]: that pot, we should say, okay, what is the fiscally responsible, you know, income support

02:04:59.960 --> 02:05:05.400
[Guest]: that we can provide from that. What India has done instead is it announced quasi UBIs

02:05:05.400 --> 02:05:10.280
[Guest]: just before the last general election, and it didn't scrap any of the subsidies. So I

02:05:10.280 --> 02:05:16.760
[Guest]: think the title of that column was UBI is universally botched by Indians. And I was

02:05:16.760 --> 02:05:20.160
[Guest]: saying something very similar to what you're saying, which is, we don't want to end up

02:05:20.160 --> 02:05:24.920
[Guest]: in a situation where we give a UBI and all these other subsidies and keep compounding

02:05:24.920 --> 02:05:28.960
[Guest]: the problem more and more. So I very much agree with you, it has to be a substitute,

02:05:28.960 --> 02:05:34.240
[Guest]: it can't be an addition. I think it's a very much, it's a cleaner substitute. And the other

02:05:34.240 --> 02:05:39.960
[Guest]: thing I would add is, we need to keep it relatively low that it doesn't turn into a moral hazard

02:05:39.960 --> 02:05:44.360
[Guest]: problem. And the moral hazard is never from the poor in our country, it's always from

02:05:44.360 --> 02:05:49.040
[Guest]: the rich. And I don't think the UBI will, will subsidize anything for the rich. So you

02:05:49.040 --> 02:05:50.960
[Amit Varma]: know, I think we can, we can stay away from that.

02:05:50.960 --> 02:05:55.280
[Amit Varma]: I agree with that in theory. But you know, the thing is that again, it goes back to the

02:05:55.280 --> 02:06:00.240
[Amit Varma]: public choice issue of incentives. The predatory state is never going to reduce any of its

02:06:00.240 --> 02:06:04.560
[Amit Varma]: predation. So if a UBI is added, it's not going to be as if you decide, okay, we'll

02:06:04.560 --> 02:06:09.440
[Amit Varma]: get rid of all the other subsidies, and we'll put the money in a pool and let's do a UBI

02:06:09.440 --> 02:06:14.120
[Amit Varma]: from that. That's not realistic, that's not going to happen. And you will just increase

02:06:14.120 --> 02:06:18.080
[Amit Varma]: the fiscal burden, which of course means that one rupee of state spending is equal to you

02:06:18.080 --> 02:06:23.600
[Amit Varma]: know, a cost of three rupees to society. And that cost of three rupees to society then

02:06:23.600 --> 02:06:29.720
[Amit Varma]: accumulates and prevents society from advancing freely and helping itself because ultimately,

02:06:29.720 --> 02:06:32.680
[Amit Varma]: as we have seen, mainly society helps itself in spite of the state.

02:06:32.680 --> 02:06:37.160
[Guest]: So I have a slightly more optimistic view on how this can happen. And you know, just

02:06:37.160 --> 02:06:41.200
[Guest]: bear with me. And this is obviously, there are some huge assumptions I'm making, but

02:06:41.200 --> 02:06:47.640
[Guest]: hear me out anyway. Now, I think it's a good idea to introduce a UBI kind of income support

02:06:47.640 --> 02:06:52.440
[Guest]: during COVID. Because once you start giving people checks that get into their bank accounts,

02:06:52.440 --> 02:06:57.120
[Guest]: it's very difficult to take it away. But to be fiscally responsible, because there are

02:06:57.120 --> 02:07:00.800
[Guest]: only so many resources and the government can't keep, you know, raising more and more

02:07:00.800 --> 02:07:08.160
[Guest]: revenue, it's already finding it hard to raise revenue. At some point, something has to give,

02:07:08.160 --> 02:07:12.360
[Guest]: and it would be very difficult to take away the UBI support, so other cross subsidies

02:07:12.360 --> 02:07:17.600
[Guest]: will go. That is my optimistic version of this problem. Now, I understand that that

02:07:17.600 --> 02:07:22.640
[Guest]: may not happen, or it may take too long to happen. But I think the UBI helps us get around

02:07:22.640 --> 02:07:29.720
[Guest]: that problem at least a little bit. Maybe I'm being too optimistic for Amit Verma, but

02:07:29.720 --> 02:07:32.080
[Amit Varma]: I will still hold on to this optimism.

02:07:32.080 --> 02:07:37.720
[Amit Varma]: You are almost being as optimist as the communists were, that everything will work just fine.

02:07:37.720 --> 02:07:43.600
[Amit Varma]: But incentives, incentives. No, no, I'm just kidding. So let's sort of I mean, I will suspend

02:07:43.600 --> 02:07:48.160
[Amit Varma]: my judgment on that. And I hope you are right. And let's move on from that. I have two broad

02:07:48.160 --> 02:07:52.600
[Amit Varma]: areas I want to talk to you about. But before I do, you know, I should clarify for people

02:07:52.600 --> 02:07:57.720
[Amit Varma]: listening in that, oh, what are these heartless people talking about? People should not be

02:07:57.720 --> 02:08:05.500
[Amit Varma]: given money and UBI is this idea, or a heartless person, speak for yourself, speak for myself.

02:08:05.500 --> 02:08:09.600
[Amit Varma]: And the whole point is that we cannot judge policies by their intentions, but by their

02:08:09.600 --> 02:08:15.360
[Amit Varma]: outcomes. And therefore, we have to take a good hard look at all policies according to

02:08:15.360 --> 02:08:20.640
[Amit Varma]: the effects that they will have, particularly what I call the unseen effects, you know,

02:08:20.640 --> 02:08:25.200
[Amit Varma]: as in the price controls we discussed earlier, who would object to everybody getting sanitizers

02:08:25.200 --> 02:08:29.720
[Amit Varma]: for cheap. But what happens if you fix the price is that nobody gets them. And you have

02:08:29.720 --> 02:08:37.400
[Amit Varma]: to look a little deeper. And, you know, I would still say a small income support is

02:08:37.400 --> 02:08:41.880
[Guest]: slightly different from price and quantity controls. But you and I agree on on what margins

02:08:41.880 --> 02:08:47.960
[Guest]: they're different. But I just want to, I want to flag that. And I, you know, I'm not a big

02:08:47.960 --> 02:08:52.880
[Guest]: fan of income support in developed countries or in Scandinavian countries. I think there's

02:08:52.880 --> 02:08:58.440
[Guest]: a genuine model hazard problem. I think there's a question of, you know, disincentivizing

02:08:58.440 --> 02:09:03.000
[Guest]: productive labor force and things like that. In India, we're talking about this at the

02:09:03.000 --> 02:09:08.640
[Guest]: subsistence and starvation level. So I find it very difficult. Maybe I have to turn my

02:09:08.640 --> 02:09:15.980
[Guest]: libertarian card in to the libertarian policemen out there. But, you know, I still think we

02:09:15.980 --> 02:09:23.320
[Guest]: have to figure something out because their impoverishment is not their fault, but our

02:09:23.320 --> 02:09:25.200
[Guest]: failure as a government and society.

02:09:25.200 --> 02:09:29.920
[Amit Varma]: I think I would, you know, go back to Sharad Joshi ji to think about this, where Joshi

02:09:29.920 --> 02:09:36.040
[Amit Varma]: ji's formulation was that, look, we need to make all these structural changes and paternalism

02:09:36.040 --> 02:09:42.600
[Amit Varma]: cannot work. However, as a short term anesthetic, while you make those changes, you better compensate

02:09:42.600 --> 02:09:47.080
[Amit Varma]: us for the misery that we have had to go through for all these decades, by at least giving

02:09:47.080 --> 02:09:51.440
[Amit Varma]: us these waivers now and never again, because once you make the structural changes, we won't

02:09:51.440 --> 02:09:56.520
[Guest]: need them. And that's the hope that India is so rich that it doesn't need this kind

02:09:56.520 --> 02:10:02.840
[Guest]: of income support. Income support is required when people are living on subsistence levels,

02:10:02.840 --> 02:10:07.800
[Guest]: they have no savings to fall back upon. You know, any kind of economic distress immediately

02:10:07.800 --> 02:10:12.360
[Guest]: pushes them into bankruptcy or they need to sell their land and their wives' jewelry.

02:10:12.360 --> 02:10:14.120
[Amit Varma]: Those are the kinds of circumstances we're talking about.

02:10:14.120 --> 02:10:20.440
[Amit Varma]: I agree. But my whole point is that those circumstances are brought about by and persist

02:10:20.440 --> 02:10:22.440
[Guest]: by pernicious regulation.

02:10:22.440 --> 02:10:29.880
[Amit Varma]: Yes. And the point is, my worry is that, you know, this will again become a paternalistic,

02:10:29.880 --> 02:10:35.680
[Amit Varma]: patronizing, sop thrown to them without any of those structural changes being made. And

02:10:35.680 --> 02:10:40.240
[Amit Varma]: then it becomes a trap that they remain trapped in, much as has happened in agriculture. But

02:10:40.240 --> 02:10:45.880
[Amit Varma]: let's move on from that. You know, I have a couple of larger questions, which I think

02:10:45.880 --> 02:10:49.720
[Amit Varma]: we can finally begin to agree on something again.

02:10:49.720 --> 02:10:53.880
[Guest]: I'm surprised, you know, I always thought we agree too much. I'm glad we found some

02:10:53.880 --> 02:10:56.040
[Amit Varma]: point of disagreement. This is great.

02:10:56.040 --> 02:10:57.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, actually, I remember the only...

02:10:57.400 --> 02:11:00.360
[Guest]: I should put on a t-shirt, I disagree with Amit Verma.

02:11:00.360 --> 02:11:05.240
[Amit Varma]: Well, you know, I think the whole freaking world is a market for that t-shirt in that

02:11:05.240 --> 02:11:11.080
[Amit Varma]: case. But yeah, so good luck with that.

02:11:11.080 --> 02:11:13.320
[Guest]: And I'll make a lot of money selling the t-shirt.

02:11:13.320 --> 02:11:14.320
[Amit Varma]: Right.

02:11:14.320 --> 02:11:15.320
[Amit Varma]: Just saying.

02:11:15.320 --> 02:11:21.160
[Amit Varma]: So this is kind of sort of the next thing I'd like to talk about, which is essentially

02:11:21.160 --> 02:11:25.680
[Amit Varma]: that what we see in many crisis of whatever sort, whether it's a pandemic sort or a war

02:11:25.680 --> 02:11:31.280
[Amit Varma]: sort or just an economic downturn sort, is that the government will use a crisis as an

02:11:31.280 --> 02:11:36.760
[Amit Varma]: excuse or rather the state will use a crisis as an excuse to take even more power than

02:11:36.760 --> 02:11:44.640
[Amit Varma]: it has in, quote unquote, peacetime. And those powers persist after the crisis is over.

02:11:44.640 --> 02:11:50.560
[Amit Varma]: For example, you know, in wartime, a government could hypothetically take over powers which

02:11:50.560 --> 02:11:53.600
[Amit Varma]: affect your privacy and which affect your freedoms.

02:11:53.600 --> 02:11:57.800
[Amit Varma]: And they would say, you know, it's a freedom versus security thing. We are in war. So freedoms

02:11:57.800 --> 02:12:01.320
[Amit Varma]: are not that important. And in peacetime, we'll see. But in peacetime, things never

02:12:01.320 --> 02:12:06.880
[Amit Varma]: go back to normal. Do you see that there's a risk of that happening during this crisis?

02:12:06.880 --> 02:12:09.120
[Guest]: And if so, in what ways?

02:12:09.120 --> 02:12:14.160
[Guest]: That keeps me up at night. So, you know, in general, I think emergency powers, they tend

02:12:14.160 --> 02:12:19.760
[Guest]: to be draconian. We already have a draconian Indian state, but emergency powers tend to

02:12:19.760 --> 02:12:24.680
[Guest]: give more discretion to the state, more power to the state to really infringe on private

02:12:24.680 --> 02:12:31.200
[Guest]: activity. And it's not clear to me that that goes away easily. Now, in India, you know,

02:12:31.200 --> 02:12:37.200
[Guest]: when you and I recorded the episode with Alex, I don't remember verbatim what he said, but

02:12:37.200 --> 02:12:42.200
[Guest]: when you asked him for his thoughts on Indian society and Indian state, he said, Indian

02:12:42.200 --> 02:12:47.760
[Guest]: people tolerate too much abuse from their state or something like that, right? Something

02:12:47.760 --> 02:12:48.760
[Amit Varma]: to that effect.

02:12:48.760 --> 02:12:52.280
[Amit Varma]: About how we are a tolerant nation. And that episode, by the way, will be recorded in early

02:12:52.280 --> 02:12:57.600
[Amit Varma]: Feb, but it will release now in June and it has nothing to do with COVID. But I don't

02:12:57.600 --> 02:13:01.160
[Amit Varma]: think it will be dated because our subject is not dated.

02:13:01.160 --> 02:13:07.200
[Guest]: Because we are timeless, Alex and I. No, it's because, so he said that, and I agree with

02:13:07.200 --> 02:13:14.400
[Guest]: him. The Indian state already has taken such extraordinary powers and had such major infringements

02:13:14.400 --> 02:13:19.280
[Guest]: on individual liberty. We don't even realize when the state is imposing more stress on

02:13:19.280 --> 02:13:23.840
[Guest]: us. And I'm very worried that COVID will do that. I'll tell you a couple of areas where

02:13:23.840 --> 02:13:30.760
[Guest]: I'm particularly worried. One major problem we have, and this goes back to the head of

02:13:30.760 --> 02:13:34.900
[Guest]: the show when we talked about healthcare capacity. So Alex and I have written about what kind

02:13:34.900 --> 02:13:39.700
[Guest]: of pandemic policies we need in developing countries in the absence of healthcare capacity.

02:13:39.700 --> 02:13:45.920
[Guest]: So we don't have enough testing kits. We already know that. One way by which Kerala has had

02:13:45.920 --> 02:13:51.960
[Guest]: success and other states should emulate is contact tracing, right? So the state is going

02:13:51.960 --> 02:13:55.800
[Guest]: to come and it's going to ask you your travel history. It's going to ask you every single

02:13:55.800 --> 02:13:59.240
[Guest]: person you've met. It's going to ask you who you shook hands with, and then it's going

02:13:59.240 --> 02:14:03.360
[Guest]: to go to each and every one of those people. And if anyone's affected, they're going to

02:14:03.360 --> 02:14:07.240
[Guest]: take them away from their family or their neighborhood. They're going to isolate them.

02:14:07.240 --> 02:14:13.200
[Guest]: This is an enormous infringement on individual liberty, right? We are tolerating it in a

02:14:13.200 --> 02:14:17.920
[Guest]: pandemic because we live in very difficult circumstances. We live in very dense urban

02:14:17.920 --> 02:14:23.040
[Guest]: environments. We don't have a good culture of social distancing because of our lack of

02:14:23.040 --> 02:14:28.240
[Guest]: resources. We have intergenerational cohabitation. So it's very difficult to socially distance

02:14:28.240 --> 02:14:35.400
[Guest]: from people who are elderly and could be at risk. So we are tolerating this kind of infringement,

02:14:35.400 --> 02:14:40.200
[Guest]: but I don't think it is a good idea ever for the state to know where I have been, what

02:14:40.200 --> 02:14:47.040
[Guest]: I have done, who I've met, who I shook hands with last. This is a really big problem. But

02:14:47.040 --> 02:14:55.040
[Guest]: contact tracing is one of the very few mechanisms we have as a substitute for wide scale or

02:14:55.040 --> 02:14:59.840
[Guest]: large scale testing, which we cannot implement in India. So in an ideal world, we'd be like

02:14:59.840 --> 02:15:04.960
[Guest]: South Korea, right? We conduct millions of tests and people just go, they test, they

02:15:04.960 --> 02:15:10.560
[Guest]: get tested positive or negative and accordingly they isolate or they don't isolate. In India,

02:15:10.560 --> 02:15:14.760
[Guest]: we don't have that. In fact, we've had people lie about their travel history, right? We

02:15:14.760 --> 02:15:19.840
[Guest]: had the infamous Kanika Kapoor, who's the singer who came and attended four weddings.

02:15:19.840 --> 02:15:24.160
[Guest]: She lied about her travel history. She did not quarantine. She's created a racket at

02:15:24.160 --> 02:15:28.680
[Guest]: a government hospital in Lucknow where they tried to isolate her. So the Indian elite

02:15:28.680 --> 02:15:35.360
[Guest]: can be very badly behaved. The Indian, the non-elite, the poor, very often they're not

02:15:35.360 --> 02:15:38.840
[Guest]: in circumstances to isolate. They're like, I'm the sole breadwinner of the family or

02:15:38.840 --> 02:15:42.920
[Guest]: I'm the only one who can look after my parents, right? If I leave, there's no one to look

02:15:42.920 --> 02:15:49.300
[Guest]: after my kid. So these kinds of infringement on individual liberty, I'm not a fan of, and

02:15:49.300 --> 02:15:55.200
[Guest]: I would really like to not see this persist. We're also getting into huge privacy issues.

02:15:55.200 --> 02:16:00.560
[Guest]: If you look at contact tracing through mobile phones, right? I was told, I don't know how

02:16:00.560 --> 02:16:05.320
[Guest]: to verify this information because I'm not a computer science person, but I was told

02:16:05.320 --> 02:16:11.520
[Guest]: that the government apps, which are the diagnostic apps, they register your location through

02:16:11.520 --> 02:16:17.760
[Guest]: GPS and Bluetooth long after you've done the diagnostic test. That is something that worries

02:16:17.760 --> 02:16:23.560
[Guest]: me deeply. So these sorts of things I'm not comfortable with. I don't see what the alternative

02:16:23.560 --> 02:16:28.680
[Guest]: is. The alternative is excellent healthcare capacity and everyone having a large house,

02:16:28.680 --> 02:16:33.680
[Guest]: lots of square footage, clean pipe water and soap and hand sanitizer to self-isolate while

02:16:33.680 --> 02:16:38.080
[Guest]: they comfortably live off their savings. But we don't have any of them, let alone all of

02:16:38.080 --> 02:16:43.120
[Guest]: the above. So these are the sorts of spaces where we are ceding a lot of control to the

02:16:43.120 --> 02:16:49.680
[Guest]: state and I'm not a fan of it persisting. And in the United States, it's passed the

02:16:49.680 --> 02:16:55.720
[Guest]: CARES Act. It's an extraordinary economic stimulus because these are extraordinary times

02:16:55.720 --> 02:17:02.640
[Guest]: we've had, I think, in America. The last time I checked, about 22 million unemployment claims

02:17:02.640 --> 02:17:07.280
[Guest]: in the last few weeks since people have started putting in a shelter in place orders and restaurants

02:17:07.280 --> 02:17:12.720
[Guest]: and other services have started shutting down and people have lost jobs. But it's a 2 trillion

02:17:12.720 --> 02:17:19.400
[Guest]: stimulus and we have to pay for it. And when I say we, I mean the future Shruti Rajgopalan

02:17:19.400 --> 02:17:23.560
[Guest]: and the future workers two years from now, three years from now in the American economy

02:17:23.560 --> 02:17:29.000
[Guest]: need to pay for this. And there is no clarity on how we came up with this number, whether

02:17:29.000 --> 02:17:35.200
[Guest]: it goes to sensible users, 2 trillion in a stimulus for COVID and the related economic

02:17:35.200 --> 02:17:40.000
[Guest]: crisis and hardly any of it has gone towards development of vaccines, which frankly is

02:17:40.000 --> 02:17:45.040
[Guest]: the only way to get out of this mess. So it's not clear how that money, you know, if the

02:17:45.040 --> 02:17:50.640
[Guest]: dollars were put to the best use either. So I'm not an expert on the CARES Act, but there

02:17:50.640 --> 02:17:55.600
[Guest]: is another way by which, you know, we've given up or we've ceded a lot of control in these

02:17:55.600 --> 02:18:03.160
[Guest]: emergency situations to the government to spend a lot of money without any of us having

02:18:03.160 --> 02:18:09.040
[Guest]: a very clear understanding of how we're going to get out of that spending and how we get

02:18:09.040 --> 02:18:13.880
[Guest]: out of that situation. And right now, everyone's attitude is, look, it's an emergency. We shouldn't

02:18:13.880 --> 02:18:18.080
[Guest]: worry about spending, just print the money. We'll figure it out later. If we don't spend

02:18:18.080 --> 02:18:22.520
[Guest]: the money now, there will be no economy to protect or, you know, the people will be dead.

02:18:22.520 --> 02:18:27.640
[Guest]: You know, there's all of that chatter and I can sympathize with some of that, but it

02:18:27.640 --> 02:18:34.440
[Guest]: does concern me on, you know, how are we going to go back and sort of control the fiscal

02:18:34.440 --> 02:18:39.200
[Guest]: excess of the state? So there is the excess in terms of privacy. There is the excess in

02:18:39.200 --> 02:18:44.560
[Guest]: terms of, you know, fiscal expenditure. There's also excess in terms of just, you know, police

02:18:44.560 --> 02:18:50.000
[Guest]: brutality and things like that happening in India. So we don't know what the appropriate

02:18:50.000 --> 02:18:54.760
[Guest]: role of police officer in these circumstances, right? When they say enforce a lockdown, is

02:18:54.760 --> 02:19:00.160
[Guest]: the job of the police officer to assist people when they're in distress and want to congregate

02:19:00.160 --> 02:19:06.600
[Guest]: or is their job to shut down things, overturn vegetable carts and milkman's trucks and,

02:19:06.600 --> 02:19:10.440
[Guest]: you know, sort of start beating people up and doing lathi charges to get them to walk

02:19:10.440 --> 02:19:16.200
[Guest]: away from a mandi. You know, we have no clarity on that. My understanding of a police enforcing

02:19:16.200 --> 02:19:21.560
[Guest]: a lockdown is we systematically control crowds and have social distancing, but the police

02:19:21.560 --> 02:19:26.840
[Guest]: need to help people get the essential things that they want. No one is out and about just

02:19:26.840 --> 02:19:30.720
[Guest]: having a good time. The people who are out and about need to be there because they need

02:19:30.720 --> 02:19:36.200
[Guest]: to buy vegetables or medicines or milk. So we don't have a good understanding of what

02:19:36.200 --> 02:19:41.480
[Guest]: it is. So the police in India is just danda, right? Anyone who comes out in lockdown, we

02:19:41.480 --> 02:19:46.440
[Guest]: just beat them up. So these are the sorts of areas where we've ceded too much control

02:19:46.440 --> 02:19:50.840
[Guest]: to the government. We're willing to cede it during a lockdown, just not comfortable with

02:19:50.840 --> 02:19:56.800
[Amit Varma]: it. Yeah. And my related thoughts, number one, in the context of, you know, ceding a

02:19:56.800 --> 02:20:02.640
[Amit Varma]: freedoms, it seems to me that there is also a widespread subject mentality in India. Like

02:20:02.640 --> 02:20:06.720
[Amit Varma]: I watch a lot of TikTok and one common meme there is about these people who are saying

02:20:06.720 --> 02:20:10.360
[Amit Varma]: ki, shall I go out? I'll go out. Mujhe kuch nahi hoga. And then the guy goes out and he

02:20:10.360 --> 02:20:13.320
[Amit Varma]: comes back later and he says mujhe toh kuch nahi hua. And then he turns around and you

02:20:13.320 --> 02:20:17.240
[Amit Varma]: realize that his shirt is torn because he's got a lathi beating. And that's completely

02:20:17.240 --> 02:20:21.760
[Amit Varma]: okay. Apparently all the police brutality is completely normalized. I mean, I had a

02:20:21.760 --> 02:20:27.440
[Amit Varma]: similar experience in my housing society here in Mumbai, where my society secretary got

02:20:27.440 --> 02:20:30.680
[Amit Varma]: a call from the nearby police station saying, Hey, the commissioner is going to walk down

02:20:30.680 --> 02:20:35.600
[Amit Varma]: the road. Can you organize your society to applaud for him? So on the society WhatsApp

02:20:35.600 --> 02:20:41.240
[Amit Varma]: group, they organized everybody to go down and applaud. And a couple of women went out

02:20:41.240 --> 02:20:47.400
[Amit Varma]: and showered flowers on the commissioner as he passed by. And that is such an obsequious

02:20:47.400 --> 02:20:54.160
[Guest]: sort of display. And yet it's a perfectly rational response in a world where the police

02:20:54.160 --> 02:21:00.360
[Guest]: is draconian and will unleash its brute force on you if you don't sort of, you know, acquiesce

02:21:00.360 --> 02:21:05.040
[Guest]: and you know, applaud them or give them whatever it is they want, including respect.

02:21:05.040 --> 02:21:10.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And it was actually rational on the part of the secretary of our society to ask

02:21:10.000 --> 02:21:13.740
[Amit Varma]: that people do this because other societies would, and you don't want to be in a situation

02:21:13.740 --> 02:21:17.520
[Amit Varma]: where the society needs something tomorrow. And the cops say, Hey, no, but you are those

02:21:17.520 --> 02:21:22.980
[Amit Varma]: guys and you didn't help us. That's number one. Number two, you know, in the, and I forget

02:21:22.980 --> 02:21:27.000
[Amit Varma]: why this thought came to me in the context of what you were saying, but it's something

02:21:27.000 --> 02:21:33.880
[Amit Varma]: that my friend Suyash Rai once said to me, in the context of demonetization, which you

02:21:33.880 --> 02:21:37.800
[Amit Varma]: and I have recorded an episode on, but Suyash and I also recorded an episode on, I think

02:21:37.800 --> 02:21:43.480
[Amit Varma]: that was, and I would recommend his overmind. They're both at different stages of the thing,

02:21:43.480 --> 02:21:47.320
[Amit Varma]: but the point that he made was that whenever, and this is really important and applies to

02:21:47.320 --> 02:21:53.600
[Amit Varma]: everything, that whenever you're doing a cost benefit analysis, you need to keep in mind

02:21:53.600 --> 02:21:58.120
[Amit Varma]: that your calculation doesn't work if you're talking about costs to one group of people

02:21:58.120 --> 02:22:04.040
[Amit Varma]: and benefits to another group of people. And it seems to me that with a lot of this, you

02:22:04.040 --> 02:22:09.200
[Amit Varma]: know, throwing money at a problem, you are borrowing from the future to fund present

02:22:09.200 --> 02:22:14.800
[Amit Varma]: problems, number one. And number two, there is also a lot of coercion going on in unseen

02:22:14.800 --> 02:22:19.680
[Amit Varma]: ways on people who do not see it, but it's going on. And we ignore all those costs and

02:22:19.680 --> 02:22:24.520
[Amit Varma]: we think about the assumed benefits. And now coming to that, that's a third point. I was

02:22:24.520 --> 02:22:28.880
[Amit Varma]: reading an excellent column by Rathen Roy today, I think, where Rathen made the point

02:22:28.880 --> 02:22:34.160
[Amit Varma]: that fiscal stimulus and all is okay, but there is a danger that if you put too much

02:22:34.160 --> 02:22:40.080
[Amit Varma]: money in the hands of people, and they don't have goods and services to spend it on, what

02:22:40.080 --> 02:22:44.120
[Amit Varma]: you will then have is hyperinflation. And these are very wise words. And this is one

02:22:44.120 --> 02:22:49.480
[Amit Varma]: of those sort of downstream effects that we are not taking into account. Now, we are sort

02:22:49.480 --> 02:22:53.860
[Amit Varma]: of going with that dogmatic thing that, oh, let's do a fiscal stimulus, we'll put money

02:22:53.860 --> 02:22:58.000
[Amit Varma]: in the hands of people, they'll spend it and the economy will bounce back, you know, which

02:22:58.000 --> 02:23:03.280
[Amit Varma]: is again thinking like a man of system, where everybody is a piece on a chessboard. But

02:23:03.280 --> 02:23:05.600
[Amit Varma]: that's not how the real world and the economy work.

02:23:05.600 --> 02:23:11.040
[Guest]: Yeah, so Rathen, I mean, Rathen is an excellent economist, you should get him on the show.

02:23:11.040 --> 02:23:18.420
[Guest]: He's really fantastic. He is the director of NIPFP. And he also writes beautifully not

02:23:18.420 --> 02:23:24.920
[Guest]: just during the COVID pandemic, but more generally on, you know, fiscal issues, and public finance.

02:23:24.920 --> 02:23:29.440
[Guest]: So he's definitely, you know, everyone should read him and his business standard columns,

02:23:29.440 --> 02:23:34.280
[Guest]: you should have him on the show. I agree with Rathen in the sense that there are so many

02:23:34.280 --> 02:23:38.400
[Guest]: effects. So as you pointed out, again, in the head of the show that you know, there's

02:23:38.400 --> 02:23:43.280
[Guest]: no one thing called an essential commodity, right? There's no one thing called a supply

02:23:43.280 --> 02:23:50.360
[Guest]: chain, the economy is a beautifully woven web of thousands of decentralized actions.

02:23:50.360 --> 02:23:54.880
[Guest]: And if you suppress or control one thing, it's going to pop up in a different unintended

02:23:54.880 --> 02:24:02.520
[Guest]: consequence somewhere else. And we need to have a very detailed and nuanced understanding

02:24:02.520 --> 02:24:07.840
[Guest]: of the economy, before we just started throwing money from helicopters or giving fiscal stimulus

02:24:07.840 --> 02:24:12.800
[Guest]: and things like that. So one area where you know, I mean, I think Rathen and I would agree

02:24:12.800 --> 02:24:18.200
[Guest]: is we need to support people at the subsistence level, we need to make sure people are fed.

02:24:18.200 --> 02:24:24.080
[Guest]: But I do agree with Rathen that we need to be very careful about broader fiscal stimulus.

02:24:24.080 --> 02:24:29.040
[Guest]: It's not clear what money in the hands of people will do if there is an overall contraction

02:24:29.040 --> 02:24:33.400
[Guest]: of the economy because of the lockdown, both in terms of aggregate demand and aggregate

02:24:33.400 --> 02:24:39.840
[Guest]: supply, right? So that is something we don't have a handle on. We don't know what kind

02:24:39.840 --> 02:24:44.040
[Guest]: of contraction we're talking about. We don't know how long it will persist because at this

02:24:44.040 --> 02:24:49.080
[Guest]: point, no one knows how long this version of the lockdown will go on, and how the next

02:24:49.080 --> 02:24:54.800
[Guest]: opening up of the economy or, you know, easing the lockdown, what exactly it looks like.

02:24:54.800 --> 02:25:01.320
[Guest]: So we don't fully have a handle on what the overall economic contraction is. And in those

02:25:01.320 --> 02:25:06.440
[Guest]: circumstances, and just waving around, you know, well known tools and just printing more

02:25:06.440 --> 02:25:10.880
[Guest]: money and saying this is a war and we should just throw money in a war economy. It doesn't

02:25:10.880 --> 02:25:13.440
[Guest]: help anyone. So I do agree with him there.

02:25:13.440 --> 02:25:19.880
[Amit Varma]: Right, let's let's move on to, you've written a paper with Alex, where you talk about 10

02:25:19.880 --> 02:25:23.360
[Amit Varma]: solutions, what we can do going forward. And you've also spoken in conversations with me

02:25:23.360 --> 02:25:31.080
[Amit Varma]: about broad strokes policy solutions, how do we look at India specifically, moving forward,

02:25:31.080 --> 02:25:35.440
[Amit Varma]: you know, and I won't even say in a post COVID situation, because I think a post COVID situation,

02:25:35.440 --> 02:25:40.760
[Amit Varma]: frankly, is a long way away. This is an ongoing crisis that we are part of, it has, it has

02:25:40.760 --> 02:25:45.880
[Amit Varma]: changed our lives forever. I don't think most people realize the extent of the cultural

02:25:45.880 --> 02:25:51.280
[Amit Varma]: changes and the economic shift that is going to happen because of this. But what are your

02:25:51.280 --> 02:25:53.720
[Amit Varma]: sort of prescriptions going forward?

02:25:53.720 --> 02:25:58.360
[Guest]: Yeah, so this is actually prescriptions not even going forward. These are prescriptions

02:25:58.360 --> 02:26:06.520
[Guest]: for yesterday. Okay, so we wrote this last week. Alex and I, one of the themes that we

02:26:06.520 --> 02:26:12.080
[Guest]: have worked on before, and this is the paper on, you know, premature imitation, and state

02:26:12.080 --> 02:26:16.360
[Guest]: capacity in India and the flailing state, which, you know, we recorded a podcast with

02:26:16.360 --> 02:26:24.080
[Guest]: you. Our theme has generally been that it is problematic when developing countries just

02:26:24.080 --> 02:26:29.960
[Guest]: borrow solutions or best practices from the developed world. Because a lot of those best

02:26:29.960 --> 02:26:36.800
[Guest]: practices don't translate and they don't work very well in India. So, you know, the WHO

02:26:36.800 --> 02:26:41.880
[Guest]: and all the international organizations say, oh, the best thing that you can do right now

02:26:41.880 --> 02:26:48.080
[Guest]: is stay at home, don't meet anyone, wash your hands, you know, be safe and clean. Now we

02:26:48.080 --> 02:26:54.280
[Guest]: know in India, most people cannot follow that prescription. And the reason most people cannot

02:26:54.280 --> 02:27:01.000
[Guest]: follow that prescription, you know, two or three different reasons. Number one, the average

02:27:01.000 --> 02:27:08.040
[Guest]: living space in India per capita is relatively low, right? And this is particularly low in

02:27:08.040 --> 02:27:14.280
[Guest]: slums. So the average Indian, you know, per capita space, especially in urban areas, is

02:27:14.280 --> 02:27:21.960
[Guest]: about 127 square foot per person, right? That's really low. So it's small. In Mumbai, which

02:27:21.960 --> 02:27:29.400
[Guest]: is India's densest city, the average living space per capita is 48 square feet, right?

02:27:29.400 --> 02:27:34.680
[Guest]: And our friends at IDFC Institute kindly pointed out that 48 square feet is smaller than an

02:27:34.680 --> 02:27:41.120
[Guest]: American prison cell. So that is the kind of tight spaces in which we live. In slums,

02:27:41.120 --> 02:27:45.400
[Guest]: that number is close to 30 square feet, right? And then there are things like shifts that

02:27:45.400 --> 02:27:50.680
[Guest]: you talked about, which don't work in a lockdown. So we're talking about very low per capita

02:27:50.680 --> 02:27:55.400
[Guest]: living space in India, either because urban areas are extremely dense or rural households

02:27:55.400 --> 02:28:01.240
[Guest]: have more space, but the size of the household is much bigger. Second, we have intergenerational

02:28:01.240 --> 02:28:05.440
[Guest]: cohabitation. So, you know, there's the, you know, the joint family system in India where

02:28:05.440 --> 02:28:09.640
[Guest]: the grandparents, grandkids, parents, everyone lives together. So it's very difficult to

02:28:09.640 --> 02:28:16.120
[Guest]: social distance. Third is we don't have access to clean sanitation facilities. The worst

02:28:16.120 --> 02:28:21.560
[Guest]: example is Dharavi where, you know, four to 500 residents have access to a single toilet

02:28:21.560 --> 02:28:27.320
[Guest]: facility out of, you know, the million people living in Dharavi. But the better form of

02:28:27.320 --> 02:28:31.680
[Guest]: it is, you know, people who do have a restroom, it's not attached to the dwelling. When it's

02:28:31.680 --> 02:28:35.800
[Guest]: attached to the dwelling, you don't get clean piped water. When you get clean piped water,

02:28:35.800 --> 02:28:40.200
[Guest]: you don't have it for all day. You know, there are huge water shortages, especially in the

02:28:40.200 --> 02:28:45.400
[Guest]: summer, things like that. And because of these reasons, we cannot follow the simple, easy

02:28:45.400 --> 02:28:51.440
[Guest]: WHO prescription of wash your hands, stay at home, protect the elders. Right. So we

02:28:51.440 --> 02:28:58.680
[Guest]: need special policies for this, for India. So number one, one of the recommendations

02:28:58.680 --> 02:29:05.560
[Guest]: we gave was we need to repurpose existing government buildings into quarantine facilities

02:29:05.560 --> 02:29:10.160
[Guest]: because we need to actually extract people out of these dense circumstances and put them

02:29:10.160 --> 02:29:14.600
[Guest]: somewhere else. And we can't extract individuals. We need to extract the whole family because

02:29:14.600 --> 02:29:18.600
[Guest]: the Indian system doesn't allow for one person in the family to get quarantined separately.

02:29:18.600 --> 02:29:25.600
[Guest]: It just doesn't work. So one of our suggestions was right now all schools are closed. Right.

02:29:25.600 --> 02:29:31.200
[Guest]: And every single district has at least one public school, usually more. And they all

02:29:31.200 --> 02:29:36.360
[Guest]: have to have under the RT requirements, they must all have access to water. They must all

02:29:36.360 --> 02:29:41.560
[Guest]: have a restroom facility and they must all have a kitchen for the mid day meal. So these

02:29:41.560 --> 02:29:46.240
[Guest]: facilities can be very quickly repurposed into quarantine areas where we move entire

02:29:46.240 --> 02:29:51.360
[Guest]: families. And this is obviously a short term solution, but it's one of the few policies

02:29:51.360 --> 02:29:56.560
[Guest]: that we can actually implement because most Indians cannot follow the social distancing

02:29:56.560 --> 02:30:02.600
[Guest]: rules. Another example is, you know, this is very, it sounds very like Mary Antoinette,

02:30:02.600 --> 02:30:08.520
[Guest]: but if you can't give clean piped water, give hand sanitizer. Right. Normally in places

02:30:08.520 --> 02:30:13.320
[Guest]: like America, we're being told that, hey, hand sanitizer is the superior good. We are

02:30:13.320 --> 02:30:17.940
[Guest]: in extreme shortage. Soap and water work great. Please use soap and water in the absence of

02:30:17.940 --> 02:30:25.800
[Guest]: hand sanitizer. And I would flip it for India. In India, we need to increase the supply of

02:30:25.800 --> 02:30:32.280
[Guest]: hand sanitizer, especially in those, you know, one rupee sachets of two ml each. You know,

02:30:32.280 --> 02:30:37.040
[Guest]: those individualized, personalized hand sanitizers that you see everywhere in pharmacies normally

02:30:37.040 --> 02:30:41.480
[Guest]: right now, there's a huge shortage. And that is what we need to scale up and distribute

02:30:41.480 --> 02:30:48.480
[Guest]: across India, because in the absence of water, you use hand sanitizer. So India needs slightly

02:30:48.480 --> 02:30:55.000
[Guest]: different policy mechanisms to deal with this, you know, social distancing and isolation.

02:30:55.000 --> 02:30:59.000
[Guest]: So there are some of these things that the government can do. One interesting solution

02:30:59.000 --> 02:31:04.060
[Guest]: we gave was right now the hotel industry is down and out. Right. And I'm sure someone

02:31:04.060 --> 02:31:08.200
[Guest]: is going to start talking about stimulus and package for the hotel industry and the tourism

02:31:08.200 --> 02:31:15.560
[Guest]: industry. Our suggestion was let the government at a subsidized rate, rent private hotel rooms,

02:31:15.560 --> 02:31:19.880
[Guest]: you know, relatively low budget and repurpose them into quarantine facilities for, say,

02:31:19.880 --> 02:31:25.620
[Guest]: the next two to three months. And this can act as both a stimulus, but it can also get

02:31:25.620 --> 02:31:31.880
[Guest]: people out of these very dense situations. And it can use existing capacity, which which

02:31:31.880 --> 02:31:36.640
[Guest]: is there in the economy, which is currently debt capital, and it can quickly switch it

02:31:36.640 --> 02:31:43.160
[Guest]: around for something that is useful and productive during the crisis. Of course, we suggested

02:31:43.160 --> 02:31:47.920
[Guest]: that they rent private hospitals. They don't nationalize them. So I want to put that out.

02:31:47.920 --> 02:31:53.120
[Guest]: Again, another simple measure is to wear a mask. Right. The world has been flip flopping

02:31:53.120 --> 02:31:58.320
[Guest]: on that. First, experts said masks don't help. Then they said that, you know, using the Hong

02:31:58.320 --> 02:32:03.220
[Guest]: Kong and Taiwanese experience, the masks help a lot. So, you know, follow Asia and everyone

02:32:03.220 --> 02:32:06.920
[Guest]: should wear a mask. So a month ago in America, they said no one needs to wear a mask. And

02:32:06.920 --> 02:32:10.440
[Guest]: today, if you don't wear a mask, the police like literally beat you up, as you saw with

02:32:10.440 --> 02:32:16.440
[Guest]: the gentleman in Philadelphia. So, you know, in an ideal world, we would want these N95

02:32:16.440 --> 02:32:23.760
[Guest]: masks to be produced and scaled up. But even the regular masks, simple masks made at home

02:32:23.760 --> 02:32:28.840
[Guest]: work reasonably well. And, you know, suddenly all our tailors are out of work. And you and

02:32:28.840 --> 02:32:35.920
[Guest]: I have friends who, you know, using civil society mechanisms are working with handloom

02:32:35.920 --> 02:32:41.560
[Guest]: facilities and tailors to quickly scale up the production of masks and distribute them.

02:32:41.560 --> 02:32:47.000
[Guest]: This will both employ tailors and also give masks to the needy. And civil society is doing

02:32:47.000 --> 02:32:49.480
[Amit Varma]: this in a way that the government has not yet been able to.

02:32:49.480 --> 02:32:54.400
[Amit Varma]: In fact, on our last zoom call of a bunch of friends last weekend, you know, two of

02:32:54.400 --> 02:32:59.480
[Amit Varma]: our friends are personally in different cities actually working on these specific initiatives.

02:32:59.480 --> 02:33:00.480
[Guest]: So that's civil society.

02:33:00.480 --> 02:33:04.480
[Guest]: They're doing it at a big scale already. So and you know, we don't just need two, we need

02:33:04.480 --> 02:33:09.140
[Guest]: 2000 of our friends to do this. So it's, it's a wonderful initiative. But those are the

02:33:09.140 --> 02:33:13.040
[Guest]: kinds of things we need to think about in the state is finding it very hard to think

02:33:13.040 --> 02:33:17.540
[Guest]: about it. So we need to switch it up, you know, civil society can think of some things

02:33:17.540 --> 02:33:20.680
[Guest]: and the state can maybe fund all this.

02:33:20.680 --> 02:33:26.240
[Guest]: Another was just removing regulatory roadblocks. And, you know, I mean, you and I have had

02:33:26.240 --> 02:33:30.700
[Guest]: hundreds of conversations over the last decade on the kinds of regulatory roadblocks that

02:33:30.700 --> 02:33:36.600
[Guest]: exist in India, but one of them is just approvals, right? So the state has tight controls on

02:33:36.600 --> 02:33:44.040
[Guest]: all kinds of approvals. So for instance, they remove the import duties on testing, but the

02:33:44.040 --> 02:33:49.680
[Guest]: Institute of virology needs to approve any test kit before it is deployed. And the drug

02:33:49.680 --> 02:33:55.760
[Guest]: controller needs to approve any important test kit before it can be deployed, right?

02:33:55.760 --> 02:34:02.160
[Guest]: And most firms have one or the other, they either have the license from the drug controller

02:34:02.160 --> 02:34:06.280
[Guest]: or they have the approval from the Institute of virology, they don't have both. So one

02:34:06.280 --> 02:34:11.200
[Guest]: of our suggestions was any test kit that's been approved in China, Japan, Singapore,

02:34:11.200 --> 02:34:15.600
[Guest]: United States, South Korea, Japan, Western Europe, just approve it in India already,

02:34:15.600 --> 02:34:20.000
[Guest]: right? There are countries with far better state capacity with far better regulatory

02:34:20.000 --> 02:34:24.360
[Guest]: capacity, which have looked into these and which have approved them. There are Indian

02:34:24.360 --> 02:34:28.680
[Guest]: firms which are exporting to these countries, but cannot sell in India because their approvals

02:34:28.680 --> 02:34:34.320
[Guest]: are stuck. The Financial Times did a great piece on that. So we need to remove regulatory

02:34:34.320 --> 02:34:39.640
[Guest]: roadblocks very quickly. And I would say there's a great time to piggyback on state capacity

02:34:39.640 --> 02:34:44.600
[Guest]: of other countries. Tying in with this is removing import tariffs on medical equipment.

02:34:44.600 --> 02:34:49.040
[Guest]: Of course, you and I think we should remove import tariffs on everything, but the urgent

02:34:49.040 --> 02:34:56.720
[Guest]: need is medical equipment. And we talked about private Indian labs running tests for which

02:34:56.720 --> 02:35:01.240
[Guest]: the government can reimburse at least to cover costs, even if they don't cover the profits.

02:35:01.240 --> 02:35:04.840
[Guest]: So these are the sorts of recommendations that we made, which are very specific to the

02:35:04.840 --> 02:35:10.480
[Guest]: Indian system. Another important tool is mobile phones. And now you and I have spoken about

02:35:10.480 --> 02:35:17.320
[Guest]: this in the past on how the mobile phone revolution in India helped India skip an entire stage

02:35:17.320 --> 02:35:21.960
[Guest]: of development. You and I come from a generation where we remember that you had to wait for

02:35:21.960 --> 02:35:28.600
[Guest]: four or five years to get an MTNL telephone line, right? And the moment they liberalized

02:35:28.600 --> 02:35:33.560
[Guest]: the telecom sector, you could get, you know, landlines much easier. And then when the mobile

02:35:33.560 --> 02:35:39.440
[Guest]: phone revolution came, hundreds of millions of Indians just completely bypassed the landline

02:35:39.440 --> 02:35:44.600
[Guest]: stage and went straight to mobile phones. Now, as a consequence, an incredible thing

02:35:44.600 --> 02:35:50.200
[Guest]: that's happened in India is two thirds of Indians either have their own mobile phone

02:35:50.200 --> 02:35:55.260
[Guest]: or have access to a mobile phone within the household. And about a quarter of Indians

02:35:55.260 --> 02:36:01.400
[Guest]: have smartphones with data, right? Now, this can be deployed in a big way when we are talking

02:36:01.400 --> 02:36:07.480
[Guest]: about testing and tracing. Now, I'd like this to be done as much on a voluntary basis as

02:36:07.480 --> 02:36:13.120
[Guest]: possible with as little state coercion. But I think there is some element of state coercion

02:36:13.120 --> 02:36:17.600
[Guest]: when it comes to contact tracing and taking down people's, you know, travel histories

02:36:17.600 --> 02:36:22.160
[Guest]: and personal histories. So you can use mobile phones. For instance, I know a couple of people

02:36:22.160 --> 02:36:26.520
[Guest]: who are already doing this, and these are private ventures. They are not hoping to make

02:36:26.520 --> 02:36:31.840
[Guest]: any money. In fact, one of the people I know who's doing this, young boy, 17 years old

02:36:31.840 --> 02:36:38.400
[Guest]: called Sohail Mohammed. He's an Emergent Ventures winner. And he created a diagnostic app in

02:36:38.400 --> 02:36:44.480
[Guest]: Kannada and English initially because he's a resident of Mysore. And you just take the

02:36:44.480 --> 02:36:48.720
[Guest]: test and it tells you, you know, you put in all your symptoms and it tells you whether

02:36:48.720 --> 02:36:54.240
[Guest]: you're at a high or a low risk of COVID and whether you should isolate and you should,

02:36:54.240 --> 02:37:00.520
[Guest]: you know, go look for a test or something like that. Now, it has two benefits. One,

02:37:00.520 --> 02:37:06.560
[Guest]: it provides information to people and provides information in local languages to an easy

02:37:06.560 --> 02:37:11.320
[Guest]: instrument that people can use and people can sort of use their phone and they can follow.

02:37:11.320 --> 02:37:16.460
[Guest]: The other is if you take permission of these people, and I'm not, I don't know exactly

02:37:16.460 --> 02:37:23.160
[Guest]: the technical details of his particular app. But if you take the permission of people and

02:37:23.160 --> 02:37:29.200
[Guest]: say, can we use your location data, not individualized, but anonymized, then depending on how many

02:37:29.200 --> 02:37:34.000
[Guest]: people in a particular district have taken a particular diagnostic test, you can figure

02:37:34.000 --> 02:37:40.000
[Guest]: out even before an outbreak in the community on whether that is a hotspot displaying certain

02:37:40.000 --> 02:37:45.560
[Guest]: symptoms in large numbers, right? So mobile phones can be deployed in a very interesting

02:37:45.560 --> 02:37:51.080
[Guest]: way. Mobile phones were deployed in Vietnam. The government introduced its own app and

02:37:51.080 --> 02:37:57.080
[Guest]: two thirds of Vietnamese people have access to the internet and to mobile phones and through

02:37:57.080 --> 02:38:03.840
[Guest]: Facebook and a number of, you know, local initiatives, they had a huge public outreach

02:38:03.840 --> 02:38:09.240
[Guest]: explaining what is the meaning of the coronavirus epidemic, how does it spread, how people can

02:38:09.240 --> 02:38:14.360
[Guest]: be asymptomatic, but still infect other people and what kind of precautions should be taken.

02:38:14.360 --> 02:38:19.880
[Guest]: And they incentivize people to give information on a voluntary basis, right? And those sorts

02:38:19.880 --> 02:38:25.240
[Guest]: of things are extremely important, especially given that we are not able to test on a large

02:38:25.240 --> 02:38:29.960
[Guest]: scale. So mobile phones can be used to screen. So one of our suggestions was it would be

02:38:29.960 --> 02:38:35.320
[Guest]: great if we can keep mobile phone accounts alive and allow mobile phone companies to

02:38:35.320 --> 02:38:41.960
[Guest]: use the 2% CSR that they are supposed to spend, you know, mandated by law towards helping

02:38:41.960 --> 02:38:46.160
[Guest]: people in distress to keep their mobile phones switched on, because that's a great way of

02:38:46.160 --> 02:38:50.800
[Guest]: reaching information to people and also collecting information from people. So we just came up

02:38:50.800 --> 02:38:55.280
[Guest]: with, you know, a list of 10 recommendations. This is in no way an exhaustive list, but

02:38:55.280 --> 02:39:00.440
[Guest]: it's just a basic list of things that are very India specific and very developing country

02:39:00.440 --> 02:39:06.360
[Guest]: specific that need to be accounted for when you're thinking of, you know, COVID policy

02:39:06.360 --> 02:39:07.360
[Guest]: during a lockdown.

02:39:07.360 --> 02:39:11.480
[Amit Varma]: And it'll be linked from the show notes, obviously. I mean, a couple of, I mean, the related worry

02:39:11.480 --> 02:39:17.680
[Amit Varma]: I have is that, of course, you know, the seductions of technology can often lead us to, even at

02:39:17.680 --> 02:39:22.600
[Amit Varma]: a voluntary basis, sign away freedoms without being aware of what could lie down the road

02:39:22.600 --> 02:39:26.840
[Amit Varma]: in a different time. And that's really the only thing that I worry about as far as privacy

02:39:26.840 --> 02:39:33.240
[Amit Varma]: is concerned. And I'm with you on that. And I'm also a little worried about and I mean,

02:39:33.240 --> 02:39:37.320
[Amit Varma]: I could actually frame it as a question to you, that, you know, it is also seductive

02:39:37.320 --> 02:39:43.480
[Amit Varma]: to be able to use all the tools of your trade and then adopt an engineering mindset. Like

02:39:43.480 --> 02:39:47.520
[Amit Varma]: I think the greatest danger to India, frankly, is the engineering mindset where you try to

02:39:47.520 --> 02:39:53.240
[Amit Varma]: fix everything from the top down and design things. And, you know, or the man of system

02:39:53.240 --> 02:39:58.640
[Amit Varma]: as, or the woman of system, as Adam Smith would have said, if he was women would never

02:39:58.640 --> 02:40:05.400
[Amit Varma]: do such a thing, would never do such a thing. So that's a joke, people. The person of system,

02:40:05.400 --> 02:40:10.320
[Amit Varma]: how do you watch out for that tendency in yourself? Because very often, you have a lot

02:40:10.320 --> 02:40:15.680
[Amit Varma]: of intricate knowledge about how a system works. You also know at a broader level that

02:40:15.680 --> 02:40:19.840
[Amit Varma]: look, this is spontaneous order, I can't control all of this. I can't design all of this, I

02:40:19.840 --> 02:40:24.320
[Amit Varma]: must not fall for the fatal conceit. But there is also then that confidence. And if I may

02:40:24.320 --> 02:40:30.440
[Amit Varma]: say it, perhaps sometimes that arrogance of that intricate knowledge. So how do you watch

02:40:30.440 --> 02:40:36.520
[Guest]: out for your tendency in yourself? So one excellent thing for me personally, is that

02:40:36.520 --> 02:40:43.000
[Guest]: I have zero power and influence on any policies actually being implemented. So that is the

02:40:43.000 --> 02:40:49.400
[Guest]: greatest check on any hubris or arrogance I may have. I can write purely from a point

02:40:49.400 --> 02:40:54.720
[Guest]: of view of educating myself and educating other people. And thinking through the economic

02:40:54.720 --> 02:41:00.560
[Guest]: logic and incentives of a particular situation. Knowing full well that I have very little

02:41:00.560 --> 02:41:06.480
[Guest]: influence or control over policy. So that's a great check, you know, on my humility overall.

02:41:06.480 --> 02:41:13.240
[Guest]: Another is, like I said, I always veer towards voluntary action as opposed to coercive action.

02:41:13.240 --> 02:41:18.920
[Guest]: Because that is an ideological preference and a personal preference of mine.

02:41:18.920 --> 02:41:20.960
[Guest]: I would say it's a moral preference.

02:41:20.960 --> 02:41:25.560
[Guest]: It's a moral preference, but it's also something I don't know if I ever cultivated it or if

02:41:25.560 --> 02:41:32.220
[Guest]: I was just always like this. So it's not like I'm trying to be like this. I just fundamentally

02:41:32.220 --> 02:41:38.480
[Guest]: have a preference towards very low coercion as far as possible to avoid it and as far

02:41:38.480 --> 02:41:43.640
[Guest]: as possible rely on voluntary arrangements. So, you know, that also helps me a little

02:41:43.640 --> 02:41:47.760
[Guest]: bit. When it comes to the stuff like, you know, we're recommending mobile testing and

02:41:47.760 --> 02:41:54.120
[Guest]: things like that, I would say the third aspect is my two checks are always it needs to be

02:41:54.120 --> 02:41:59.640
[Guest]: incentive aligned and it needs to tap into as much local information as possible. Right?

02:41:59.640 --> 02:42:06.000
[Guest]: So this mobile phone testing, while it seems like an engineering tech solution, it is really

02:42:06.000 --> 02:42:13.480
[Guest]: the success or failure of it depends on bottom up information coming from various decentralized

02:42:13.480 --> 02:42:18.080
[Guest]: actors. And if people are not willing to participate in this, then the whole thing, you know, you

02:42:18.080 --> 02:42:22.520
[Guest]: can have as many mobile phones as you want. It's not going to do anything. Right. And

02:42:22.520 --> 02:42:29.640
[Guest]: the man of system government thing has to do nothing short of 100% invasive surveillance

02:42:29.640 --> 02:42:34.940
[Guest]: to substitute for that decentralized information to get any traction to, you know, instead

02:42:34.940 --> 02:42:43.080
[Guest]: of testing. So these are some of the checks that are in place. I'm not claiming that I

02:42:43.080 --> 02:42:49.200
[Guest]: get any of it right all the time. But I think just having a huge preference towards voluntary

02:42:49.200 --> 02:42:57.840
[Guest]: action keeps my power hungry side in check. Not that that side is being fed at all. I

02:42:57.840 --> 02:43:02.080
[Guest]: don't even have power when it comes to my dog in my house. So, you know, that's kind

02:43:02.080 --> 02:43:06.600
[Guest]: of my status on the totem pole. So I think that's usually what keeps me in check. But

02:43:06.600 --> 02:43:12.680
[Guest]: I think it's very important to worry about certain things. I think reading history helps,

02:43:12.680 --> 02:43:17.400
[Guest]: you know, thinking about what happens when we cede a lot of power to the government during

02:43:17.400 --> 02:43:23.880
[Guest]: war or during other emergencies. That helps a lot. Understanding the kinds of things that

02:43:23.880 --> 02:43:27.920
[Guest]: you have talked about, which is, you know, there is a lot of inertia in government and

02:43:27.920 --> 02:43:33.080
[Guest]: anytime we roll out a new government program, it's very difficult to roll it back. So what

02:43:33.080 --> 02:43:40.120
[Guest]: kinds of ways do we, you know, what are the methods we use to make sure that temporary

02:43:40.120 --> 02:43:45.360
[Guest]: relief or temporary use of draconian power do not persist in the long term? And these

02:43:45.360 --> 02:43:48.920
[Guest]: are just lessons. It's not like I knew this all along. It's just something you learn from

02:43:48.920 --> 02:43:54.200
[Guest]: reading a lot of history. So I think just reading the kinds of things I have read, you

02:43:54.200 --> 02:43:59.680
[Guest]: know, over a period of time, which is world history, lessons from Indian political economy,

02:43:59.680 --> 02:44:05.520
[Guest]: the kinds of draconian measures Indira Gandhi took during the emergency, whether it is forced

02:44:05.520 --> 02:44:10.800
[Guest]: sterilization, slum demolition. These are just lessons for us that we must just never

02:44:10.800 --> 02:44:17.680
[Guest]: forget. So I guess having a good memory on things that happened long before I was born

02:44:17.680 --> 02:44:22.400
[Guest]: and thinking about them constantly helps, too. So those are some of the checks. But

02:44:22.400 --> 02:44:29.120
[Guest]: I don't think any of us, you know, only people who believe no action should be taken in any

02:44:29.120 --> 02:44:34.040
[Guest]: circumstance can be completely protected from, you know, veering into engineering mindset

02:44:34.040 --> 02:44:38.480
[Amit Varma]: from time to time. Fair enough. That's a good point. And you know, what do you say about

02:44:38.480 --> 02:44:43.160
[Amit Varma]: learning from history? Well, look, Indians, firstly, do not learn from history. And secondly,

02:44:43.160 --> 02:44:48.440
[Amit Varma]: they don't read history. And secondly, we use the tools of WhatsApp University to manufacture

02:44:48.440 --> 02:44:53.080
[Amit Varma]: our own history according to the lessons we want to learn. These are dark and depressing

02:44:53.080 --> 02:44:58.400
[Amit Varma]: times for more reasons than just COVID-19. And, you know, on this, I have to say, I'm

02:44:58.400 --> 02:45:03.320
[Guest]: going to throw the Indian elite under the bus because they have been one of the greatest

02:45:03.320 --> 02:45:09.200
[Guest]: disappointments for me in recent times. We were talking about all the areas in India

02:45:09.200 --> 02:45:15.480
[Guest]: which are rendered invisible. A lot of it is because Indian elite just carry on business

02:45:15.480 --> 02:45:22.000
[Guest]: as usual and don't apply themselves and their influence enough. So one huge area is how

02:45:22.000 --> 02:45:26.840
[Guest]: we treat essential workers. So, you know, we want our cities to be clean. We want our

02:45:26.840 --> 02:45:30.920
[Guest]: bathrooms to be clean. We want the sewage system to be cleared. We want the garbage

02:45:30.920 --> 02:45:36.800
[Guest]: to be picked up. But we never acknowledge who are the people who are actually doing

02:45:36.800 --> 02:45:42.760
[Guest]: this work. Even right now, everyone is clapping for people who are doctors and nurses who

02:45:42.760 --> 02:45:47.680
[Guest]: are still people of relatively privileged positions. But you and I have discussed this

02:45:47.680 --> 02:45:54.320
[Guest]: before a disproportionate percentage of our health and sanitation workers, especially

02:45:54.320 --> 02:45:59.480
[Guest]: the sanitation workers, are Dalits. And there is zero acknowledgement for them. There is

02:45:59.480 --> 02:46:03.480
[Guest]: zero increase in their pay. We don't believe in paying them overtime because they're working

02:46:03.480 --> 02:46:09.200
[Guest]: overtime right now. They're not acknowledged as an essential service. We've read reports

02:46:09.200 --> 02:46:13.680
[Guest]: of, you know, Dalit sanitation workers going to work who get beaten up on their way to

02:46:13.680 --> 02:46:20.440
[Guest]: work. We simply don't treat people well. Right. So same thing with slum dwellers. We've created

02:46:20.440 --> 02:46:25.840
[Guest]: a slum problem because of the nimbyism of the elites. Right. Even in Mumbai, routinely

02:46:25.840 --> 02:46:31.240
[Guest]: people will say, but you know, if we increase the FSI, there's going to be too much overcrowding

02:46:31.240 --> 02:46:36.080
[Guest]: and we won't get enough water and parking. And in the process, you know, we limit the

02:46:36.080 --> 02:46:42.120
[Guest]: FSI and we get slums. And every single one of these elites there, the bhai who comes

02:46:42.120 --> 02:46:46.760
[Guest]: to work in the house to clean it, or the garbage man who comes to pick things up, or the auto

02:46:46.760 --> 02:46:50.280
[Guest]: rickshaw driver who takes them everywhere, they all live in these slums. You know, the

02:46:50.280 --> 02:46:55.600
[Guest]: taxi driver Kumar spoke to is living in slums and shifts. And we just look the other way

02:46:55.600 --> 02:47:02.000
[Guest]: making these people and their problems invisible. So in that sense, I think the elites right

02:47:02.000 --> 02:47:06.960
[Guest]: now for the first time, we're talking about Indian husbands, chopping vegetables at home.

02:47:06.960 --> 02:47:10.360
[Guest]: There's a whole thing on TikTok and Instagram on, you know, how people's rotis are getting

02:47:10.360 --> 02:47:16.960
[Guest]: burned and they don't know how to cook. It's simply because we never paid any acknowledgement

02:47:16.960 --> 02:47:21.880
[Guest]: to essential workers who do the bulk of the unpleasant jobs in our society. And we've

02:47:21.880 --> 02:47:26.640
[Guest]: never created mechanisms to support them. We've rendered them invisible. And now we're

02:47:26.640 --> 02:47:30.320
[Guest]: like, Oh, how do I manage without a bhai? You know, how do we manage without the garbage

02:47:30.320 --> 02:47:35.760
[Guest]: getting picked up or the milkman, you know, delivering milk. So the Indian elite really

02:47:35.760 --> 02:47:40.920
[Guest]: need to step it up. Okay. And routinely we have the Indian elite who, you know, I've

02:47:40.920 --> 02:47:45.200
[Guest]: been watching this on Twitter all the time. As you know, the first super spreader event

02:47:45.200 --> 02:47:51.040
[Guest]: just happened to be a Muslim congregation. It could have been anybody, right? This was

02:47:51.040 --> 02:47:55.040
[Guest]: a pure chance, according to me, you know, in, in the timeline of things, but it was

02:47:55.040 --> 02:47:59.880
[Guest]: a super spreader event. And now suddenly we have Indian elites just outraging against

02:47:59.880 --> 02:48:06.400
[Guest]: Muslims on Twitter, as if Corona virus is a Muslim created problem. And, you know, like

02:48:06.400 --> 02:48:11.320
[Guest]: telling the government that the policeman to use as draconian measures as possible,

02:48:11.320 --> 02:48:14.600
[Guest]: saying things like, we need to beat them up. We need to put them in prison. We need to

02:48:14.600 --> 02:48:21.840
[Guest]: isolate them, you know? So it's like the Indian elite is a little too comfortable giving up

02:48:21.840 --> 02:48:25.520
[Guest]: more and more part of the government because they're very comfortable in the knowledge

02:48:25.520 --> 02:48:31.600
[Guest]: that the abuse of that power is always only against people who are already marginalized.

02:48:31.600 --> 02:48:35.520
[Guest]: And for this, you know, the Indian elite has to just be blamed and thrown out of the bus,

02:48:35.520 --> 02:48:42.200
[Guest]: especially the middle class. So I have suddenly in this COVID crisis, a very bad taste in,

02:48:42.200 --> 02:48:46.440
[Guest]: in my mouth because of everything I read, written by them on Twitter and TikTok and

02:48:46.440 --> 02:48:49.160
[Guest]: places like that. I don't know what your thought is on this.

02:48:49.160 --> 02:48:52.800
[Amit Varma]: No, I agree with you entirely. These are very wise and sad thoughts, though. I'd say that

02:48:52.800 --> 02:48:57.880
[Guest]: it's a rant, but we'll turn them into wise and sad thoughts. That's what we do in podcast

02:48:57.880 --> 02:49:03.120
[Amit Varma]: rant on any other medium is a wise thought on a podcast. So I will say one thing about

02:49:03.120 --> 02:49:06.600
[Amit Varma]: TikTok that I've actually watched thousands of TikTok videos over the last few days. And

02:49:06.600 --> 02:49:12.240
[Amit Varma]: I think got a better, much better sense of my society from it. And there is not only

02:49:12.240 --> 02:49:17.360
[Amit Varma]: cause for despair, but some cause for hope. And I'll end on the note that I actually,

02:49:17.360 --> 02:49:22.680
[Amit Varma]: you know, listening to your words, I thought to myself that I wish Indian society was a

02:49:22.680 --> 02:49:29.280
[Amit Varma]: little bit more like the coronavirus, because the coronavirus does not discriminate. Shruti,

02:49:29.280 --> 02:49:30.840
[Amit Varma]: thank you so much for coming on the show.

02:49:30.840 --> 02:49:35.200
[Guest]: Thanks so much for having me, Amit. It was really nice chatting with you. I mean, normally

02:49:35.200 --> 02:49:40.840
[Guest]: we do this face to face after you fed me a lovely Bengali meal at OCalcutta across the

02:49:40.840 --> 02:49:45.960
[Guest]: street from your studio where we used to record. But in these times when I don't know when

02:49:45.960 --> 02:49:50.640
[Guest]: I'll see you next, it is just really nice to be still be able to talk to you.

